a new jersey congressman says ``something just doesn't smell right'' about a federal banking agency's request for an fbi check of one of its critics
the request to the fbi from a federal home loan bank board official ``smacks of a way of life that seems to be more appropriate to life in latin america than it does in the united states,'' rep. james florio, d-n.j., said friday
the fbi check was revealed by an internal bank board investigation requested by florio, chairman of the house energy and commerce consumer protection subcommittee
the report, by bank board inspector general paul gibbons, disclosed that the office of rosemary stewart, bank board enforcement director, asked the fbi on aug. 17 to check on william juliano, a mount laurel, n.j., developer
the fbi returned the request, which listed only juliano's name and address, stamped ``insufficient information,'' and ms. stewart decided not to pursue the matter
because of juliano's criticism, florio had asked for an investigation of the federal asset disposition association, the arm of the bank board that manages and sells real estate from bankrupt savings and loans
fada was under attack from juliano, other business people and members of congress for reported mismanagement and conflicts of interest
juliano had threatened to bring a class action lawsuit against fada on behalf of disgruntled developers who believed they had been poorly treated by the agency
ms. stewart told investigators she was asked in june to obtain the fbi check from fada general counsel robert j. axley, who said juliano had made verbal threats and written nasty letters to then fada president rosyln payne
axley told the investigators that ms. payne asked him to ``have juliano checked out'' after she received anonymous telephone calls in the middle of the night to her unlisted home telephone
axley said he subsequently received a tip that juliano had ties to organized crime. however, the bank board report said the tip referred to someone with a different first name than juliano's
after her request to the fbi was returned, ms. stewart said she learned more about the nature of juliano's dispute with fada, consulted her superiors at the bank board and decided it was not appropriate for her to resubmit the query to the fbi
but florio said, ``for the bank board to even contemplate investigating a citizen for complaining raises a lot of questions. ... something just doesn't smell right here.''
ms. stewart did not immediately return telephone messages left at her office friday afternoon. there was no answer at juliano's office
karl hoyle, a bank board spokesman, said the agency acknowledges that the request to the fbi should never have been made
once we were aware of it, we indicated we didn't want that pursued and after that it was not,'' he said. ``rosemary, to her credit, said `maybe we're not supposed to be doing that sort of thing.'''
the bank board has also acknowledged that a law firm hired by fada engaged a private detective agency to look into juliano's finances
fbi spokesman william carter said the fbi would not consider it proper to investigate a government critic. the bureau's practice, he said, is to ask for more information about the reason a background check is requested and if the explanation is not appropriate it can recommend administrative or disciplinary actions against the person who made the request
hoyle said ms. stewart has not been reprimanded
horseradish eaten during traditional passover dinners can pose a health hazard, says a jewish doctor whose father collapsed after consuming an olive-sized serving of the bitter herb
dr. haya r. rubin said friday that her father, cleveland state university sociologist israel rubin, quickly recovered after he fainted, keeled over and suffered a small seizure during a seder, or traditional passover meal, several years ago
she said the incident shows that people prone to high blood pressure, heart or artery disease or stroke might be better off if they let horseradish fumes evaporate by keeping it uncovered for a half hour before the seder, or use a substitute such as chopped romaine lettuce stalks
rubin suffered high blood pressure before the incident, said his daughter, an internist at the university of california, los angeles, and consultant to the rand corp
the passover holiday, which celebrates the israelites' exodus from slavery in ancient egypt, extends from friday night until sundown april 9. seders are held on the first two nights. horseradish is eaten during the ceremonial meal as a ``bitter herb'' symbolizing the bitterness of slavery
a letter warning that horseradish can be dangerous was published friday in the journal of the american medical association by ms. rubin and dr. albert w. wu, a clinical instructor at the university of california, san diego
wu said the horseradish-induced sudden loss of blood pressure that caused rubin to faint and collapse could trigger a fatal stroke, heart attack or abnormal heart rhythm in people with heart disease
wu and ms. rubin trained together at mount sinai medical center in new york. they decided to write the letter after wu spotted a letter about a similar incident published in the same journal in january
in that letter, dr. daniel e. spitzer of montefiore hospital in new york told how a healthy 63-year-old man collapsed after eating a large mound of wasabi, or green-colored japanese horseradish, during a meal of sushi
spitzer's letter was headlined: ``horseradish horrors: sushi syncope.'' syncope means fainting. the follow-up letter by ms. rubin and wu carried the headline ``the bitter herbs of seder: more on horseradish horrors.''
ms. rubin said horseradish usually is grated. but the night her father collapsed, the family ground it in a food processor, then placed it in an airtight container, preventing vapors from escaping and making the horseradish unusually potent
wu said the collapse probably occurred because the horseradish vapors caused a reflexive drop in blood pressure. coupled with the elder rubin's consumption of passover wine and use of medicine to reduce his high blood pressure, that briefly deprived the brain of enough blood
he still eats horseradish,'' ms. rubin said. ``my dad is sort of macho.''
about 400 people huffed and puffed friday at the 17th annual hash bash, a spring rally for the legalization of marijuana
police made no arrests and issued no citations during the event on the university of michigan campus. university officials had issued a permit for the event but emphasized they were not endorsing it
possession of small amounts of marijuana in ann arbor is punishable by a $5 fine
i've been coming to this since i was a little boy,'' said a 29-year-old who called himself jizmo noodles and was one of the first to light up. ``my first one was in 1973. it's a means of expression, civil disobedience.''
noodles, carrying incense and wearing jeans, a t-shirt and a denim vest with a peace sign, described himself as a ``student of life.''
jon gettman, assistant director of the national organization for the reform of marijuana laws, or norml, told the gathering that pot smokers were tired of being labeled criminals
we're here for a lot of different reasons today,'' he said. ``a lot of people think that because this is april fools' day, that this is some some kind of a joke. we are serious, very serious.''
norml wants marijuana legalized, with taxes on it used to develop treatment centers for cocaine and heroin users
mark amicone, sophomore history major, said he started smoking marijuana at 16. ``i got a late start,'' he said
american corporations that owe taxes to panama will be allowed the u.s. foreign tax credit if payments are made to the government of ousted president eric arturo delvalle, the internal revenue service says
friday's announcement was aimed at discouraging u.s. businesses from sending tax payments to the panamanian government controlled by military strongman manuel antonio noriega, which washington does not recognize
some large u.s.-based multinational firms recently made quarterly tax payments just in time to give that government a desperately needed infusion of cash
the foreign tax credit is designed to prevent two national governments from taxing the same dollar of income. in general, the united states will not tax income that an american corporation earns in and pays taxes on to a foreign country

washington (ap) _ the general accounting office recommends mandatory inspection of all nuclear power plants for pipe deterioration following findings that nearly one-third of the nation's commercial reactors already have such a problem
the congressional watchdog agency deemed the industry-wide inspections necessary after reviewing actions taken by the nuclear regulatory commission and the utilities themselves since a pipe rupture at the surry unit 2 plant in virginia killed four workers in late 1986
rep. edward j. markey, d-mass., who released the gao report, declared that the nrc's ``failure to act aggressively on this matter is astounding.''
after the surry accident, the nrc did develop evidence of widespread pipe deterioration at the trojan nuclear plant in oregon, and as of jan. 21 this year the commission had identified a total of 34 plants with at least some pipe damage caused by erosion or corrosion
in defense of the nrc's approach, robert newlin, a commission spokesman, said the commission had sent out ``several notices'' to the industry asking them to inspect their own plants and report back

washington (ap) _ taking advantage of an appeals court ruling earlier this week, the army has ordered a resumption of random drug testing of civilian employees in certain critical jobs
the directive went out today,'' paige eversole, an army spokeswoman at the pentagon, said friday. ``it orders resumption of the program effective immediately.''
the move had been expected since tuesday, when a federal appeals court struck down a preliminary injunction that had stopped the drug-testing program a month ago
a three-judge panel of the u.s. circuit court of appeals said it was staying the injunction granted to employee unions while it considered the legal merits of the case

washington (ap) _ the veterans administration is raising its maximum interest rate for federally backed va home mortgages by one-half percentage point to 10 percent
the va said it was making the change, which will take effect sunday, to reflect recent increases in interest rates in financial markets
in the past 12 months, the va rate has been changed seven times, fluctuating between 9.5 percent and 11 percent. the last change was feb. 1, when the rate was lowered a full percentage point from 10.5 percent to 9.5 percent
the federal home loan mortgage corp. said friday that the national average for 30-year conventional mortgages, those without government guarantees, rose above 10 percent for the first time since late january. the national average rate was 10.05 percent, up from 9.99 percent the previous week

washington (ap) _ the air force has rewritten its contracts covering development of the new midgetman mobile nuclear missile, canceling almost $1 billion worth of work planned by six contractors
the service, in a brief statement, stressed it could not speak for the six contractors involved but estimated the cutbacks could affect the jobs of as many as 2,300 private-sector employees
the air force action became inevitable several months ago when defense secretary frank c. carlucci decided the pentagon could not afford to develop and deploy the single-warhead midgetman within the budget levels set by the white house and congress
the air force had recommended carlucci kill the program outright, but the defense secretary decided to request $200 million in fiscal 1989 to keep the program alive pending a final decision by the next president

washington (ap) _ the food and drug administration is warning consumers not to use nutrien and vitalite powdered drink mixes because they may be contaminated with salmonella bacteria
both products are nutritional supplements marketed as powdered drink mixes by sunrider international of torrance, calif., and marketed nationally through more than 37,000 independent distributors, generally individuals who sell them door-to-door or to friends
the fda reported there have been at least seven cases of illness associated with the products
it said sunrider has agreed to begin a nationwide recall, but has not supplied the agency with specific distribution information. honasan were his guards. picks up 3rd graf, `chief of ...</note>
the leader of the august coup attempt that almost toppled the government of president corazon aquino escaped saturday from his prison ship in manila bay, the military announced
a statement said former lt. col. gregorio ``gringo'' honasan fled at about 2:30 a.m. saturday (1:30 p.m. est friday) aboard two rubber boats along with 13 of his guards
chief of staff gen. renato de villa ordered a massive search for the 39-year-old honasan and alerted subordinate commands nationwide to be on the lookout for him
the charismatic former lieutenant colonel had been detained on the navy ship since his arrest last december in a manila suburb
col. oscar florendo, chief military spokesman, said a reserve lieutenant who was frustrated over his inability to obtain a regular commission had aided in the getaway
florendo said the boats used in the escape had been sent to increase security after the military learned of a plot to free honasan
de villa immediately relieved the commander of the vessel, the rps andres bonifacio, and ordered his arrest, florendo said in a radio address. he appealed to the public to provide information to help recapture honasan
honasan, former chief of security at the defense ministry, played a key role in the feb. 22, 1986, mutiny which triggered the popular uprising that toppled president ferdinand marcos
but honasan became disillusioned with marcos' successor, president corazon aquino, accusing her of ``weak and inept'' leadership that fortified the 18-year-old communist insurgency
on aug. 28, honasan led a force of 2,000 men who attacked the presidential palace and seized several media and military installations in the capital before they were driven off by pro-aquino forces
the coup attempt left 53 people dead and wounded hundreds, and mrs. aquino said it was aimed at killing her and her family
honasan's effort was the most serious of several major plots to unseat mrs. aquino's government
military sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the former colonel was so popular that he had become the ``dominant figure'' aboard the ship which was supposed to be his prison
it is with sadness that the afp (armed forces of the philippines) makes public the unfortunate escape from custody of ex-col. gregorio honasan from his detention,'' florendo said in a statement. ``during a normal inspection of the ship, it was discovered that subject detainee together with his guards headed by lt. j.g. gerardo mojica and 12 enlisted personnel were found missing
initial investigation revealed that honasan was apparently assisted and joined by his guards led by lt j.g. mojica ... it is believed that bribery was a factor that led to the betrayal of their oath and sworn duty.''
florendo said de villa had alerted the military to take precautions to ensure that communist rebels did not take advantage of the confusion to launch ``terroristic actions.''
the spokesman said troops were being deployed around manila to search for honasan
florendo said the military received information a week ago that honasan would try to escape and it sent rubber boats to guard the ship
he said the military expected outsiders to try to storm the vessel but ``instead it came from the inside.''
honasan was security chief of the defense ministry when opposition sen. juan ponce enrile was minister of national defense. enrile was fired in november 1986 after the government said it thwarted a coup attempt by his followers
honasan remained in hiding for months after the august coup. brig. gen. ramon montano, commander of the national capital regional defense command, said weeks before the arrest that honasan was being protected by undisclosed civilian and military figures
the nikkei stock average closed at 26,282.12 points, up 177.90 points, on the tokyo stock exchange saturday
douglas edwards, one of the ``founding fathers'' of broadcast journalism, signed off after more than four decades on the air by thanking his coworkers and his viewers during his last tv appearance for cbs
and so ends the chapter of almost 46 years as this reporter moves on along the journey,'' edwards, 70, said on friday's midday ``cbs newsbreak.''
a deep bow of gratitude, love and respect to the men and women of cbs news and to the company for which they stand. to you out there, thank you for honoring me with your presence in my audience, and most of all for your voices, your most sweet voices. douglas edwards, cbs news, new york.''
edwards was the nation's first nightly tv anchorman, preceding walter cronkite in the job at cbs in 1948
edwards joined cbs radio in 1942, and was a member of edward r. murrow's legendary london staff toward the end of world war ii. he also served as paris bureau chief
edwards' last radio broadcast was friday night. at its close, cbs news vice president joe dembo wished edwards ``goodbye and godspeed,'' and cbs evening news anchorman dan rather saluted him as ``one of the founding fathers'' of broadcast journalism
president reagan sent a congratulatory letter calling edwards a ``consummate professional.''
edwards plans to move to sarasota, fla., and continue lecturing on broadcast journalism while he starts work on a book
actress britt ekland has given birth to her third child, an 8-pound, 12-ounce boy named thomas jefferson ekland mcdonnell, her manager says
the baby, born thursday at cedars-sinai medical center, is miss ekland's first child with husband james mcdonnell, manager paul cohen said friday
miss ekland and mcdonnell, former drummer for the stray cats rock group have been married four years
miss ekland, 45, has appeared in more than 30 films, including such movies as ``the man with the golden gun.''
her other children are victoria sellers, 23, and nickolai edland adler, 14
