carter is coming to oregon to give a lecture at linfield college in nearby mcminnville, and plans to stay wednesday night at the governor's residence here, goldschmidt spokesman gregg kantor said friday
goldschmidt served as secretary of transportation under carter
carter also plans to spend some time vacationing in oregon, kantor said
hall of fame pitcher vernon ``lefty'' gomez was hospitalized after complaining of chest pains, and was expected to remain in the hospital for several days, a hospital spokeswoman said
gomez, 79, was in improved condition, marin general hospital nursing supervisor diana rich said friday night. ``he's doing very well, but he'll be here awhile longer,'' she said
gomez has a longstanding heart condition
he was driven to the hospital by his wife, june, from their home in nearby novato, 25 miles north of san francisco
if he lets me drive him, he has to be sick,'' mrs. gomez said. ``thirteen years ago he had a heart attack and he drove me to the hospital. he said he didn't trust me to drive. then he had a triple bypass.''
gomez, a strong left-hander who pitched for 14 years in the major leagues, all but one year with the new york yankees, had a career record of 189-102. he was 6-0 in appearances in five world series
performers robert cray, albert collins and kim wilson of the fabulous thunderbirds are to headline a benefit concert sunday for grammy-winning blues singer koko taylor, who was injured in an auto accident
miss taylor, known as the ``queen of the blues,'' suffered broken ribs and a broken collarbone in the feb. 4 accident, which also injured three band members
it was a disaster, but we are so fortunate to be alive,'' miss taylor said in a telephone interview friday from her chicago home. ``i'm very thankful that so many people think so much of me to put on this benefit.''
sunday's benefit will raise money to pay for the $40,000 in medical bills, said bruce iglauer, president of alligator records, who helped arrange the event at the riviera nightclub
miss taylor said she was unsure whether she'll be able to attend. but she was grateful for the support, and for the thousands of cards and letters she's received
it makes me know there are lots of people out there that care,'' she said
gunmen in a passing car opened fire indiscriminately on people gathered in several groups along a street friday night, killing one and wounding at least 10, police said
among the wounded was a 4-year-old boy shot four times, a hospital spokeswoman said
the shooting started around 7:20 p.m. when several gunmen in a car ``indiscriminately fired at people who were on a sidewalk,'' said deputy police chief william rathburn
at least 11 people initially were reported wounded, although rathburn said others may have been hit
four people were taken to los angeles county-usc medical center, where a 19-year-old man shot in the right side was pronounced dead, said hospital spokeswoman adelaida de la certa
the 4-year-old boy was in serious but stable condition, ms. de la certa said
a 29-year-old man hit in the right hand and right leg and a 20-year-old man shot in the left leg were both in fair condition
the other seven wounded were taken to other hospitals, she said
drive-by shootings have become a problem in recent months in the los angeles area. police have attributed many of them to gang wars, but did not say if friday's shootings were gang-related
two years after an iowa physicist nearly ruined his reputation by suggesting that 10 million small, speedy comets hit earth's atmosphere annually, a nasa scientist has found evidence supporting louis frank's theory
i'm happy, but it's been a long two years,'' frank said friday, adding that he was met with ``total disbelief'' and ``lost a lot of friends'' after proposing that billions of water-bearing comets could have provided enough water to fill the seas during earth's early history
other scientists said they remained skeptical of the new evidence, which came from telescope observations by clayne yeates, a physicist at the national aeronautics and space administration's jet propulsion laboratory here
i'm very convinced that what i'm seeing is real,'' said yeates, who is deputy project scientist for the planned 1989 launch of the galileo space probe to jupiter. ``these objects would not have been seen inadvertently during other searches. they're small, they're dark and they're moving fast.''
the theory by frank, a physicist at the university of iowa, is ``one of the decade's most controversial astronomical theories,'' a nasa news release said
frank proposed the theory after ultraviolet photographs of earth taken by nasa's dynamics explorer 1 spacecraft between 1981 and 1986 revealed countless dark spots that appeared to be tiny holes in earth's atmosphere
he theorized that about 10 million comets, essentially 30-foot-diameter fluffy snowballs with a dark coating, plunge into the atmosphere each year, forming holes, then breaking up and vaporizing
yeates said his observations on the 36-inch spacewatch telescope at kitt peak national observatory in arizona make him believe that at least a million such comets hit the atmosphere annually at a speed of 22,000 mph
the comets appeared as white streaks on enhanced telescope images, he said
in a telephone interview from iowa city, frank said a soon-to-be-published study, in which atmospheric holes were recently observed by sweden's viking spacecraft, also supports his theory
i'm a little skeptical,'' said astronomer anita cochran of the university of texas at austin. ``he (yeates) may be seeing something, but to leap to 10-meter comets is a fairly large leap of imagination.''
cochran voiced the most common objection to frank's theory: if so many icy comets hit earth's atmosphere, they also should strike the moon, creating a lot of water vapor. yet the moon has very little water vapor
university of michigan physicist and planetary scientist thomas donahue said that until he examines yeates' findings, ``i'm not going to say this sounds like confirmation of frank's comets or not. but it certainly is exciting.''
about a year ago, donahue used 1977 data from the voyager 2 space probe to show that earth's atmosphere contained an excess of hydrogen atoms released from water vapor. he said the discovery could be consistent with frank's theory, but also could be explained if the hydrogen came from 10 million times fewer comets that were smaller, faster and much more active than those postulated by frank
the less abundant comets wouldn't provide enough water to fill the oceans, donahue said
i really am a bit skeptical'' of yeates' observations, said brian marsden, associate director for planetary sciences at the harvard-smithsonian center for astrophysics in cambridge, mass
if they (comets) are as numerous as he's talking about, then some of these should show up when the telescope is in more normal operation, and they haven't,'' marsden said
frank said only two specialized telescopes in the country, including spacewatch, are capable of observing the comets
mayor edward i. koch says he disagrees with jesse jackson on virtually every issue, but will vote for jackson if he is the democratic presidential nominee
i think that in three weeks, based on all the social programs we would be putting into effect (under jackson), if you did everything he said he wanted to do, we'd be in bankruptcy,'' koch said friday. ``people know that's pie in the sky.''
in response, jackson's campaign manager, jerry austin, said koch has ``solidified his position in the national exaggeration hall of fame.''
koch said jackson is ``on the wrong side of every issue i know of with two exceptions: drugs _ he's great in opposition to drugs _ and he's great in talking about the need for family responsibility and particularly as it relates to education
on the economy, he's terrible. we'd be in bankruptcy.''
nevertheless, the mayor said, he'd vote for jackson if he were the nominee out of party loyalty and because ``he'd be better than (vice president george) bush.''
in green bay, wis., jackson told reporters he had not heard of koch's remarks. but when they were described to him he said, ``that's unfortunate. i should not dignify that statement.''
iowa democrats say they'll expose and work to defeat supporters of political extremist lyndon larouche who filed as democrats to run in legislative and congressional primaries
what they seek to do is clothe themselves with the respectability and tradition of the democratic party in order to further their misguided beliefs,'' said house speaker don avenson. ``i will use all the available resources to ensure the defeat of larouche candidates in every democratic primary contest.''
they apparently feel this is fertile ground, but we are going to teach them a major lesson,'' said joe shanahan, who runs legislative elections for the party
their alarm grew out of the number of larouche supporters meeting friday's deadline for filing nomination papers to run in the june 8 primary for legislative and congressional seats
roeder and shanahan said they've identified 16 larouche supporters who had filed nominating petitions to run in the democratic primary
