u.s. taxpayers helped the nicaraguan contras smell good, play volleyball and watch tv from a new sofa in 1986, but u.s. officials refused to approve bills for whiskey and jumbo shrimp
using the freedom of information act, peter kornbluh of the national security archive obtained a 1986 letter to a liaison for the rebels from the director of the state department's nicaraguan humanitarian assistance office
the letter lists some ``approved'' and ``disallowed'' expenses incurred by the contras in 1985 and 1986 and submitted to the office for reimbursement. all items on the list, published in the may issue of harper's magazine, previously had been rejected ``pending further review.''
allowed:
_ $5,760.53 for deodorant
_ $1,071 for volleyball equipment
_ two living room sets worth $1,283.63, a dining room set worth $654.94 and a $477.75 sofa
_ 12 domino sets worth $132.18
disallowed:
_ 16 bottles of whiskey worth $120
_ 32 pounds, or $8 worth, of meat for dogs
_ $369.82 in christmas decorations
_ 25 pounds of jumbo shrimp worth $235
_ $226 in guitar strings
the office approved three 19-inch color televisions that cost about $1,000 each, but rejected two other sets. it approved 620 boxes of candy worth $6,570, but rejected 14 boxes of chocolate and two boxes of candy worth $381.35
the office, which was opened to distribute humanitarian aid appropriated by congress and closed in july 1986, did approve a limited amount of martial aid: two pairs of boxing gloves
the contras have been fighting nicaragua's sandinista government. a 60-day cease-fire went into effect friday
breezy weather early today forced organizers to scratch their attempt at a world-record human-powered flight across the aegean sea by a cyclist-pilot in a flying machine called the daedalus
windless weather is important for the 74-mile flight to the island of santorini and winds of nearly six miles an hour grounded the silver-and-pink aircraft on a military runway at the last moment
it's disappointing, but the wind seems to be a little too strong,'' pilot greg zack, 26, a professional cyclist from wilmington, n.c., told reporters
the last-minute postponement illustrated just how unpredictable the weather can be on this southern greek island
gusting winds and rain squalls delayed the first scheduled flight of the daedalus 88 on wednesday
after nine days of blustery weather, conditions thursday were good enough to allow the five athlete pilots to take turns test-flying the plane at speeds of around 14 miles per hour and about 15 feet above the tarmac of the greek air force base
a successful touchdown on santorini (thira) would more than triple the exisiting record of 22.5 miles for straight-line human-powered flight, set by bryan allen piloting the gossamer albatross across the english channel in 1979
built of high-tech composite materials _ graphite epoxy, kevlar plastic fiber and mylar polystyrene film _ the daedalus plane has a huge 112-foot wingspan and resembles an outsized insect in flight
the flight in a fragile pedal-powered plane is aimed at emulating daedalus, the legendary craftsman who flapped his way across the aegean on wings of wax and feathers, according to a 3,500-year-old greek myth
according to the myth, daedalus made it safely across the aegean but his son icarus flew too close to the sun and plummeted to his death as his wings melted
a man working at an archaeological dig attacked co-workers, stabbing two women to death and injuring a pregnant woman and her husband, police said
the suspect, identified as arthur faulkner and believed to be 40 to 45 years old, remained at large today, police said
authorities said they had no motive for the stabbings friday
police temporarily shut down a nearby expressway and searched a wooded area in this philadelphia suburb after the man fled in a pickup truck registered to one of the victims
the four graduate students were ``stabbed with a knife or other sharp instrument,'' while working in a house where artifacts are tested, police capt. john sheehan said. he refused to say whether a weapon was recovered
glenn w. sheehan, 39, was stabbed several times. he ran from the house to a neighbor's house, then to a construction site where the archaeological dig was under way, according to witnesses
sheehan was taken to bryn mawr hospital with stab wounds of the legs, arms and abdomen. he was in stable condition, hospital officials said
his wife, 31-year-old anne m. jensen, was taken to hahnemann hospital in philadelphia, where she was treated for multiple stab wounds to the back and internal injuries
she was in serious but stable condition, said an unidentified hospital spokeswoman. her fetus suffered no damage, the spokeswoman said
the couple were working on their doctorates in anthropology at bryn mawr college, college spokeswoman catherine lafarge said
the two slain women, also graduate students in anthropology and archaeology, died of multiple stab wounds, montgomery county coroner dr. theodore garcia said
lower merion township police lt. john maloney identified them as clarice j. dorner, 30, of elk grove village, ill., and annaliese h. killoran, 22, of lynn, mass
