the young officer who led an august coup attempt that nearly felled president corazon aquino's government fled a prison ship in manila bay early today aided by his elite navy guards
mrs. aquino cut short a private easter holiday in northern luzon and rushed to the capital for an emergency cabinet meeting after hearing of the escape of former lt. col. gregorio ``gringo'' honasan
she told a national television audience honasan was to have been court-martialed for leading the bloody aug. 28 coup attempt, in which at least 53 people were killed and hundreds wounded
mrs. aquino warned military personnel that those who assist or harbor honasan ``will be dealt with promptly and severely with the full force of the law.''
the charismatic soldier escaped at about 2:30 a.m. aboard two rubber boats along with 14 guards from the navy's special warfare unit who were guarding him, col. oscar florendo, chief military spokesman, told reporters
florendo said the roughly half dozen remaining guards fired on the boats as they slipped away in the darkness, but apparently missed. the prison ship, the andres bonifacio, was anchored 500 yards from the navy's main wharf, he said
chief of staff gen. renato de villa ordered a nationwide search for the 39-year-old honasan, who had been on the ship since his december arrest in a manila suburb
armored personnel carriers and bulldozers blocked entrances to military camps in manila, and checkpoints were set up on major highways
florendo said a reserve lieutenant who was frustrated over his inability to obtain a regular commission had aided in the escape
it is believed that bribery was a factor,'' the spokesman added, saying the lieutenant and 13 enlisted personnel had apparently assisted and joined in the escape. he said the boats used to flee had been sent to increase security after the military learned of a plot to free honasan
florendo warned that honasan may try to organize a new bid to topple mrs. aquino. he said the government expected honasan to resume anti-aquino propaganda efforts and again try to divide the military
mrs. aquino said honasan fled to avoid prosecution for mutiny and sedition, arson, murder and conduct unbecoming an officer. she said his escape ``is tantamount to an admission of his guilt.''
she also said honasan staged his coup attempt to evade investigation of alleged misapproriation of $100,000 worth of military equipment and to avoid a combat assignment against communist rebels
i appeal to all citizens and leaders, public and private, to assist us in the recapture of honasan as soon as possible,'' she said
presidential guards stepped up security around the presidential palace immediately after word of the escape. civilians were barred from the palace compound
defense secretary fidel v. ramos said the military was ``taking every possible action'' to bring back honasan and ``minimize or neutralize any further damage that he can make.''
honasan, former defense ministry chief of security, played a key role in the feb. 22, 1986 mutiny that with a popular uprising toppled president ferdinand marcos
but he became disillusioned with mrs. aquino, accusing her of ``weak and inept'' leadership that fortified the 19-year-old communist insurgency
on aug. 28, honasan led a force of 2,000 men who attacked the presidential palace and seized several media and military installations in the capital before they were driven off by pro-aquino forces
mrs. aquino said the attack it was aimed at killing her and her family
honasan's was the most serious of several major plots to unseat mrs. aquino. the military says 11 officers and 90 enlisted men involved in the coup attempt are still at large
honasan is widely regarded within the 160,000-member armed forces as a courageous, experienced officer. military sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he is so popular he had become the ``dominant figure'' aboard the ship that was supposed to be his prison
florendo said the military received information a week ago that honasan would try to escape and it sent rubber boats to guard the ship, expecting outsiders to try to storm the vessel. ``instead, it came from the inside.''
honasan was defense ministry security chief when opposition sen. juan ponce enrile was minister of national defense. enrile was fired in november 1986 after the government said it thwarted a coup attempt by his followers
honasan remained in hiding for months after the august coup
maj. gen. ramon montano, former commander of the national capital regional defense command, said weeks before the arrest that honasan was being protected by undisclosed civilian and military figures
a disc jockey who told a white lie about the weather found his listeners ready for an april fools' day snow job
wkir-fm radio personality dan baxter told a whopper about the weather that was swallowed hook, line and sinker by some listeners. his phony forecast _ freezing rain and snow _ in a state where the merest hint of winter weather sends residents scurrying to the grocery put a damper on at least one businessman's day
they said the rain was supposed to turn to sleet and snow, and the temperature tonight and tomorrow was going to be in the 20s,'' said barber larry kirk, who said trade was slow following baxter's bogus prediction of icy streets
i'm not going to listen to that station any more,'' kirk said
the state highway patrol was bombarded with anxious calls about road conditions. troopers were stymied, however, when they turned to the national weather service for help
the weather service called us wanting to know where we got our information,'' station spokeswoman rhonda perry said. ``then the highway patrol called wanting to talk to the station manager. then, the civil defense called wanting to talk to the station manager.''
baxter went on air to apologize, and told listeners he'd lost his job
april fool!
he's still kidding around,'' perry said
the phone hasn't stopped ringing (with listeners concerned for baxter) since i got in,'' said tim allen, the disc jockey who follows baxter
a disc jockey's on-air account of an unidentified flying object causing commotion in a park was so convincing that some people claimed they witnessed the mysterious rumble and flash of light
people are seeing it. but it ain't there,'' said fred honsberger, news director for kdka-am, the station that broadcast the april fools' day joke
we just had a lady call who said she saw a bunch of gray trucks go in led by a jeep. these people are claiming to have seen that thing. but we started it all,'' honsberger said, chuckling
not everyone was laughing
worried listeners flooded the switchboard at the allegheny county police station in north park. sgt. william wolverton repeatedly assured callers there was nothing going on and that the radio report had been a hoax
they were pretty much upset with the fact that a radio station would be allowed to get away it,'' wolverton said. ``a lot of them were critical because they picked good friday. good friday seemed to be more important than april fools' day.''
morning disc jockey john cigna startled his listeners with the report and offered no explanation or elaboration when he ended his four-hour broadcast at 9 a.m. but his replacement, doug hawkes, informed listeners it had been a joke
remember everyone, today is april fools' day,'' hawkes said
none of the morning news reports included the so-called emergency, honsberger noted
that should be a clue to anybody,'' he said. ``if anything was happening, it would be our lead story. we'd have reporters there.''
tornadoes touched down in five east texas towns, destroying two mobiles homes, damaging dozens of houses and overturning cars, authorities said. one minor injury was reported
in east mountain, near longview, a tornado damaged 25 homes friday, blowing seven or eight of them off their foundations, witnesses said
i was on top of the mountain watching for tails out of the clouds when the rain began falling so hard you couldn't even see,'' said east mountain assistant city marshal phil luchau. ``we knew the storm was getting worse, but it happened so quick, there wasn't time to warn anyone.''
a tornado also destroyed two mobile homes and damaged three homes in nearby glenwood acres, officials said, but it was unclear whether it was the same tornado that struck east mountain
the city hall, an elementary school and a car dealership suffered heavy damage at gladewater, about 20 miles northwest of longview. a supermarket and several mobile homes also were hit
another tornado damaged four homes in mound city, and severely damaged the mound city store
it just hasn't sunk in yet,'' said deanna holden, owner of the store. ``we just all got underneath the dining room table. if we hadn't gotten my grandbaby out of her crib, she'd be dead because of all the flying glass.''
