secretary of state george p. shultz today received pope john paul ii's blessing on the eve of his new middle east peace mission. the pontiff stressed any accord must respect the ``legitimate rights'' of both israel and the palestinians
god bless your efforts,'' the pope told shultz following their 30-minute private meeting in the papal library
i go from here to the middle east with your blessing to sustain the effort'' to spur the arab-israeli peace process, shultz responded in front of reporters and photographers
shultz leaves for jerusalem on sunday on the first part of a trip that will also take him to jordan, syria, egypt and saudi arabia. his trip to the region last month failed to bring an agreement
vatican spokesman joaquin navarro said the talks focused on the two mens' ``common preoccupation for international peace,'' specifically east-west relations, ``the continuing grave situation'' in the middle east and developments in central america
the pope ``insisted on the legitimate rights of the palestinian people and on the moral duty to find a solution that also takes into account the legitimate rights of israel,'' the spokesman said
john paul voiced ``great interest in the efforts under way for the search, obligatory for everyone, of a process that opens the way to solutions acceptable to all,'' navarro said
the pope has frequently spoken in favor of a palestinian homeland
the vatican does not have diplomatic relations with israel. vatican officials have cited the palestinian question, israel's unsettled boundaries and the status of jerusalem as reasons for the absence of ties
the vatican does not have diplomatic relations with jordan either
shultz, who is episcopalian, brought to the vatican today an entourage of 31 people, including his wife, helena, a roman catholic
after a salute in the vatican's marbled, frescoed clementine room by seven swiss guards in multi-colored uniforms designed by michelangelo, shultz was ushered into the pope's chambers by archbishop dino monduzzi, head of the papal household
following the audience, the two were joined by mrs. shultz, wearing a black dress and a black lace mantilla over her head, and the u.s. ambassador to the holy see, frank shakespeare, and his 21-year-old daughter, fredericka
john paul, wearing white robes, presented shultz with a framed sketch by italian artist lello scorzelli. he gave pontifical medals and rosaries to the others
the group then moved to the salome throne room, where the pope shook hands with the rest of the delegation, including secret service agents and state department spokesman charles redman. the pope wished them all a happy easter
it was shultz's third meeting at the vatican with john paul. he and his wife visited the vatican in 1986 for easter. the previous meeting was in december 1982
shultz and his wife are scheduled to attend the pope's easter mass in st. peter's square on sunday morning
