iraq said today that its forces have overrun kurdish guerrilla bases in the mountainous northeast in an offensive aimed at crushing iranian-backed rebels who threaten vital oilfields
kurdish guerrilla leaders have claimed the iraqis, backed by tanks and air strikes, were dropping poison gas bombs on villages in what one commander called ``a war of genocide.''
baghdad radio, monitored in nicosia, quoted a military communique as saying its troops ``completely purged'' the area around qara dagh in the sulaimaniyeh region, 50 miles west of the kirkuk oilfields
qara dagh is only 20 miles west of lake darbandikhan, where iranian revolutionary guards have thrust into iraq in a 16-day-old offensive
all traitors have finally been destroyed,'' the communique declared in a reference to the iranian-backed kurdish rebels who have been fighting baghdad for an independent homeland for years
there was no independent confirmation
jalal talabani, leader of the patriotic union of kurdistan, told the associated press that heavy fighting was raging in the region friday but that he had no reports of an iraqi breakthrough
massud barzani, leader of the iranian-backed kurdish democratic party, said in a statement several days ago, that the iraqi army had launched a major offensive against the guerrillas march 23
he said two divisions of troops, backed by tanks, artillery and air strikes, were seeking to dislodge kurdish fighters from the qara dagh mountains between kirkuk and the provincial capital of sulaimaniyeh
an iraqi division usually numbers about 12,000 men
barzani said the iraqi assaults had been beaten back
he claimed iraqi warplanes were dropping chemical bombs on kurdish strongholds and villages suspected of harboring guerrillas
the villages were north of the iranian bridgehead around lake darbandikhan, where iran claims iraqi chemical bombing attacks march 16-17 killed 5,000 civilians and injured as many more
talabani said the iraqis had seized some villages. he also charged the iraqi air force was dropping gas bombs on kurdish settlements
it's a war of genocide against the kurdish people,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``they use chemical weapons against us all the time and raze our villages.''
today's communique said an iraqi force, including kurdish fighters loyal to baghdad, had overrun 21 kurdish bases and villages used by the guerrillas in the last few days. it gave no casualty figure
the kurdish guerrillas have in the last 18 months created a second front in the 7{-year-old iran-iraq war. the iraqis have had to divert tens of thousands of troops badly needed in the main battle zones in the south to contain the insurgency in kurdistan
the kurds claimed to control 4,000 square miles in the northeast
about 20 million kurds live in the mountainous region where the borders of iran, iraq, syria and turkey meet
authorities in the southern chinese province of guangdong seized 792 pounds of opium and heroin and arrested several gangsters involved in drug smuggling, the pro-beijing newspaper wen wei po reported saturday
the newpaper did not say how many people were arrested but said the gang had more than 80 members who have been dealing in drugs since 1985
it said the gang transported the drugs from the golden triangle area of vietnam, burma and thailand to the southern chinese province of yunnan and guangdong and then to the british colony of hong kong
the operation was directed by a hong kong man identified only as chan x kwong, the newspaper said, but it did not say if chan was among those arrested
it said chan directed the drug smuggling operation with a walkie talkie from a house in suburban canton, the capital of guangdong province
a truck modified in hong kong transported 264 pounds of the drugs through the chinese special economic zone of shenzhen into neighboring hong kong, the paper said
the gang members fought among themselves and chan reportedly tried to rob his partner ah wing last year, the paper said
hong kong police said they have not heard of the gang
the marxist government imposed huge price inceases on food, and a government newspaper said saturday that the increases were necessitated by a guerrilla war that has ravaged the economy
prices for rice, sugar, corn, cooking oil, bread and soap all rose sharply under government-mandated increases that took effect friday in the southern african nation. in a bid to offset the higher food prices, the government also granted wage increases to some workers
rice went from 9 cents to 60 cents per kilogram, about 2.2 pounds. corn flour rose from nine cents to 32 cents per kilogram and a kilogram of sugar went from 11 cents to 59 cents
the minimum wage for an industrial worker has been raised from about $17 a month to $29 per month. however, raises were not granted to workers in factories that were losing money
mozambique also has a high unemployment rate and thousands of refugees displaced by a war raging since the 1960s. mozambique won independence from portugal in 1975 after years of fighting. since then guerrillas of the mozambique national resistance have been battling to oust the marxist government
the daily newspaper noticias, in an editorial saturday, blamed the country's economic woes on ``the continued and systematic aggression against mozambique, carried out by the racist regimes of the region _ first rhodesia and later south africa.''
in the mid-1970s, then white-ruled rhodesia helped backed the anti-marxist guerrillas. after rhodesia became black-ruled zimbabwe in 1980, south africa began supplying the rebels
south africa and mozambique signed a mutual non-aggression pact in 1984, but both sides regularly accuse the other of violations
noticias said foreign support of the rebels has destabilized mozambique and ``has prevented us from consolidating our independence and developing our economy.''
mozambique, devastated by more than 20 consecutive years of war, is currently one of the poorest countries in the world,'' noticias said. ``the state can no longer go on paying food subsidies.''
an estimated 5 million of mozambique's 14.5 million people are in need of food aid
in other developments, government troops killed 38 rebel fighters in clashes during the past week in three separate provinces, the national news agency aim said
the rebels were killed in clashes from march 29-31 in the central provinces of sofala and zambazia and the northwestern province of tete, aim said, citing a report on radio mozambique
the report made no mention of government troop casualties
soviet officials negotiating with the united states on halving nuclear arsenals no longer believe they will have an agreement to sign by the time president reagan visits next month, well-placed soviet sources say
the ruling politburo officially remains determined ``to work intensively for the speediest drafting of a set of documents'' to have them ready for signing at the moscow summit. but soviet officials said privately they do not sense a similar urgency on the american side
reagan is scheduled to meet soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev in moscow may 29 to june 2 at the fourth u.s.-soviet summit since gorbachev came to power three years ago
one source familiar with the negotiations said the united states still has not responded directly to four specific proposals gorbachev put forward at his last meeting with u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz in february
they don't appear to be in a position to make decisions at this point,'' the analyst said of the american negotiators
speaking on condition he not be identified, the source said there are ``major, substantive issues'' outstanding on how to cut both sides' strategic arsenals by 50 percent even before consideration of the u.s. ``star wars'' program for a space-based shield against nuclear attack. disputes over that program have blocked agreement in the past
the concept of a 50 percent cut has been accepted by both sides, but the issue is complicated by the differing numbers and types of weapons in each side's arsenals
the source said the two sides remain far apart on how to reduce mobile intercontinental ballistic missiles, which make up an important element of the soviet arsenal, and on cuts in sea-launched cruise missiles
chief u.s. arms negotiator max kampelman acknowledged differences in those areas as well as others in testifying before congress last week
a western diplomatic source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the united states is pressing for a ban on mobile icbms such as the soviet ss-25 because it would be too difficult if not impossible to verify the number of such weapons remaining in the soviet arsenal after an agreed-upon number had been destroyed
the soviets, the diplomat said, are pressing to include sea-launched cruise missiles in any agreement, but u.s. negotiators contend they should be left out because no acceptable verifications measures exist to ensure compliance
a soviet source said, and the diplomat confirmed, that the soviets have proposed a joint project to test a verification procedure using airborne electronic sensors. u.s. negotiators have expressed doubts such sensors could tell one nuclear weapon from another or from a ship's nuclear reactor
we proposed a way to verify sea-launched weapons,'' a soviet official said. ``they told us they didn't think it would work. but they haven't come up with any other plan.''
another soviet analyst in the communist party apparatus said he suspects the u.s. side has concluded the soviets are so anxious for an agreement that the reagan administration can gain more concessions by holding out longer
kampelman said the united states is still trying to conclude an agreement before the summit. but he, too, was skeptical
achievement of a treaty in that time frame is possible, but it will be difficult given the number and complexity of issues which remain unresolved,'' kampelman said
mailing a letter costs more starting sunday, as new postage rates go into effect
it will cost 25 cents to mail first-class letters, up 3 cents
the second ounce of first-class mail also rises 3 cents, to 20 cents
but postal cards are up only a penny, to 15 cents
the rate increases cover most classes of mail, with larger hikes for advertising and periodicals than for letters
daylight-saving time is back
the change, moving clocks ahead one hour, occurred at 2 a.m. sunday
folks who forgot likely found themselves an hour late for church or other activities
daylight time will remain in effect until oct. 30 this year, when that hour of lost sleep will be returned
bombs planted by the afghan intelligence agency, created and run by the soviet kgb, have killed more than 400 civilians in pakistan, according to u.s. and pakistani officials
pakistan has balked at signing a united nations-brokered deal calling for an end to covert u.s. aid to afghan guerrillas at the same time that moscow stops aiding the the kabul regime
the bombings definitely have people worried. they are designed to get pakistan to sign the geneva agreement. but the government has stuck to its position,'' said a pakistani official. he, like u.s. intelligence sources interviewed about the bombings, spoke on condition of anonymity
the afghan ministry for state security, or wad, ``is a mirror image of the kgb,'' combining domestic and foreign intelligence activities with military functions, said one u.s. intelligence analyst
a state department report issued last year said wad had 20,000 agents, although some u.s. and pakistani officials put the number at 30,000. wad has its own uniformed military units and assigns officers to regular military units to bolster discipline, according to the state department
wad has 1,500 advisers from the kgb, which has run it since since shortly after the coup that brought marxists to power in april 1978, the sources said
the most recent terrorist episode was last thursday, when a bomb exploded in a poultry shop near the afghan border, killing seven people and injuring 18
the bloodiest incident was last july 14, when three car bombs exploded at the main bazaar of karachi, the largest city in pakistan, killing 72 and injuring 260
wad staged about a dozen bombings inside pakistan in 1985, 20 in 1986, and more than 100 in 1987, said a second u.s. analyst. ``they are continuing at about the same rate this year.''
among recent bombings attributed to wad:
_feb. 22, one person was killed and two others were hurt by a bomb in a popular hotel in bajaur in the northwest frontier province
_feb. 23, a boy was killed by a bomb in his home in bajaur. the same day, another bomb destroyed a shop owned by an afghan refugee in the city
_feb. 27, five people were killed and 11 injured by a bomb in a motorcycle in a in the main bazaar in thal, a refugee center in the northwest frontier province
_march 1, two people were killed and two others were injured when a bomb exploded in peshawar, a city in northern pakistan crowded with afghan refugees
_march 18, a letterbox exploded at a bus station, in rawalpindi, setting fire to an empty bus
_march 25, nine people were injured, one critically, by a bomb at a bus stand in rawalpindi
diplomats at the afghan embassy in washington declined to comment on wad or any other subject
the bombings started in 1985, about when mikhail s. gorbachev became general secretary of the soviet communist party, and the current afghan leader, known by the single name of najibullah, left the afghan intelligence agency to become secretary in the ruling party, say u.s. and pakistani sources
najibullah, trained as a physician in kabul, became party leader in 1986 and head of state last year. col. geb. ghulam farouq yaqubi now runs wad, which until last year was known as the committee for state security, or khad
clearly, sometime in 1985, moscow decided it had to increase pressure on pakistan, and began cross-border air raids'' in afghan warplanes piloted by soviets and afghans, said one u.s. government source
but the air raids ``backfired,'' said the source. the united states came very close to selling pakistan high-technology airborne warning and control (awacs) planes to track the intruders, a sale that was opposed by india, a friend of the soviet union and an enemy of pakistan
instead, wad ``stepped up the terror bombing, and there hasn't been so much of a reaction,'' said the source
the initial bombings were aimed at the 3 million afghan refugees who live just inside pakistan, crossing the border to wage their guerrilla war against the estimated 115,000 soviet troops backing the kabul regime
the campaign became more serious, said a pakistani official, when the bombs began to explode in major cities like islamabad, rawalpindi and lahore, far from the refugees, deep in the heart of pakistan
afghan intelligence, under soviet tutelage, recruits agents to plant the bombs, which analysts describe as ``crude,'' and consisting in part of soviet-made components
we have arrested a lot of these guys, and they say they are paid by the kabul government,'' said the pakistani official. ``they include pakistanis and afghans,'' who are drawn from the same ethnic groups and cross the border easily, he said
for each bombing, they are paid several hundred dollars, ``a huge amount of money'' in such an impoverished area, said the official. ``for killing, they get more.''
in the best of times, which these are not, life was no cinch in san miguelito
but a general strike aimed at overthrowing the regime of gen. manuel antonio noriega closed panama's banks and much of its business and sent the poor suburb's unemployment even higher. the few who have jobs often can't cash their checks to buy food because of government-ordered banks closures and u.s. financial sanctions
better-off panamanians had cash at home or were able to withdraw some before the banks closed, and by buying only essentials they are managing to get by
but in the hillside shacks of san miguelito, that option didn't exist
hunger spread so rapidly that the parish churches, which were distributing food, have had to pass the job to caritas, a roman catholic relief organization, and content themselves with trying to catalogue the soaring need
they are giving out 3,500 meals a day in my parish,'' said the rev. reynaldo karamanites, who heads the samaria parish in san miguelito. three days earlier, he said, the number was 2,800
in 1980, there were about 80,000 people in the parish and 44,000 were unemployed,'' he said. ``add at least 30 percent to the unemployment figure now.''
unemployment always has been bad,'' said the rev. jorge altafulla of the slightly less impoverished san miguelito parish of christ the redeemer. ``a lot of people here had only occasional day work and now they have lost even that.''
caritas is feeding about 9,000 families in the province of panama, which includes the capital, and the number is soaring. most of the 9,000 are in san miguelito
the caritas food is donated or bought with donated money
we keep praying that people will give more food and money,'' said the rev. laurino duran, who heads caritas in the panama city area
he said donations are meeting the present need but worried about the near future
we've received nothing from the government,'' said ursinis de castillo, who helped dish out cooked rice and scrambled eggs to residents of sector 28, where she lives in christ the redeemer parish. ``all we have is the church and our community.''
some people from the government were here with 100 bags of food to sell to government workers,'' said one man. ``they charged $15.60.''
yesterday, (caritas) brought rice with chicken,'' said soia de aguilar, who was waiting for food. ``they try to see that everybody has enough, but each family gets the same and some families have eight or nine members.''
caritas started giving food to churches to distribute starting in early march after banks closed because a political crisis had sparked panic among depositors
on march 3, the united states froze panamanian funds in american banks, one of several steps intended to force noriega from power. noriega, head of panama's armed forces and the power behind the civilian government, is under indictment on drug trafficking charges in the united states. the freezing of funds deprived panama of its supply of dollars, the official panamanian currency, and on march 4 noriega ordered the banks to remain closed
the churches stopped trying to hand out the caritas packages last week when the crowds got too big too fast, and now the food is brought to central distribution points, cooked over wood fires and distributed to the list of the neediest compiled by the church
even if banks were to reopen, they are critically short of dollars because of the american freeze. the government has been unable to pay most of its 130,000 employees, and the banks likely would have trouble producing dollars to cover checks waiting to be cashed
generally, stores insist on cash and will not take checks or credit cards
caritas officials say it now requires about $600,000 in donations a month to keep the people it feeds supplied with basics such as rice, beans, cooking oil and powdered milk. in sector 28, a caritas worker said the list of families deemed eligible is growing by five or six families a day and that the increase is higher in other areas
a few people here worked for the government, a few had other jobs, all sorts of jobs,'' said mrs. de aguilar. ``that's san miguelito. we do a little of everything and a lot of nothing.''
president francois mitterrand and politicians from france's left and right put aside their quarrels saturday and paid their last respects to edgar faure, one of the most widely respected statesmen of the century
faure, a brilliant and witty politician who in four decades of service occupied nearly every important french government post except president, died wednesday at the age of 79
the ceremony at paris' st. clotilde basilica was simple. faure's plain coffin was draped with the french tricolor. upon it was placed the bicorn hat and sword of the academie francaise, of which he was a member
mgr. daniel pezeril, former auxiliary bishop of paris, represented cardinal jean-marie lustiger in conducting the service. in his brief homily, pezeril noted faure's long fight for human rights, saying he believed such a fight was a ``touchstone of political responsibility.''
as a christian, the deceased will have thus participated in the fate of the world,'' he said
also attending were bernadette chirac, representing her husband, premier jacques chirac, who was on a trip to the french antilles; former president valery giscard d'estaing; jacques chaban-delmas, president of the national assembly; alain poher, president of the senate; finance minister edouard balladur and other present and former leaders and opposition members
faure was known for his oratorial skills and his ability to advance policies that went beyond the traditional right-left cleavage in french politics
although he was a member of several socialist governments in the fourth republic, he was widely respected by all
his last post was as head of the bicentennial commemoration of the french revolution, which occurs next year
efforts to wrap up farm provisions of the 1,000-page trade bill are snagged over a plan by sen. tom harkin, d-iowa, to pump $75 million a year into crop research every year for 20 years
the plan is designed principally to spur demand for corn and soybeans by finding new, non-food uses for them, leading to higher farm earnings. ``it's really a long-term agricultural bill, an investment in the future,'' press secretary pam mckinney says
thus far, house negotiators on the trade bill aren't so sure
the plan would be a boon for iowa state university and similar research centers but could whet other lawmakers' appetites for more of the same for the folks back in their own states
the chairman of the house agriculture committee, e. ``kika'' de la garza, d-texas, has been cool toward the notion thus far. and for that reason farm lawmakers were still wrangling late in the week, when most other conferees on the trade bill had reached tentative agreement
it now appears unlikely that the matter will be resolved until after april 11, when congress returns from its spring break
as big as it is, the plant research provision is small potatoes compared to some of the subsidy programs that do have tentative approval from the trade conferees
chief among them is a so-called ``triggered marketing loan'' program, similar to export subsidies contained in the 1985 farm law, that sent u.s. cotton and rice exports skyrocketing _ but at a hefty price to taxpayers
the latest proposal focuses on the reagan administration's goal of using the current uruguay round of trade talks to start the united states and its trading partners on a course of phasing out all agricultural subsidies
failure to make ``substantial progress'' on such an agreement by 1990 would trigger the estimated $500 million marketing loan program designed to boost exports of wheat, feed grains and oilseed crops
soybean farmers have been clamoring for a marketing loan program, under which producers receive price-support loans from the government as usual, pay them off at the lower, world price of the crop and pocket the difference
even if uruguay round talks bogged down, the next president could refuse to put the 1990 marketing loan into effect if he were prepared to assure congress that the subsidy program would would harm the international negotiations
doing that, however, would trigger one of the trade package's most expensive and complex features _ an offshoot of the 1985 export enhancement program, which has sent millions of dollars in government-owned surplus crops to private exporters
big grain companies and other exporting firms receive the surplus crops as bonuses to spur overseas shipments of american farm products
the program remains in effect and the trade proposal would extend it through 1990 and boost the price tag from $1.5 billion to $2.5 billion
a presidential waiver of the marketing loan would automatically trigger a new export program, requiring the government to pay out no less than $2 billion in additional surplus-crop bonuses. these bonuses represent a heavy cost to taxpayers because the commodities were acquired mainly through unredeemed price-support loans to farmers. congressional chairman; originally moved in advance for sunday editions as b0698-9</note>
it is the evening of april 4, 1968. the rev. martin luther king jr. leans over a balcony railing at the lorraine motel. the crack of a single shot from a high-powered rifle shatters the air
suddenly, he's gone
this much is clearly documented. but who killed the 39-year-old civil rights leader and winner of the nobel peace prize?
james earl ray, the small-time thief who pleaded guilty, has spent the past 20 years trying to prove he didn't do it. he talks of a shadowy ``raoul.''
other principals in the case hold widely varying opinions: ray's attorneys disagree on whether he was the triggerman; the prosecutor acknowledges he wasn't confident about the case; u.s. rep. louis stokes, d-ohio, the chairman of a congressional committee that studied the assassination, says he still concurs with the committee's findings that ray may have been part of a larger, unsolved conspiracy
the questions remain. what of the cigarette butts found in the getaway car _ given that ray did not smoke? what of the clothing in two sizes in the car's trunk?
the fatal shot came from a communal bathroom at the rear of a flophouse across a narrow street from the lorraine motel. ray maintains he was not in that bathroom when the shot was fired
i was a few blocks away, trying to get a tire fixed on my car,'' he said in a recent interview with the associated press at brushy mountain state prison, where he is serving a 99-year sentence. ``when i started back to my room i saw a police roadblock had been set up; it was about that time that i heard on my car radio king had been shot and the police were looking for a man in a white mustang, the same kind of car i was driving, so i took off for atlanta.''
ray, who had checked into the rooming house the day king was killed, said he was in memphis to take part in an illicit gun-running scheme. he said the scheme was concocted by a mystery man named raoul, an international smuggler whom ray contends he met several months earlier at a waterfront bar in montreal
he also says raoul, whom he describes as a blond man with a latin american accent, set him up to be framed for king's murder
the fact is i don't know who killed king,'' said ray, who recently turned 60. ``i only pleaded guilty because i was desperate. i had been in isolation for eight months in the memphis jail, and percy foreman was pressuring me to cop a plea. he was telling me my family would get in trouble and i'd get the death penalty if i didn't do what he said.''
foreman, the houston attorney who represented ray when he entered his guilty plea march 10, 1969, angrily disputes these assertions
the s.o.b. got down on his knees and thanked me for saving his life when i told him i had gotten the prosecutor to go along with a guilty plea,'' foreman said when contacted in houston recently
foreman, now in his mid-80s, says he thinks ray was extremely fortunate not to have stood trial. he also rejects ray's story about raoul. ``i think he acted alone,'' he said
asked what might have motivated ray to commit such an act, foreman said, ``it was racism. his conversations simply steamed with racist remarks.''
ray, who was a fugitive from the missouri state penitentiary at the time king was killed, denies he harbored any ill will toward king and defies anyone to prove otherwise
king was just another politician to me,'' he said. ``why would i want to do something like kill a big-shot politician, me a fugitive, and bring all that heat down on myself?''
he admits buying the rifle, a remington gamemaster, 30.06 caliber, that authorities say was the murder weapon. but he says he bought, at a birmingham, ala., gun shop, at raoul's instruction and with money provided by raoul
i gave the rifle to raoul,'' ray said. ``if i had been buying it to kill king, you can bet i wouldn't have bought it at a gun shop. i would have gotten it from a fence, so it couldn't have been traced.''
birmingham lawyer arthur hanes sr. said he tends to believe that story. he represented ray for four months before foreman
i've never believed ray shot king,'' said hanes, a former fbi agent and one-time birmingham mayor. ``i personally stood in that flophouse bathroom and looked across to the motel balcony where the rev. king was standing when he was shot. it was a difficult angle. ray simply didn't have enough expertise with rifles to make a shot like that, in my opinion.''
hanes also said he had never heard ray utter a single racist statement
i've given this case a lot of thought, and i've concluded someone assisted ray,'' he added, ``but i can't say who.''
the case should have gone to trial, he said, ``to clear the air, if nothing else. i tried to get the judge to try the case, but he said there was too much pressure, from the government and the memphis business community, to accept a guilty plea and avoid the publicity that a trial would generate.''
the judge, w. preston battle, died a week after ray's guilty plea. however, the chief prosecutor, philip canale, acknowledged last week that, contrary to foreman's assertion, he had been happy to get a plea from ray
it would have been a big, time-consuming and expensive trial with dozens and dozens of witnesses from all over the country,'' said canale, now an assistant u.s. attorney in memphis. ``i have never regretted the guilty plea because we got a substantial sentence. also, i didn't want to take a chance on getting a cranky juror and having a mistrial.''
canale added that although he had no eyewitness and the evidence against ray was largely circumstantial, he doesn't buy the conspiracy theory
i think he acted alone,'' he said, noting that the fbi had found ray's fingerprint on the rifle discarded by the gunman near the scene of the crime
however, supporters of ray's story say his fingerprint was on the rifle because he had purchased it. they also note that, while ray is a lifelong non-smoker, viceroy cigarette butts were found in the rooming house bathroom and in his car ashtray, and that two sizes of clothing were found in his trunk
ray said the fact that raoul often used his car may explain the butts in the ashtray and clothes in the trunk. ``as for cigarettes in the bathroom i can't say because i was never in that bathroom,'' he said. ``my prints were never found in there, you know.''
then there were the two white mustangs. the late guy canipe, whose amusement company was located next door to the flophouse, told investigators he saw a fleeing man ditch a rifle and a small overnight bag in front of his store and then drive away in a white mustang, one of two that had been parked in front of the store that afternoon. he described the man as having dark hair and a beard
ray, who was captured in london two months after king's death, says the fact that the gunman ditched the rifle and his bag _ which ray says he had left in his room when he went to get the tire fixed _ shows somebody was trying to frame him
why would i have dumped my stuff there for the police to find when all i had to do was put it in the car and drive away?'' he asked
after two years of hearings, ending in 1978, the house select committee on assassinations couldn't answer that question. the committee issued a report saying ray probably had been part of a larger conspiracy
but while the committee couldn't say who else had participated in the plot, it did exonerate the cia and fbi, both of which had conducted extensive illegal surveillance and smear campaigns against king throughout the 1960s. former fbi director j. edgar hoover was known to have hated king
fbi agents testified that no evidence could be found of conspiracies involving the mafia, ku klux klan or foreign communists
some of king's friends, however, still feel that letting hoover's fbi investigate king's assassination was like letting a hungry fox guard a henhouse
i have no proof but i feel in my heart that the government, probably the fbi and j. edgar hoover, and perhaps the cia, were involved,'' says the rev. ralph david abernathy, who was with king when he died in a memphis hospital an hour after the shooting
it's just a pity but, given the way things were back then, we'll probably never know the whole truth about one of the greatest tragedies of our time.''
strat douthat is the ap southeast regional reporter, based in atlanta
about one-third of the 185 drug traffickers sentenced to death in malaysia since 1975 have been hanged, a malaysian official said saturday
idris ibrahim, who is deputy president of a malaysian anti-drug organization, said 62 people had been hanged and another 109 were awaiting decisions on their death-sentence appeals
idris did not comment on the status of the remaining 14 people on death row. he did say, however, that 299 people were serving life imprisonment
in 1975, malaysia passed a law under which convicted drug traffickers received a death sentence or life imprisonment. in 1983, parliament amended the law, mandating the death sentence for traffickers
on july 7, 1986, two australians convicted of heroin trafficking became the first whites to be hanged in malaysia
malaysian officials have said about 500,000 of the country's 15 million people are drug addicts
when the clock jumps forward an hour for daylight-saving time at 2 a.m. sunday morning, it means a little more than a lost hour of sleep
people's stomachs will be telling them `snickers bar' and we'll be serving lunch. but if you're an early eater, it'll be beneficial,'' said jeff manzer, manager of the chattanooga riverboat company
the firm plans to serve an easter brunch on the tennessee river sunday afternoon, but the time change ``will probably affect people's appetites,'' said manzer
businesses and services that work on into the night lost an hour _ or gained an hour, depending on the point of view
some police officers who work the night shift get to go home an hour early. they don't lose an hour's pay for their ``early'' departure. and when the time changes back in the fall, they'll get an hour's overtime pay, officials said friday
firefighters who work 24-hour shifts are in the same situation
some churches will hold additional services for sleepyheads and for the holiday crowds
going visiting for easter? the nation's public transportation system is ready for the switch, said fred waymack, manager of a nashville travel agency
at some points there are some minor changes in schedules, but for most airlines, cruise ships and trains, it's just another day on the job,'' waymack said
most of the schedule changes come about because of the season, not daylight-saving time, he said. some flight times might be adjusted one or two minutes because of changes in headwinds, waymack said, and others might be changed to accommodate peak passenger loads
it's really a very sophisticated system,'' waymack said. ``they've had a number of years since the wright brothers to perfect it.''
but he urged passengers to double-check departures 24 hours in advance
at first tennessee bank in memphis, spokesman bob young said the time change would have little effect on most banking services. however, he said, there might be a moment's hesitation when computer operators key in the commands to switch times on the banking computers, automated tellers and other equipment
it just depends on how quickly an operator can enter it in,'' young said
recorded time and temperature announcements must be changed, along with signs at banks, shopping malls and stores. teresa birdsong, assistant to the general manager at nashville's wyhy-fm, said she will have to come to the station at 2 a.m. sunday morning to make the change in the time and temperature announcement computer
bank and store signs are also changed by computer, usually by the owner of the sign, said mark allison, owner of allison sales and marketing
the time works off an internal clock, which you reset just as you would a digital clock,'' allison said
time clocks must also be changed before workers punch in monday morning. most computerized time clocks will make the change automatically, but there will still be thousands of older models that need to be changed by hand, said southern time services technician bill asplint
we could be doing daylight-saving time changes for the next two weeks,'' he said
this is the second year that daylight-saving time will begin on the first sunday in april. before congress changed the law, the time switch occurred on the last sunday of april
strikes, demonstrations and tensions between national groups in two southern soviet republics have quieted but economic damage from the unrest is severe, newspapers reported saturday
official and dissident sources said the atmosphere in the republics of armenia and azerbaijan was improving. but in moscow, activist sergei grigoryants said ethnic relations remained volatile
at a news conference at his north moscow apartment, the half-armenian former political prisoner said he had spoken with sources in armenia who told him tensions have eased there and in the disputed region of nagorno-karabakh in neighboring azerbaijan
however, he said he was told some residents of stepanakert, nagorno-karabakh's main city, remained on strike
armenian activists want nagorno-karabakh, which is mostly armenian, annexed to armenia. at least 32 people have died in ethnic violence in the region since late february in bloody clashes between azeris and armenians
grigoryants said the stepanakert airport had been reopened for local residents but that frequent document checks were being made at all roads leading into the region to keep outsiders away
workers in stepanakert, angered over the kremlin's failure to issue a clear decision on appeals to annex the region, have been staying home for more than a week
official newspapers acknowledged labor unrest continued, but said more people have been showing up for work. in the beginning, virtually the entire adult population went out on strike
the communist party newspaper pravda carried an interview with armenian scholar gevorg garibdzhanyan, who accused the state-run press of telling a one-sided story about the nagorno-karabakh situation and being too quick to label armenian activists as extremists
but he also defended the presence of soviet troops in the armenian capital of yerevan, saying he ``slept peacefully knowing our soldiers were in the city.''
it appeared from his comments that the armed security troops that patrolled the city last month had been reduced
foreign reporters have been barred from traveling to the caucasus region and telephone contact with the area has been disrupted
the national television news program vremya reported friday that public transport and many major industries in stepanakert had been idled by the strikes and urged residents of the area to go back to work
the daily sovietskaya rossiya said saturday that some workers showed up at major enterprises in the city of stepanakert on friday for the first time in more than a week, although the factories were still not up to full strength
an editor who answered the telephone at the soviet karabakh newspaper in stepanakert on saturday said the labor situation was returning to normal in the city, but declined to give his name or details
selskaya zhizn newspaper wrote that state and collective farms in the troubled region had lost nearly $775,000 by mid-march because of strikes and demonstrations. shortages of meat, milk and eggs have resulted, the newspaper said
even larger losses have been reported in recent days due to the industrial strikes in stepanakert, where production and deliveries ground to a halt over the past week
nagorno-karabakh has been part of the azerbaijan republic since 1923, although more than three-quarters of the region's 160,000 residents are armenians. armenians are predominantly christian, while most azeris are shiite moslems
the labor situation worsened in stepanakert in mid-march, when the soviet leadership called armenian agitation for nagorno-karabakh's annexation ``intolerable.''
while apparently rejecting the bid for reuniting the region with armenia, the party and government leadership unveiled a program to invest $690 million in housing and social services like armenian-language schools, literature and broadcasting
the fbi and the federal food and drug administration are probing an incident in which a nurse was blinded by eye drops contaminated with a caustic chemical
her left eye looks like it melted and her right eye looks like it's covered with white glue,'' said richard critchlow, an attorney for aerial van zee miller, 34, of fairfax in marin county
although the clear eyes drops were found to contain a caustic alkali solution, an fda spokesman said friday no recall will be ordered unless it is found that the incident was not an isolated case
miller was taken to marin general hospital moments after she put some of the solution into each eye monday. critchlow said 80 percent of miller's left cornea and 60 percent of her right cornea was destroyed, and doctors do not know if she'll ever recover her sight
cathy babington, a spokeswoman for abbott laboratories, said ``there has never been a complaint before'' against clear eyes
secretary of state george p. shultz insisted saturday on the ouster of gen. manuel antonio noriega but sidestepped a report that he had recommended kidnapping the panamanian strongman
shultz predicted he would ``see a little headway'' when he again takes up his plan for mideast peace talks next week with arab and israeli leaders. shultz called on palestinians to participate in the negotiations, but he again ruled out talks with the palestine liberation organization
obviously, there are some we won't meet with,'' shultz said as he reiterated the 13-year-old u.s. policy of not dealing with the plo until it accepts irael's right to exist
shultz held the news conference after receiving pope john paul ii's blessing at the vatican for his new venture in the middle east that begins sunday evening in jerusalem. the pope stressed any accord must respect the ``legitimate rights'' of both israelis and palestinians
the vatican does not have diplomatic relations with israel nor does it recognize its control of once-divided jerusalem, the israeli capital
the los angeles times reported friday that shultz recommended kidnapping noriega and fomenting a military coup coordinated with the central intelligence agency
the newspaper also said shultz and elliott abrams, the assistant secretary of state for inter-american affairs, suggested landing more than 3,000 u.s. soldiers to encourage panamanian military officers to move against noriega
the proposal was strongly opposed by the cia and defense secretary frank c. carlucci, who labeled it dangerous and ill-timed, said the times, quoting unidentified adniminstration officials
asked if he made such recommendations, shultz said ``the position of the u.s. government is that noriega should go. everybody agrees about that. he's been indicted on drug charges.''
in a lengthy reply, shultz said the panamanian people have demonstrated they agree with the united states in opposing noriega. he said u.s. forces in panama were being increased to guard the panama canal
we debate various possible options,'' shultz said. ``but basically this is a question of a person who is no longer welcome in his own country by his own people and he should leave.''
when another reporter suggested shultz had not really answered the question, shultz showed some irritation and said, ``i never comment on speculative newspaper articles.''
told u.s. officials reportedly had described a kidnapping plot as harebrained, shultz said: ``i never comment on particularly harebrained-type proposals.''
he also refused to say whether the united states would seek noriega's extradition to face criminal charges
shultz and his wife, helena, are spending a leisurely weekend in the italian capital and planned to attend the pope's easter mass in st. peter's square
shultz also held a series of meetings with italian government officials
he praised italy for its willingness to host the 72 u.s. f-16 jet fighter planes that spain is expelling in 1991
on the middle east, shultz said he had no further word from arabs and israelis on whether they would accept his proposal, but ``we expect to see a little headway.''
his plan calls for negotiations to begin may 1 on arrangements for self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinians on the israeli-held west bank and in gaza
israel would deal directly with a joint delegation of jordan and palestinians. in december, negotiations on an overall settlement of the 40-year arab-israeli dispute would open, also with syria's participation
shultz said he would keep working for peace even if he were turned down on his second trip to the region in a month
the problem is there,'' he said. ``everybody recognizes it. and the problem isn't going to go away.''
shultz said after talking with arab and israeli leaders he could ``feel it in my bones there is an answer out there if you can only find it.''
roland dickey once again is ready to don a rabbit costume and take some holiday cheer to area hospitals in his annual spring role as the ``ether bunny.''
dickey, 73, first put on the fuzzy suit and long ears when fellow members of the loyal order of moose asked him to preside over the club's annual easter egg hunt
then i got the idea that i would like to expand and bring the bunny into the children's hospital wards,'' dickey said. nurses dubbed him the ``ether bunny'' many years ago after he fainted on the bunny trail, he said
i was at methodist hospital, walking back to the children's wards, when i walked past one of the operating rooms,'' dickey said. ``back in those days, they used ether as anesthetic. the ether got trapped up in that bunny head and out i went.''
after doing his routine for 41 years, dickey said he has no plans to retire
everybody asks me, `when are you going to get someone else to do it?' i want to keep doing it for as long as i can,'' he said
mr. wolf wasn't taking calls at the bronx zoo friday
neither did buffy lowe, bob katz, bob boon, don key or p.n. gwynne. but that didn't stop many april fools' targets from trying to return calls to those characters
they's groaners, i'm telling you,'' luanne mcgrain, a publicist for the zoo, said friday. ``we've had a lot of doctors calling _ `this is dr. rosenberg. may i speak to mr. g. raffe?'''
for the second year running, the zoo turned the annual prank into a brief fund-raiser. other zoos around the nation use the same tactics with people are fooled into calling on april fools' day
the switchboard answered calls friday with ``nyzs,'' the call letters of the new york zoological society. when callers said they were returning a call from mr. wolf, they were transferred to a volunteer phone bank
they say, `mr. wolf is being fed right now. you have reached the bronx zoo. somebody's played a joke on you for april fools' day. but while i have you on the phone, would you care to make a donation?''' mcgrain said
if they can stop laughing long enough, generally people do make a pledge.''
callers wound up making $4,000 in donations, which new york telephone has promised to match
thousands of dead african desert locusts have shown up on beaches just outside rome, the coast guard reported saturday, prompting concerns some swarms might reach italy alive
coast guard officials said winds must have pushed the insects from northern africa toward italy and that they died in the cold weather
the italian press expressed concern that warmer weather might allow future swarms of locusts to survive and thrive. the rome daily il tempo described the scene on the beach as ``the sign of a narrowly missed invasion, or worse, of an invasion that lies at the gates.''
but experts have said italy will not be hit by the same invasion of locusts that has spread over morocco, tunisia, algeria and libya. last month, the rome-based u.n. food and agriculture organization described the insect invasion in north africa as the worst in 30 years. possibility of military offensive to oust noriega; edits 4th and 5th grafs pvs to conform and picks up 6th graf pvs, but the</note>
the reagan administration has considered a number of military alternatives to oust panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega, but has rejected them, president reagan's chief spokesman said today
asked about a flurry of news reports that secretary of state george p. shultz was pushing a bold military or covert move to get noreiga out, fitzwater said the panamanian problem has presented ``fertile ground for a rich imagination'' about possible solutions
but the united states' intentions are to protect our citizens and our assets there,'' he said
there have been any number of offensive plans raised, but to this point, they have been rejected,'' he added
reagan, who has started a 10-day easter vacation at his mountaintop ranch near here, is closely watching the situation, fitzwater said, as the pentagon prepares to send 1,300 u.s. military personnel to strengthen the american military presence there
shortly after reagan arrived in california friday, the defense department announced that the additional troops would be deployed, beginning next week, to improve the security of u.s. military installations in the troubled country
the reagan administration for weeks has been applying economic and diplomatic pressure to force noriega out of power. noriega has been indicted by a federal grand jury in the united states on drug trafficking charges
fitzwater, asked earlier this week if the administration was considering seizing noriega, said, ``no.''
but the spokesman told reporters accompanying reagan to california on air force one on friday that the administration was still ``reviewing options'' aimed at securing noriegan's departure
the pentagon decision to send additional manpower, many of them military police officers, came in the wake of a march by panamanian troops on a panama city hotel earlier in the week. during that incident, several u.s. journalists were detained briefly, and authorities confiscated videotapes of four u.s. television networks
fitzwater said reagan would be kept abreast of several matters while the president and his wife, nancy, relax at rancho del cielo in the santa ynez mountains
he'll get daily intelligence updates on world situations,'' the spokesman said. ``he could get special information on three or four areas of interest. one is panama, a continuing problem to keep an eye on.''
reagan also will be kept informed of any progress that shultz makes as he renews the administration's middle east peacemaking efforts with visits to several countries in the region
the president also will be briefed on the goings-on in nicaragua, where the marxist sandinista regime is scheduled to enter talks with the contra rebels tuesday aimed at bringing about democratic reforms envisioned in a truce agreement signed march 23
but the political and governmental crisis in panama seemed sure to take much of reagan's attention
reagan has sought to minimize the possibility of u.s. military force being used to oust noriega. last monday, for instance, he told high school students in vienna, va., he did not think the citizens of panama wanted to see ``the great colossus of the north'' flex its muscles there
but the administration apparently has become increasingly frustrated as noriega has survived an array of economic sanctions. these include the withholding of payments the united states makes to the panama canal commission under terms of the 1979 treaties providing for the canal to be gradually turned over to panama by the turn of the century
in another effort to turn the financial screws on noriega, the administration on thursday announced steps to stop u.s. dollars from flowing into the central american nation
the administration is concerned that the continuing flow of tax payments by american corporations with operations in panama has served to sustain the existing government headed by noriega
the first family plans a quiet easter vacation, which lasts through april 10. fitzwater said there were no plans for get-togethers at the ranch by reagan relatives, and it could not be learned whether the first couple would leave the mountain to attend easter services here _ as they did last year
reagan's lone public outing is an appearance monday at a luncheon of some 75 supporters of the reagan presidential library
he is scheduled to make a foreign policy address to a convention of the national association of broadcasters in las vegas, nev., en route back to washington on april 10
mormon church leaders today urged followers to love god above worldly success and prepare themselves for the second coming of jesus christ
in the opening session of the 158th annual general conference of the church of jesus christ of latter-day saints, leaders said service to god and love of christ should be the highest priority of the faithful
we should put god ahead of everyone else in our lives,'' said president ezra taft benson, the 88-year-old spiritual leader of the 6.5 million member church
when we put god first, all other things fall into their proper places or drop out of our lives. our love of god will govern the claims for our affection, the demands on our time, the interests we pursue and the order of our priorities,'' benson said in prepared remarks
the sermon was the first of three scheduled to be delivered by benson, who has been convalescing from a heart attack the past six months. church spokesman jerry cahill said benson, who served as secretary of agriculture during the eisenhower administration, appeared to be in good health and excellent spirits
benson was one of 22 of the church's general authorities scheduled to speak during the conference's five sessions. general authorities are full-time clergy who lead the church under the direction of the first presidency, which consists of benson and counselors gordon b. hinckley and thomas s. monson
thousands of lay clergymen and other church members from around the world have gathered for the two-day conference held in the tabernacle on temple square in downtown salt lake city
during this morning's opening session, leaders stressed fundamental church doctrines, such as belief in resurrection and atonement of jesus and the importance of missionary work
leaders were expected to announce this afternoon that convert baptisms reached an all-time high during 1987. cahill said the exact figure would not be released prior to the afternoon session, but said it was about 250,000. he said the church's full-time, volunteer missionary force also has reached an all-time high of 34,200 men and women
neal a. maxwell, of the council of the twelve apostles, urged church members to prepare for christ's second coming, but said they should not believe the rapture necessarily is near at hand
the council of the twelve are second to the first presidency in the church hierarchy, and assist in directing the church
over the sweep of christian history, by focusing on a few prophecies while neglecting others, some believers have prematurely expected the second coming. today, while obviously closer to that great moment, we are in the same danger,'' maxwell said. ``on the other hand, smugness is also a real danger.''
maxwell noted that a number of biblical prophecies said to be precursors of christ's return already have occurred. among them, he said, is the return of the jewish people to the holy land
l. tom perry, of the council of the twelve, said mormons should get involved in community affairs and promote honest government, neighborhood beautification and high educational standards
rather than spend time complaining about the direction in which these institutions are going, we need to exert our influence in shaping the right direction. a small effort by a few can result in so much good for all mankind,'' he said. cycle designator</note>
an apparent fuel spill stretched about 70 miles down the ohio river today from near cincinnati to louisville, ky., according to the u.s. coast guard
at this point it smells like diesel fuel, so we are assuming it is diesel fuel,'' said lt. eric mosher, with the coast guard in louisville
mosher said his agency had contacted water companies along the river and health officials in louisville
our first step is trying to find a source and secure the source,'' mosher said
there is about a 1-foot chop on the river right now. to contain the oil is almost an impossibility,'' he added
sgt. james hickerson with the indiana state police post in sellersburg said investigators had used a helicopter this morning to track the spill about 70 miles
it's not thick and heavy all the way, but there are traces of it. it's heaviest between madison (in jefferson county) and clark county (across the river from louisville),'' he said
we don't know exactly what it is, some kind of petroleum,'' he said
one report i got from the (police) radio was that it was in spots as wide as the river. they say it is a real thin film, but they don't know if it is a fuel or a chemical,'' said patrolman tim armstrong of the police department in madison, about halfway between cincinnati and louisville
armstrong said madison residents began reporting a strong diesel fuel smell friday night. he said officials at the indiana-kentucky electric corp. generating plant took a boat out to check the river and discovered the spill shortly after 6:30 a.m
consumer advocate ralph nader is criticizing the rise in postage rates and urging consumers to organize and insist on a voice in postal affairs
the new postage rates, including a 3-cent rise in the cost of mailing a first-class letter, take effect sunday. it will now cost 25 cents to mail a letter
nader termed the increase a ``harsh blow'' on individuals and said the postal service routinely hears from businesses and non-profit groups about mail service and rates, but not from the average consumer
nader's solution is to form a group called residential postal action
if we can get 10,000 people to write in, we could escalate this to something significant,'' he said in a recent telephone interview
clearly, there is a great imbalance of representation,'' nader said, and a consumer group ``can help even the scales.''
the rate hike comes at a time when congressional budget cuts have forced the postal service to curtail window hours and some collections
at the same time, proposals to allow private firms to begin competing in the delivery of first-class mail have been put forth
this combination of factors ``threaten the stability of what was once a well-regarded public service'' nader said in a letter to postmaster general anthony frank. nader urged frank to find ways to cut costs without reducing services
he called on interested individuals to write to residential postal action, p.o. box 19367, washington, d.c., 20036
the group could be funded through voluntary member contributions, nader said
pope john paul ii gave his blessing saturday to u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz's new middle east peace mission and stressed that any settlement must respect the rights of israel and the palestinians
shultz, who is on a three-day visit to italy, briefed the pope on his mideast peace proposals during a 30-minute private audience in the papal library
god bless your efforts,'' john paul told shultz as the two posed for pictures with the rest of the american delegation after the meeting
i go from here to the middle east with your blessing to sustain the effort'' to promote arab-israeli peace negotiations, shultz responded
the american plan calls for israel to give land to the palestinians in exchange for peace
under the plan, negotiations would begin may 1 on arrangements for self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinians on the israeli-held west bank and in gaza. israel would deal directly with a joint delegation made up of jordanians and palestinians
in december, negotiations on an overall settlement of the 40-year arab-israeli dispute would open with syria's participation
the u.s. envoy leaves sunday for israel, the first stop on a trip that will also take him to jordan, syria, egypt and saudi arabia. shultz visited the region last month but found no consensus for an agreement
shultz also discussed the mideast situation with his vatican counterpart, cardinal agostino casaroli
progress comes in small increments,'' shultz said, holding up his thumb and index finger close together to stress his point
vatican spokesman joaquin navarro said the pope and shultz have a ``common preoccupation for international peace,'' and their talks focused on east-west relations, ``the continuing grave situation'' in the middle east and developments in central america
the pope ``insisted on the legitimate rights of the palestinian people and on the moral duty to find a solution that also takes into account the legitimate rights of israel,'' the spokesman said
john paul voiced ``great interest in the efforts under way for the search, obligatory for everyone, of a process that opens the way to solutions acceptable to all,'' navarro said
the pope has spoken frequently in favor of a palestinian homeland
the vatican does not have diplomatic relations with israel. vatican officials have cited the palestinian question, israel's unsettled boundaries and the status of jerusalem as reasons for the absence of ties
the vatican also does not have diplomatic relations with jordan
at a news conference later in rome, shultz declined to give details of his meeting with the pope. ``it is always an extraordinary privilege to have the opportunity to talk with his holiness the pope,'' he said. ``i have benefited greatly from that audience.''
shultz was asked whether in his talks with vatican and italian officials he had urged them to play a role in mideast peace efforts
i found very warm support for our efforts and a readiness to help in any way they can,'' he said
shultz, who is episcopalian, brought to the vatican on saturday an entourage of 31 people, including his wife, helena, a roman catholic
it was shultz's third meeting at the vatican with john paul. he and his wife visited the vatican in 1986 for easter. the previous meeting was in december 1982
shultz and his wife planned to attend the pope's easter mass in st. peter's square on sunday morning. impeachment</head>
democratic acting gov. rose mofford has walked a tightrope in the nearly two months since republican gov. evan mecham was impeached, and from all appearances she has enjoyed nearly every minute of it
she's everyone's auntie rose,'' said state rep. cindy resnick, and there's proof in the way children come up without prompting to hug the tall woman with the white beehive hairdo
she may not be the kind of technocrat some people want her to be, but she certainly knows people,'' says democratic house minority leader art hamilton
she moved quickly to calm arizona's troubled political waters after mecham was impeached on feb. 5 and she, as secretary of state, took his office until he is acquitted or ousted. her bipartisan volunteer staff included many who served under mecham's predecessor, democratic gov. bruce babbitt
with mecham's fate up in the air pending a senate verdict on the house impeachment allegations, plus an upcoming criminal trial and recall election, mrs. mofford has avoided any policy initiatives beyond indicating a willingness to consider tax hikes that mecham opposes
mrs. mofford did not seek a place on the ballot in the may 17 recall election, but a draft committee gathered enough petition signatures to put her on anyway and she is the favorite in a seven-way race
a court challenge has been filed arguing that she cannot remain on the ballot unless she files a financial disclosure report. if she files that, she could be considered to be actively campaigning and that, under arizona law, would mean she would have to resign both as acting governor and as secretary of state
god only knows what the future holds for rose mofford, but i'm telling you while i'm sitting up there as acting governor i'm there to serve you,'' she told a luncheon club in one of her many public appearances
besides speaking at building dedications, county fairs and countless luncheons and dinners, she has posed for photos with school children, cotton farmers, mayors, basketball players, lawmakers, annette funicello and mickey mouse. as she goes, she hands out mofford pens, address books and watches
when she isn't making speeches, she can be found flipping through her three huge rotary files for the telephone number of those who are on her list of birthdays or anniversaries that day
no matter who you want to see, honey, you call me _ i'll probably know him,'' she tells visitors
in her 46 years in state government, many of the roles she's filled have had little substance, and there are conflicting views of how well she will do on heavier matters
but a statewide poll released by the phoenix gazette last week gave mrs. mofford an 81 percent approval rating for her job performance
mecham is automatically on the ballot unless he is ousted via impeachment in a vote expected this week. also on the ballot are another democrat, two republicans and two minor candidates
as secretary of state, mrs. mofford's duties included such non-controversial functions as keeping the state's great seal, attesting to official acts of government and handling government publications
the office also keeps records on lobbyists and campaign financing, and john anderson, former executive director of the government watchdog organization arizona common cause, says the state has done a poor job in that area
i think they tried real hard,'' he said of mrs. mofford and the secretary of state staff, ``but the system they used for maintaining any files that i was primarily interested in was not a good one.''
records often were missing and there was no attempt to enforce or have the state attorney general's office enforce laws against violations, anderson says
mrs. mofford was ``not really interested in the compliance end of things unless somebody made waves, especially the press,'' he said
hamilton and other defenders of mofford note that she had to contend with a gop-controlled legislature and was short-staffed, and anderson himself acknowledged that record-keeping improved somewhat with addition of computers
mrs. mofford is divorced and has no children. she began her government career in 1941 as a secretary, and she has worked for or with 11 of the state's 16 governors. she was appointed assistant secretary of state in 1955 and secretary of state 22 years later. she won the post in her own right in 1978, 1982 and 1986, each time by wide margins
her honeymoon in office is in sharp contrast to mecham, who seemingly never had one
mecham became the subject of criticism from the start over errors, news conferences, appointments, hirings and firings, and his cancellation of a state martin luther king holiday established by babbitt
mrs. mofford has drawn little public criticism in such areas, and there also has been little stir over her generally having refused to voice her opinion on major pending bills
i think rose is a very capable person,'' said republican house speaker joe lane. ``she's been very conciliatory toward me.''
she doesn't offend folks,'' said hamilton
a telephone company has decided to print a photo of acting gov. rose mofford instead of impeached gov. evan mecham in an advertisment for arizona, a spokesman says
us west, parent company of mountain bell, has been running a series of full-page ads in the wall street journal highlighting each of the 14 states in its territory
each ad in the series, which cost $1.4 million and started in january, includes a picture of the portrayed state's governor and text provided by the governor. the ads are intended to emphasize the states' strong points and to encourage business development in the company's service area
the arizona ad was slated to run early in the series, which began in january, but was delayed because of circumstances surrounding mecham, company officials said in february
the state senate is winding up mecham's impeachment trial, with closing arguments scheduled monday. the first-term republican also faces an april 21 criminal trial and a may 17 recall election
as secretary of state, mrs. mofford, a democrat, became acting governor after mecham was impeached by the arizona house on feb. 5
now, us west has decided to go ahead with the arizona ad the week of april 18, but with a photo of mrs. mofford instead of mecham, mountain bell spokesman jim cullison said friday
we certainly don't want to offend anyone or step on any toes. we just went with what will be the reality at that point, which is that rose mofford will be acting governor at that time,'' said cullison
father panik village, a giant public housing project once called bridgeport's ``greatest christmas gift,'' has come unwrapped
the mice run around like they're paying the rent instead of you,'' said brenda johnson, president of the concerned tenants of father panik village
people are a problem too. ``they're selling guns like it's the old west and they're dealing (drugs) in the open,'' she said
the project could lose millions of federal dollars if city officials don't follow orders to tear parts of it down, partially reconstruct it, and relocate about 1,300 of the estimated 4,000 residents to other housing in bridgeport
tenants of the complex claim that some of the 41 three-story buildings are in such poor shape and crime so pervasive that living there puts them in peril
i would say it's one of the worst projects in the country,'' said tom sherman, director of the office of public housing in the u.s. department of housing and urban development
several years ago the modernization money was not used properly, and we're afraid the bricks are going to pop off the buildings and someone could get killed,'' sherman said in a telephone interview from washington, d.c
you just can't have a dump sitting there and that's more or less what father panik is.''
father panik village began as yellow mill village on dec. 23, 1939. it was renamed in 1955 in honor of the rev. stephen panik, a roman catholic priest who served as the first chairman of the brideport housing authority and was considered a connecticut pioneer in low-rent housing projects
for it means perhaps the greatest christmas gift that ever was given to the people of bridgeport _ not a promise, but the beginning of a reality, fine decent homes for about 5,000 people at rentals that are well within their means,'' panik said at a ceremony in 1939
today the largest housing project in the state's largest city looks like a battlefield. gunshots occasionally echo within the project and drug deals are routinely made on street corners. walls are marked with graffiti and the hallways smell of urine
at least 90 percent of the residents are single parents with an average of two children and annual incomes of $5,000 to $10,000
the federal government has given the bridgeport housing authority $36 million to demolish 13 buildings, relocate residents to new quarters to be created around the city, and rebuild some units
hud is waiting to see if those directions are carried out before it makes plans or allocates any more money to improve the rest of the project
sherman said the bha has been slow in submitting its plans
we should have had the application for the demolition by the end of december and it's not in yet,'' he said. ``we'll give them an extension, but we're kind of tired of giving them extensions.''
he said if the city doesn't make progress by april 15, he'll recommend cancelling the federal grant
clarence craig, executive director of the bha, said the agency is determined to meet its deadlines
all of the little pieces show we're moving ahead,'' craig said
but so far the authority has located only 10 sites to fit 88 apartments, leaving them short of locations for 251 units that must be moved in the first phase of the project
the problem is bridgeport does not have all of the resources to do things as quickly and well as hud would like,'' said u.s. rep. christopher shays, r-conn. ``it would be very self-defeating if hud punished the residents and city for inadequacies that exist that we're trying to work out.''
meanwhile, tenants of father panik are uneasy about the future, said johnson, president of the tenants' group
johnson, who has lived in father panik for all but two of her 36 years, said that even if it is torn down and rebuilt, crime problems will linger
if they don't do something about the security here, it doesn't matter if they call it mud,'' johnson said
mayor thomas w. bucci said the village is ``one of the city's most important priorities.''
it is known as being one of the worst housing complexes in the country and that reputation naturally is associated with the city,'' bucci said. ``it's not moving as quickly as we'd like, but progress is being made.''
president reagan today urged congress to enhance federal support of scientific research, saying ``we couldn't be where we are'' without such exploration
in his weekly radio address, delivered from reagan's ranch in the santa ynez mountains, the president said that while spending for scientific research is 58 percent higher than a decade ago, after discounting for inflation, this is insufficient
he said that since world war ii, the united states has won more nobel prizes for science than europe and japan combined, and that this country must not lose its world leadership role
he said that scientific research, unlike the construction of bridges, interstate highways and courthouses, has no local constituency. but reagan said the united states cannot let this political fact of life get in the way of continuing breakthroughs
