with 23 more deaths reported saturday, india's troubled state of punjab has suffered the bloodiest week since sikh rebels first began calling for a separate nation six years ago
last week's death toll of 120 has prompted calls for imposing a federal emergency in the northern state and already may have crippled the government's latest effort to reach a compromise with militants of the religious minority
prime minister rajiv gandhi called the appointed governor of punjab state, s.s. ray, and state police chief julius f. ribiero to new delhi on saturday to plan new initiatives against the violence
ray told reporters that the government would keep up its ``relentless war'' against the sikh radicals who have been blamed for more than 630 killings this year
the united news of india said sikh militants shot to death six people saturday night in the village of ragarh in amritsar district, adding to the 17 deaths reported since friday night
no new government actions were announced saturday, but sikhs in punjab expressed fears that gandhi's goverment would declare an emergency, severely limiting civil rights and imposing harsh police rule
this is an excuse by new delhi to impose emergency on the state,'' darshan singh ragi, a sikh religious leader, said saturday at his home near punjab's capital, chandigarh. ``the bullet is not an answer to any problem, either from the militants or new delhi.''
at the same time, opposition political leaders and some in gandhi's congress party demanded action. and three radical groups issued a statement blaming the latest killings on police agents
all this is being done to defame the militant sikh youths in the eyes of the sikh masses so that the movement for khalistan is weakened,'' said a statement from the radical groups
l.k. advani, leader of the opposition indian peoples party, demanded in new delhi that gandhi impose a security belt along punjab's border with pakistan, believed to be the source of the ak-47 assault rifles used by the rebels in their latest onslaught
past efforts to seal the porous border, the traditional domain of smugglers on both sides, have failed
harsh police action, exemplified by the indian army's raid on the sikhs' golden temple in amritsar in 1984, has succeeded only in turning ordinary sikhs against the government
the june 1984 raid to drive radicals from the shrine left more than 1,200 people dead, most of them sikhs. soon afterwards, sikh bodyguards killed prime minister indira gandhi, who was gandhi's mother. sikh radicals began openly demanding an independent khalistan _ ``land of the pure'' in the punjabi language
the killings are spiraling despite the gandhi government's direct federal rule over punjab since last may when it invoked indian law to dislodge the elected state government of sikh moderates
in march alone, 272 victims were gunned down, compared to 215 who died in the first three months of last year
the latest police reports confirm the pattern of random killings with the victims both hindus and sikhs
in the neighboring villages of tara and kaler in gurdaspur district, two sets of hindu brothers, in their 60s and 70s, were shot to death friday night by four men with ak-47 rifles
in tara, about 30 miles south of amritsar, all but two of the 50 houses in the village were deserted by families fleeing the persistent violence
ram lal, a hindu, said he and a few other villagers had been coming during the day to mind their fields and shops. after friday night's slayings, he said: ``we will not come back at all. we are not able to stay here with the terror.''
sikhs, whose religion is a mixture of hinduism and islam, make up only 2 percent of india's 800 million population, but they are a majority in punjab
the radicals argue that only a separate sikh nation can save the minority faith from being overwhelmed by the hindus, who comprise more than 80 percent of the country's people
ironically, some sikh sources say the upsurge in killings results from a new effort by the government to find a compromise with the militants through jasbir singh rode, a 34-year-old sikh preacher
rode was among about 40 sikhs who were freed in early march after being imprisoned without trial. he was promptly elected to the most powerful post in the sikh faith amid reports his freedom was part of a government move to compromise with the radicals _ or divide them
rode has denied there were any conditions to his release, and the government has not publicly outlined its plans
gandhi was asked in an interview published saturday in london's financial times why he had decided to release rode and other imprisoned sikhs
we have tried everything else,'' he replied
chrysler corp.'s labor problems, inflamed by the closing of a wisconsin plant and the threatened sale of a parts subsidiary, are not expected to prevent it and the united auto workers from reaching a settlement in contract talks this month
since chrysler backed down in early march from the planned sale of its 28,000-worker acustar inc. parts subsidiary, caustic rhetoric and threats of crippling strikes have been replaced by silence as negotiators prepare demands and strategies for the opening of talks april 18
the union's demands will be discussed and approved by the 140-member uaw national chrysler council during a meeting this week in kansas city, mo
the talks are likely to be much less dramatic than the unrest that led to chrysler's agreement to negotiate early, since the contract must follow an industry pattern contract established last fall at ford motor co. and used at general motors corp
the framework should be there, and the readiness to bargain early should generally be an admission that things will go smoothly,'' said harley shaiken, labor and technology expert at the university of california at san diego
however, shaiken added: ``given all the trauma (at chrysler) in recent years, there could be a surprise. there is discontent in chrysler plants, a real unease that could come out in this bargaining.''
chrysler's contract covering 59,500 active workers and 8,000 on layoff expires sept. 14. the uaw wanted to adapt the three-year ford and gm contracts to chrysler last fall
chrysler, however, didn't agree until it backed off from the acustar sale, realizing it had opened a wound that would only fester if left until the normal mid-july opening of talks
chrysler's workers agreed to concessions in the early 1980s to help the company survive its brush with bankruptcy
many workers say they are disillusioned because a spirit of camaraderie, of fighting together, has disappeared now that chrysler is in the black and their contributions aren't so keenly needed or appreciated
the average auto worker at chrysler in 1979-81 had no business assuming they were going to have a job there. but they made it through beautifully, the company's done very well. to now have to start worrying about your job is very nerve-wracking,'' said michael luckey, an independent auto industry analyst who has worked closely with chrysler
indeed, 5,500 uaw members are to lose their jobs this summer when chrysler closes a plant at kenosha, wis., that it acquired last year when it bought american motors corp
the union and state and local officials protested bitterly when the plan was revealed, saying chrysler had promised to operate the plant for up to three years, but chrysler insists there was no agreement and that the market does not justify keeping the 86-year-old factory open
chrysler also appears to want to close at least one assembly plant not previously announced and possibly more than the six announced acustar plants planned for closing the next two ye
chrysler also will maintain heavy pressure to produce the most products with the fewest workers possible, said chris cedergren, industry analyst with j.d. power and associates in agoura hills, calif
while vital to all automakers, cost-cutting is crucial at chrysler because its sales depend on keeping its prices lower than gm and ford, cedergren said
the pattern contract includes these protections for workers:
_a ban on plant closings
_job security provisions that forbid layoffs unless sales of a particular product fall and restrict transfer of inside work to outside suppliers. workers who otherwise would be laid off because of subcontracted work or improvements in technology or efficiency are put into a job bank where they receive most of their regular pay and often retraining
_an agreement for the two sides to study jointly over six months ways to improve quality and productivity at each plant, preventing the company from abruptly forcing drastic workplace changes on plants by threatening to close those whose workers refuse
among potential obstacles to a quick and eventually healing settlement is what many view as a loophole in the pattern contract
although the pattern contract forbids plant closings, gm has skirted that obstacle by simply laying off all the workers at a plant whose product isn't selling well and indefinitely idling the factory
in the chrysler talks, uaw negotiators are expected to seek a tighter definition of indefinite idling, a difficult task and one likely to be resisted by chrysler, shaiken said
it would be difficult to renegotiate the ford and gm contracts at chrysler,'' he said
president reagan voiced fear saturday that the united states could slip to a second-rate world power in technology, saying scientific research is ``an indispensable investment in america's future.''
we can travel as far as the eye of our imagination can see,'' reagan said in his weekly radio address to the nation. ``but one thing is certain: if we don't, others will, and we'll fall behind.''
this is why i've urged congress to devote more money to research,'' reagan said in the speech delivered from his ranch in the santa ynez mountains near this seaside resort city
this year, we'll begin work on the great-grandchild of those particle accelerators that have meant so much to our economic growth,'' he said. ``it's called the super-conducting supercollider. and it will harness the galloping technology of superconductivity so we can explore sub-atomic particles in ways we've never been able to before.''
reagan also said that ``we'll also continue developing the space station. when it's in orbit, the space station will let us perform once-impossible experiments in the weightless environment of outer space, and understand our world and universe better.''
meanwhile, back on earth, we will be pursuing breakthroughs in biotechnology that promise to revolutionize medicine, agriculture and protection of the environment,'' he said
but in his talk, reagan acknowledged that scientific research is expensive
some say that we can't afford it _ that we're strapped for cash,'' he said. ``well, leadership means making hard choices, even in an election year.''
without citing dollars-and-cents figures, reagan said that federal spending for scientific research is 58 percent higher than a decade ago, after discounting for inflation. but he indicated this is still not enough
we've put our research budget under a microscope and looked for quality and cost-effectiveness,'' he said. ``we've put together the best program for the taxpayers' dollars
after all, the american tradition of hope is one we can't afford to forget
the problem here is that science, unlike a bridge or an interstate highway or a courthouse, has no local constituency,'' he said. ``federal funding for science is in jeopardy because of budget constraints. that's why it's my duty as president to draw its importance to your attention and that of congress.''
a 25-pound lobster that nearly became somebody's easter dinner has been rescued and will be jetting to maine on monday to live out its old age beneath the atlantic
publicity forced a seafood company owner, a seafood lover, an animal-rights group and the maine department of marine resources into an unlikely alliance to save the creature, which was estimated to be between 40 and 125 years old
also saved from the pot was a 19}-pound companion
this was something that strikes you in your moral craw,'' said gloria felscher-cohen, vice president of the rights group, pity not cruelty inc
here is a very old lobster and it just seemed disgusting that it should end its life to the cruelest predator _ man _ in a pot of boiling water.''
the 25-pounder, equipped with claws the size of baseball mitts, arrived from boston on march 25 after an order got mixed up at hill's main line seafood co. in ardmore
when owner kevin hill recovered from his astonishment, he and his staff dubbed her shirley. then he sold her and the other hefty crustacean to a regular customer, a retired carpenter from haverford, for $287
but before shirley was out the door, the philadelphia inquirer ran a story about her, and hill's phone began ringing with calls from lobster advocates, including ms. felscher-cohen
she told him it would be a ``lovely gesture'' during the passover and easter holidays to celebrate themes of freedom and resurrection by buying back the lobsters
she even offered to top the carpenter's price
after several calls like that, hill was convinced. when the carpenter came to pick up the second lobster, hill offered him $387 for both
his first feeling was `what do you mean they're going to take the lobsters?''' hill said
i said, `look, there's too many people (calling). let's free the things.''
the customer, robert miller, agreed to exchange the large lobsters for 45 pounds of smaller ones, rather than for money
i think it's ridiculous,'' miller said. ``what's the difference between a one-pound lobster and a 25-pound lobster?''
pity not cruelty, meanwhile, had already made arrangements with the state of maine to turn the creatures loose. the group assumed the flight costs
crated and covered with seaweed, the lobsters are due to fly to portland monday afternoon for a few hours of observation
if they are healthy, we will liberate them the next day,'' said lt. joseph fessenden of the maine bureau of marine patrol
they should be freed off the shore of cape elizabeth, by the portland head light, he said
in maine, he added, it would be illegal to catch shirley, because she is much longer than the five-inch maximum (measured from the rear of the eye socket to the end of the body shell) allowed by the maine department of natural resources. the older lobsters are protected, he said, because they have more offspring
his department will probably investigate shirley's origins, he said
the state helped save a 23{-pound alaskan lobster from gourmands last november, he said
that lobster ``was very lively,'' he said. ``i'm pretty optimistic that these will fare as well.''
restoration work on rembrandt's ``danae,'' which was cut and splashed with acid by an attacker in 1985, has revealed how the dutch painter reworked the 17th century masterpiece, the tass news agency said saturday
restoration experts in leningrad using x-rays, ultraviolet and infrared light, have completed the first stage of their work and now are getting ready to retouch the areas where the original paint was destroyed, the report said
a ``case history'' of hundreds of pages has been recorded, tass said
the painting was damaged june 15, 1985, by what officials described as a ``madman'' who threw sulphuric acid on it and slashed it twice with a knife at leningrad's hermitage museum
soviet art officials have said the damage was serious, but never have said specifically how much of the painting was destroyed
restorers, including chemists, biologists, physicists and other scientists, began work immediately on the canvas. the painting depicts the mother of perseus, who, according to greek legend, killed medusa and her head of snakes
soviet art books say rembrandt painted ``danae'' in 1636 and repainted it in 1646-1647
x-ray studies showed that rembrandt had repainted the gesture of the right hand, changed the appearance of the old woman looking from behind the canopy, that he had painted over danae's earrings and beads, and that he had altered her facial features several times in the course of the work,'' tass said
experts also established that the 81-inch canvas was actually two pieces that had been skillfully sewn together, covered first with a brown primer, a layer of gray and then whiting
it is our immutable principle not to paint over even a single millimeter of the author's painting,'' yevgeny gerasimov, head of the restoration effort, told tass
now we are beginning work on those sections where the layer of paint had been washed off, and advancing from the sides of the painting to the four epicenters that suffered most from the acid. we are drawing copies of `danae' to master rembrandt's style,'' he said
the experts also tried to restore the painting's lacquer, which had seriously deteriorated in several places, tass said
the report said experts would not speculate on when restoration work would be done, but that they were confident the painting would be displayed once more in the hermitage when the work is completed
gov. roy romer shouldn't have to look for a new tailor any time soon
thom payseno offered to make a new overcoat for the governor after a denver attorney walked off with romer's coat. payseno is serving a life sentence for murder in state prison
the original coat was eventually returned, but romer said he accepted payseno's offer because he believes it is important for inmates to be able to display their talents
romer showed off the new coat at a news conference at the capitol on friday. the coat is too large because the governor furnished his measurements before he lost more than 20 pounds on a diet
rather than make the coat fit by gaining the weight back, we're going to go alter the coat,'' romer said. ``it's certainly large enough. it's a nice coat.''
ann landers is better than dear abby, but the two sisters both beat out seven other advice columnists by a wide margin, the harris poll reported saturday
fifty-one percent of respondents chose for ann when asked which of the nine did the best job of writing an advice column
ann landers leads among all regions and major segments of the public, but is particularly popular in the midwest, among women, business executives, as well as blue-collar and white-collar types,'' wrote pollster louis harris
dear abby shows strength in the west, and among less well-educated and less affluent readers.''
abby was first choice for 31 percent, followed by dr. joyce brothers with 13 percent and miss manners with 4 percent
harris said advice columns claim a total of 96 million readers. nearly two-thirds of all women are readers, he said. middle-class people and those over 50 are among the more avid readers
democrats tend to read the columns more than republicans, and political moderates read them more than liberals or conservatives, harris found
the poll, taken by telephone march 9-13 among a national cross section of 1,257 voters, had a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points
jeff brown and diane ridley got in on a bit of 18th-century romance when they married in an old blacksmith's shop
brown, 28, a landscape designer and part-owner of basketball's boston celtics, and ridley, 28, came here from huntsville, ala., to be wed by rev. adam barr. the couple met barr, 21, who lives near glasgow, while he was studying in the united states last year
we wanted to wed in scotland for a touch of romance but had never heard of gretna green until adam suggested it,'' brown said. ``it was a neat idea.''
gretna green became a mecca for couples in the 18th century when marriages involving just a declaration of intent before witnesses were outlawed in england. runaway couples flocked over the scottish border to the first town _ gretna green _ and made their declaration before the blacksmith
marriages by blacksmiths were outlawed in 1940
princess anne returned to britain saturday from a five-day visit to australia, smiling cheerfully and looking none the worse after her fall from a horse
the 37-year-old daughter of queen elizabeth ii, an expert horsewoman, was thrown from her mount at sydney's randwick racecourse friday when the horse apparently shied at some running water on the side of the track
in contrast to her fitness, anne's husband, mark phillips, was hobbling on crutches because of an achilles tendon injury he suffered last fall
the couple had been in australia to help celebrate the country's bicentennial
here is the text of president reagan's radio address saturday, as delivered from his ranch in the santa ynez mountains
my fellow americans, passover and easter are festivals of hope. that's why this weekend is a good time for all of us to reflect on the enduring importance to mankind of hope and faith in the future, and nowhere do our hopes take more visible form than in the quest of science
science has grown, and with it the fascination it holds for all us. but as the pursuit of science has become ever more nationally and even multinationally funded, it has also become more expensive. the problem here is that science, unlike a bridge or an interstate highway or a courthouse, has no local constituency
today, when we are witnessing some of the most exciting discoveries in the history of science, things similar to the breakthroughs associated with einstein, gallileo and newton, federal funding for science is in jeopardy because of budget constraints
that's why it's my duty as president to draw it's importance to your attention and that of congress. american has long been the world's scientific leader. over the years, we've secured farm more patents than any other country in the world. and since world war ii, we have one more nobel prizes for science than the europeans and japanese combined. we also support more of what is called ``basic research.'' that is, research meant to teach us, rather than to invent or develop new products. and for the past 40 years the government has been our leading sponsor of basic research
the remarkable thing is that although basic research does not begin with a particular practical goal, when you look at the results over the years, it ends up being one of the most practical things government does. for example, government-sponsored basic research produced the first laser. today, less than three decades later, lasers are used in everything from microsurgery to the transmission of immense volumes of information and may contribute to our strategic defense initiative that promises to make ballistic missiles obsolete
when i think that over the past 50 years the government has helped build a number of particle accelerators so scientists could study high-energy physics, major industries, including television, communications and computer industries, couldn't be where they are today without devlopments that began with this basic research
we cannot know where scientific research will lead. the consequences and spin-offs are unknown and unknowable until they happen. in research, as albert einstein once said, ``imagination is more important than knowledge.''
we can travel wherever the eye of our imagination can see. but one thing is certain: if we don't explore, others will, and we'll fall behind. this is why i've urged congress to devote more money to research. after taking out inflation, today's government research expenditures are 58 percent greater than the expenditures of a decade ago
it is an indispensable investment in america's future. let me tell you about just a few of the many projects we'll fund this year. this year, we'll begin work on the great-grandchild of those particle accelerators that have meant so much to our economic growth. it's called the super-conducting supercollider, and it will harness the galloping technology of superconductivity so we can explore sub-atomic particles in ways we've never been able to before
we'll also continue developing the space station. when it's in orbit, the space station will let us perform once-impossible experiments in the weightless and sterile environment of outer space, and understand our world and universe better. and we're developing new technology to allow man eventually to journey beyond earth's orbit
astronaut sen. jake garn and others in congress have given the space program the support it needs to once again reach for the stars. meanwhile, back on earth, we will be pursuing breakthroughs in biotechnology that promise to revolutionize medicine, agriculture and protection of the environment
we're working on new ways to spread the seeds of federal research. working with universities across the country, we have established 14 engineering research centers devoted to basic research on emerging technologies. and we're planning 10 to 15 new science and technology centers to do the same thing in the fields of general science
all of these centers will work with industry so that what they discover can quickly lead to new and better and internationally competitive products. all of this and more is before congress now. some say that we can't afford it, that we're too strapped for cash
well, leadership means making hard choices, even in an election year. we've put our research budget under a microscope and looked for quality and cost-effectiveness. we've put together the best program for the taxpayers' dollars. after all, the american tradition of hope is one we can't afford to forget
until next week, happy easter and passover. god bless you
former democratic presidential candidate george mcgovern on saturday warned democrats that an attempt to deny the party's nomination to the front-runner at the convention could spell defeat in november
i don't want to see a big, divisive fight at the convention and a desperate attempt to block the front-runner because i think that would bring a repeat of 1972,'' mcgovern told the associated press
mcgovern said efforts by some democrats to block his nomination despite his delegate lead going into the 1972 democratic convention split the party and contributed to his landslide defeat to then-president nixon in the general election
it really cost us heavily. the fallout was devastating,'' mcgovern said
those last-minute, desperation blocking efforts contributed to the democratic defeat in the fall,'' he said. ``we should not repeat that experience in 1988.''
mcgovern's advice to fall in line behind a front-runner echoes a similar call by democratic party chairman paul kirk, who also wants the nomination settled before the convention
mcgovern said a brokered convention is unnecessary because ``the voters are the brokers and they are making it clear that michael dukakis and jesse jackson are the two candidates who command the most support.''
after the last primary, we should rally around whichever of these two front-runners has the most delegates,'' he said
if dukakis and jackson end up in a ``virtual dead heat'' after all the primaries, then the convention delegates should decide which will be the candidiate, mcgovern said
but if one of the candidates compiles a significant first-place win, he is entitled to the nomination,'' mcgovern said
mcgovern said the democratic race has narrowed to ``a two-man race now'' between michael dukakis and jesse jackson
he said neither sen. albert gore of tennessee nor sen. paul simon of illinois is likely to pull ahead, but he said he was not suggesting they drop out
that's a judgment they should make, but i think that if at the end they come up as short as they are now, they should get behind the front-runner,'' he said
mcgovern has not endorsed anyone in the race yet. he said jackson ``offers a message of hope and reconciliation'' and dukakis ``offers a record of experience and competence in government.''
democrats should evaluate both ``progressive spirited men'' and nominate the one with the most delegates, he said
