seamen in the french ports of calais, dunkirk and dieppe voted to accept an agreement worked out friday between their unions and the maritime arm of the state-run railroad. the accord provides for employment guarantees, better working conditions and higher salaries for part-time employees
the workers were readying three idled ferries to serve easter sunday passengers. they join two british ferries that had been carrying the backed-up traffic alone
but on the british side of the channel, talks broke down friday between ferry workers and p and o european ferries and a two-month strike continued
senate republicans are complaining that the democratic-controlled judiciary committee hasn't acted quickly enough on president reagan's federal judge appointees
there is no reason, why we can't with a little extra hard work, hold hearings when necessary and move some of the nominations presently pending out of this committee,'' sen. strom thurmond, r-s.c., said at a recent committee hearing
but sen. patrick leahy, d-vt., who heads the ad hoc subcommittee that screens candidates, denied there has been any foot-dragging over nominations. and leahy told thurmond in a letter, ``your concern is misplaced.''
leahy also said there is no truth to a rumor circulating on capitol hill that the senate would not take up any executive or judicial nominations if they were not received by senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., by april 1
i don't know where that rumor came from,'' leahy said in an interview. ``sen. byrd never told me anything like that. sen. kennedy also told me that he has received no such instructions.''
sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., who heads the senate labor and human resources committee, has been running the judiciary committee in the absence of joseph r. biden jr., d-del., who is at home recovering from surgery
linda peek, byrd's spokeswomen, also said that byrd had not made a demand on the senate's committee chairmen for nominations by early april
thurmond, backed by other republicans on the judiciary panel, complained about what he called ``the extremely slow pace that the committee is processing nominations this year.''
in 1986, he said, the judiciary committee received 145 nominations and 139 were confirmed, including two supreme court justices, 11 appeals court judges and 33 district court judges. that was the last year the republicans controlled the senate
thurmond said there are currently 36 judicial nominees waiting for committee action, five of which are for the appeals court and 21 for the district court
thurmond said some of the nominees have been waiting for nearly a year for senate action
others have been waiting months. specifically, he cited the nominations of david treen of louisiana, which has been pending eight months, and stuart summitt of new york, six months, both for the appellate court; and paul gadola of michigan, 11 months, richard voorhees of north carolina, eight months, david ezra of hawaii, four months, robert roberto of new york, four months, vaughn walker of california, three months and howard levitt of new york, three months, for the district bench
leahy said thurmond had written to biden three times in march complaining about what he described as ``the extremely slow pace that the committee is processing nominations so far this year.''
in a reply, leahy wrote: ``i believe your concern is misplaced.''
he said the committee had received nine nominations to the federal courts this year thus far. he said his committee had already held hearings on 11 nominations with seven more scheduled
i can offer you my personal assurance that, as far as i am concerned, every single judicial nomination that comes before this committee will be considered fairly, thoroughly, and without any unjustified delay,'' leahy wrote. ``i know joe (biden) shares this attitude, and i believe the committee has lived up to this standard throughout his chairmanship.''
a study that is looking at ways to help students enjoy college has found that the happiest students at harvard university are athletes
the preliminary study also has found that too many students don't give enough thought to their major and suggests a need for better advising
the results are too new to have been properly interpreted, cautions richard f. light, director of the harvard seminar on assessment. he suspects athletes are happier because of the social life inherent in their activity
almost by definition anybody in an athletic group has a group of people they become very good friends with,'' light said in a recent interview
the seminar is a three-year, $350,000 project funded by private, federal and college funds. it involves 90 faculty, administrators and students from northeastern colleges including amherst, brandeis, pennsylvania, princeton, smith, williams, mit and brown
among the findings halfway through the project, a student at wellesley college said she chose a joint major in middle east and peace studies after a friend suggested it fit her personality, said wellesley professor david pillemar
another student chose psychobiology the first week of her freshman year because her mother, leafing through a course catalogue, thought it sounded interesting
a lot of people feel an improvement in the overall college experience may not come from teaching the subject a tiny bit better but from better advising,'' light said
the researchers also have found that less than half the female freshmen who entered a science program at dartmouth, harvard or yale graduated in the field, but they aren't sure yet what that means, light said
one interpretation is that is bad _ we're losing talented women,'' he said. ``the other is that's great, they're making choices.''
the researchers will examine 18 separate areas, including the effects of part-time work and extra-curricular activities on student success
and at a time when secretary of education william j. bennett has accused colleges of ``ripping off'' students through poor instruction, the project will look at different methods of instruction, ways to improve student writing and student advisory programs
researchers expect to issue a report this summer. grafs after 5th pvs to add explanation why testimony can't be compelled; picks up 6th graf pvs, on friday</note>
independent counsel james mckay's criminal investigation of attorney general edwin meese iii has run into roadblocks because key witnesses have refused to cooperate with the probe
among those who have erected a wall of silence that mckay has been unable to penetrate is a central figure in the probe, longtime meese friend e. robert wallach
the attorney general's former financial manager, w. franklyn chinn _ who was introduced to meese by wallach _ also isn't talking to mckay. chinn and wallach were indicted in december in the wedtech scandal, one of the areas in which meese has been under investigation since last may 11
former wedtech consultant r. kent london, another indicted in the wedtech scandal, also has also refused to talk to mckay
the latest figure to stand in the way of mckay's probe is swiss oil man bruce rappaport. sources familiar with the probe said he decided at the last minute not to give a deposition in london, where he had agreed to meet with mckay's investigators, on questions of whether meese may have been part of a bribe conspiracy in connection with a $1 billion iraqi pipeline project. the washington post reported that rappaport changed his mind because he was afraid he might not remember everything accurately
federal prosecutors decided to have criminal charges filed against wallach, chinn and london and decided not to grant them immunity from prosecution to compel their testimony
in december, after the three invoked their fifth amendment right against self incrimination, mckay said he might seek their testimony again after their criminal trial on racketeering charges in the wedtech scandal
on friday, mckay said there was insufficient evidence to date to warrant indicting meese in connection with a $1 billion iraqi pipeline plan in which wallach was involved, or a possible conflict of interest involving meese's telephone company stock, a matter in which chinn was involved
meese said he was ``gratified by the action and the statement.''
at a news conference, meese referred to the independent counsel's investigation as ``an exhaustive process. ... when that particular process is completed i think there will be no doubt in anybody's mind what the facts are and at that time i will rest on that judgment.''
when a reporter pointed out that principals in the investigation weren't talking, meese responded, ``i'm not going to comment on any aspect or details of the inquiry. that's something that will have to be determined by the independent counsel.''
sources familiar with mckay's probe have said that although the special prosecutor has not found sufficient evidence to indict meese, he could issue a sharply critical report about meese's conduct
the grand jury will continue to examine the pipeline and telephone stock matters mostly to tie up ``loose ends,'' the source said, speaking on condition of anonymity
if mckay dismisses the grand jury without bringing charges, he could retain his appointment or seek reappointment if new evidence surfaces later, the source said
the grand jury is expected to question meese, his wife, ursula, and u.s. circuit judge douglas h. ginsburg, who was head of the justice department's antitrust division during the breakup of the american telephone &amp; telegraph co
in regard to the pipeline, wallach, who was rappaport's lawyer, obtained meese's help in arranging a meeting with then-national security adviser robert mcfarlane to help boost the pipeline project
four months later, wallach wrote meese a memo that wallach said was based on conversations with rappaport. it said a portion of up to $700 million from the oil pipeline would be funneled to the labor party of then-israeli prime minister shimon peres
that raised questions of whether meese, who has said he doesn't recall reading that portion of the memo, may have violated the foreign corrupt practices act barring bribes to foreign officials
without being able to question wallach or rappaport, mckay is at a dead end
another part of mckay's probe the independent counsel says he has insufficient evidence on which to seek indictment is meese's ownership of $14,000 in stock in the regional bell telephone companies
chinn was involved in the baby bell stck ownership at a critical juncture
meese as attorney general met with executives of four of the regional bell telephone companies at a time when he owned the stock
at the time, the bell companies were seeking to reverse the justice department's position opposing the bells' expansion into new areas of business. meese ended up approving a reversal of the department's position early in 1987
meese says he had intended to sell the stock in 1985 but couldn't because he had lost the stock certificates
complicating mckay's investigation was the fact that meese had signed a transfer of property agreement with chinn assigning the baby bell stock to the financial manager for more than two years. meese initially listed the stock as having been sold on his financial disclosure forms for 1985 and 1986
meese got replacement certificates late last summer and finally sold the stock himself after getting chinn to return it to him
meese says he considered the transfer agreement a legitimate divestiture of the stock. but mckay's investigators are unable to delve into details of the arrangement because they were unable to question chinn
in december, mckay said he had insufficient evidence at that time to seek an indictment of meese in the wedtech scandal and said he might seek testimony from wallach and chinn again after their trial
in the wedtech probe, then-white house counselor meese interceded on the company's behalf at wallach's behest to assist the firm in its efforts to obtain a $32 million no-bid contract to build small engines for the army
the company got the contract following a crucial white house meeting called by meese's deputy. three years later, meese set up a financial partnership after wallach introduced meese to chinn _ who at the time was doing work for wedtech and who later sat on the company's board of directors
senate majority leader robert c. byrd asked americans on saturday to pressure president reagan into signing comprehensive trade legislation
write the president and tell him ... that this trade bill will help you and help america feel proud again,'' byrd, d-w.va., urged in the democratic party's weekly radio address
under a compromise worked out by house and senate negotiators thursday night, the u.s. trade representative would have the authority to impose import curbs on the goods of nations who violate trade agreements. the president could waive the curbs if he thought their cost would outweigh the benefit
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater on friday renewed the threat of a veto by president reagan, saying the bill unreasonably ties the president's hands and that the administration has ``grave reservations'' about it
byrd complained that ``the president has done nothing but cry protectionism and wave his veto pen'' as the ability of the united states to compete has eroded
this is not the time for a veto,'' he said. ``the trade bill is a strong comprehensive bill that helps american workers help themselves.''
he said the democrats' ``goal has been a bill that the president will sign,'' adding, ``we have extended our hand in cooperation.''
the president may not understand what this bill means to the american worker ... i think you do,'' byrd said in urging his listeners to write to the white house
the measure also would impose import restrictions to punish toshiba corp. of japan for a subsidiary's role in selling computerized submarine propeller milling equipment to the soviet union
and, it would require employers to give workers a 60-day notice of plant closings and large layoffs
here is the text of the democratic party's weekly radio address, delivered saturday by senate majority leader robert c. byrd of west virginia:
good afternoon. this is sen. robert c. byrd from west virginia. the congress is putting the finishing touches on a very important trade bill
it is not a minute too soon. our nation's trade policy is in shambles. you know it. i know it. we import more than we export. we send more of our money overseas than we get back. we are losing american jobs. we are losing our industrial base. we are in hock to foreign lenders
once it wasn't so. america traded hard all over the world. the result was money in the bank and jobs for american workers. america ran a trade surplus. ``made in the usa'' was on the product that everybody looked for. americans took pride in being no. 1
now our ability to compete is eroding. for seven years the president has refused to act. ``free trade,'' he says. what about fair trade? the president has done nothing but cry protectionism and wave his veto pen. yet, unless we change the way america trades the tide of change will sweep our economic destiny out of our hands
you know what i am talking about. you see it in the frustration of all the young families who cannot afford to buy their first home. you understand it when american companies take their jobs overseas
america is rapidly developing a treadmill economy; everyone is working harder just to keep up; yet we still seem to be losing ground to our foreign competition. our prosperity has always been built on working smarter as well as harder. yet, despite our new technology and effort to compete, we have been losing the productivity race
for years the reagan administration has left trade policy to the whims of the international marketplace and our foreign competition. the administration has refused to act. it has had a do-nothing trade policy
it is time to get america moving again. the stakes are high and measured in jobs, and in the life style we pass on to our children, and in our vital national security
congress will soon send the president a comprehensive trade bill. we are not ready to say good-bye to the america of our dreams. what must be done to rebuild america's dreams?
first, america must boost its exports. selling more goods overseas lowers the deficit. it is that simple. our bill gives the president new tools to open new markets for american products
second, we must take steps to promote america's long run competitive strengths. we want to see more investment in individuals and in ideas. that means a better educated work force, stronger laws to protect american inventions from piracy by foreign firms
third, we want to give american industry and workers the opportunity to retool and retrain quickly. i have seen the devastating impact in my own state of west virginia where closed factories leave workers and whole communities struggling for their economic future
this trade bill sharply improves the opportunities for workers to retrain, to start new careers. if american workers want to move to expanding parts of the job market they ought to have that chance
finally, this trade bill would prevent foreign investors from dominating industries vital to our national security. america cannot control its destiny if our foreign competition is buying up our assets
opening new markets for exports, giving american industry a leg up to retool, creating new opportunities for american workers to retrain, keeping america's destiny in american hands, educating our children for a prosperous future _ these are the essentials of this trade bill, which the president would veto
in the last few months you have heard a lot of talk about this trade bill from the president. i am sure you will hear more. our goal has been a bill that the president will sign. we have extended our hand in cooperation
this is not a time for a veto. the trade bill is a strong comprehensive bill that helps american industry and helps american workers help themselves
the president may not understand what this bill means to the american worker, to young families who cannot buy their first home, to the unemployed worker who has lost his job to a foreign competitor. i think you do
so write the president. tell him of your concerns. let him know that this trade bill will help america feel proud again. let's put america's future back in american hands
an iraqi pilot held captive by iran said saturday he was shocked to learn how many civilians were killed in an iraqi gas attack on a border town and assumed the raid was a mistake
air force maj. ahmed sakr salaleh, 31, said he was shown an iranian documentary of the aftermath of the raid two weeks ago on the kurdish town of halabja, in northeastern iraq
all of us suffer seeing these pictures,'' salaleh told reporters in tehran. ``i ask god to take all of them to paradise.''
salaleh said he was aware that the iraqi air force had been dropping chemical weapons but added: ``we are under orders. we are officers.''
he said the chemical bombs were dropped to halt iranian advances into iraqi territory. iran and iraq have been at war since september 1980
iraq has denied using chemical weapons, which are banned by international law
iran has said it captured large tracts of territory in northeast iraq in league with kurdish separatists. iraq said saturday it routed the attackers
iran says chemical weapons raids on halabja, 160 miles northeast of baghdad, killed 5,000 people and wounded another 5,000 on march 16-17
the iraqi pilot said his soviet-built sukhoi su-22 was shot down 30 miles south of halabja on march 18 after the gas attacks were over
he said he earlier had released four conventional-explosive 1,100-pound bombs over uninhabited territory when clouds prevented bombing of a road
salaleh said he ejected and parachuted into iranian-held territory. iran has claimed shooting down more than a dozen iraqi warplanes since mid-march
the iraqi officer said he was not involved in the halabja attack. he said he was assigned to drop a chemical bomb into wetland border territory of iraq in 1983 to prevent an iranian offensive there
the bomb he dropped then was put on his plane by a crew in civilian clothes who arrived at the air force base with a truck and trailer with civilian plates, salaleh said
he estimated about 50 planes raided halabja from march 16-18 after the iranians and kurdish guerrillas captured the town. salaleh, speaking in relatively good english, said he thought the chemical-bomb attack was a ``mistake.''
he said one possible explanation was that iraqi intelligence did not know the inhabitants were still in the town
salaleh said he had been well treated since he was captured but had not yet been transferred to a prisoner-of-war camp
he said he had heard on iraqi television that iran has used artillery gas shells but had no confirmation of this, adding that iraqi forces had been issued gas masks
iran has denied using the internationally banned chemical weapons, but has said it has the capability to produce them
iraq has repeatedly denied using the weapons, while coupling its denials with assurances it will use ``all means'' at its disposal to defend its territory. industry</head>
the sale of federated department stores inc. to campeau corp. is more than just a retailer changing hands. analysts fear the $6.58 billion deal may lead to more centralization and less innovation in the retail industry 
when ownership of the nation's fifth-largest retailer passes to campeau, the toronto-based developer will do what it did when it acquired allied stores corp. at the end of 1986: pare the company down, sell its less attractive divisions and keep its most profitable stores
the forecasts are that federated, now a collection of diverse department and specialty stores, will become a centralized retailer with few differences among its various units
the structure will be much more of a chain store company,'' said walter loeb, a retail industry analyst with the investment firm morgan stanley &amp; co
robert h. morosky, the president of allied stores, denied saturday that campeau would centralize buying operations of federated department store divisions that include bloomingdale's and abraham &amp; straus in new york, lazarus in the midwest and burdine's in florida
operations such as distribution will be centralized, he said, but the stores' merchandise mix ``will be determined by the local department store divisions.''
however, loeb predicted that under campeau, federated would consolidate operations such as purchasing and marketing that are now carried out separately by the federated units
the merchandise will be uniform,'' said loeb, who has been tracking the industry for almost 40 years. ``it's bad for the whole industry.''
retail industry watchers want to see what loeb called ``innovativeness and testing,'' which helps develop new styles and trends. when there are more retailers buying and experimenting, there is a greater opportunity for growth in the retail industry
friday's announcement of an agreement between federated and campeau ended a grueling takeover battle that began jan. 25. federated resisted campeau's overtures for a month, agreed to negotiate with the canadian company, and then in early march accepted a buyout offer from r.h. macy &amp; co. inc
the wrangling continued for yet another month, until macy agreed on friday to bow out. but the new york-based retailer came away from the fight with the federated divisions it wanted most, bullock's stores in california and the southwest and the san francisco-based i. magnin chain
many retail industry analysts were rooting for macy to win the battle outright. they believed macy would have re-energized federated's department store divisions in much the way macy has revitalized its own image in recent years
campeau, they believed, was interested more in federated's real estate than its retail operations. the stores would give campeau chairman robert campeau an instant entree into major shopping malls in the united states
the expected sale of several of federated's divisions represents a chance for the retailing industry to move in a new direction, but whether that happens depends on who buys the stores
morosky said campeau will retain bloomingdale's, abraham &amp; straus, lazarus and burdine's, as well as tennessee-based goldsmith's and atlanta-based rich's department stores
campeau has already agreed to sell federated's texas-based foley's and boston-based filene's department stores to may department stores co
federated's discount and specialty store chains and its supermarkets divisions are expected to go on the block. however, morosky said, ``after we comple te our review, we might choose to keep certain divisions.''
campeau wants to sell some of the divisions to pay off debt incurred in the federated purchase and to simplify operations, morosky said
thomas tashjian, an analyst with the los angeles investment firm seidler amdec securities inc., said recently that if campeau sells federated's units to larger companies _ such as may _ it would continue the trend toward central control and ``sameness.''
however, he said, if the stores are sold to smaller companies or to entrepreneurial management groups, it would mean increased competition, which in turn leads to growth in the retail industry
the long-term benefit is to the consumer,'' tashjian said
morosky said campeau already has received inquiries from retailers, existing management and real estate developers about some of the federated stores. he said the stores would go on sale several days after the purchase of federated is completed
israeli troops shot and killed six arab protesters saturday on the eve of u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz's visit to the middle east. it was the highest one-day death toll in four months of unrest in the occupied territories
the violence, coming at the beginning of the jewish passover holiday, was expected to take its toll on christian easter celebrations as well
church officials have said they expect a severe drop in pilgrims attending the traditional easter sunday mass in jerusalem because of the unrest
thousands of christians usually attend the mass at the 12th-century church of the holy sepulchre, where tradition says jesus christ was crucified and resurrected
in bethlehem, army helicopters buzzed a funeral procession for a slain palestinian and flew over the site where chrisitans believe jesus was born
since dec. 8, 133 palestinians and one israeli soldier have been killed in the violence in the territories occupied by israel in the 1967 middle east war
the most violent clash saturday took place in the seaside gaza strip, where the army said a gang of palestinian protesters hurled knives and metal rods at troops patroling a main street of gaza city
an army spokesman said the protesters tried to seize the soldier's weapons, and troops opened fire to extricate themselves, killing three arabs and wounding two
one israeli soldier suffered medium stab wounds and was taken to nearby tel hashomer hospital, the spokesman said. he said another soldier was slightly injured
troops in the biblical west bank town of bethlehem shot and killed a 23-year-old arab during a battle with hundreds of protesters in the winding, cobblestoned streets of the town's main market
troops also killed a protester in beit liqya, in the west bank 10 miles north of jerusalem, and killed another in nearby deir al sudan when their patrols came under attack, the army spokesman said
palestinian reporters identified the dead as jihad assi, 19 from beit liqya and hamis mahmud ahmed, 41, from deir al sudan
the army's version of the clash in gaza conflicted with reports from u.n. officials, who said the violence began when israelis in civilian clothing got out of two cars and tried to arrest a palestinian youth
christine dabagh, a u.n. spokeswoman in gaza, quoted local residents as saying the boy's father attacked the israelis with an axe, and troops who arrived at the scene killed the father. in the ensuing clash, the boy's uncle was shot and wounded, she said, and two others were killed
palestinian reporters identified the dead men as jamil rashad al kourdy, 55, ahmed samir al kourdy, 40, and hassan al kourdy, 21, all members of the same family
there were conflicting reports on the number of wounded protesters. the army reported two wounded by gunfire, but palestinian journalists set the number as high as 13
in bethlehem, a crowd of easter holiday tourists outside the historic church of the nativity watched as a funeral march for salim hallas el shaer, the 23-year-old shot earlier saturday in bethlehem, become a defiant anti-israeli demonstration
after burying el shaer on the outskirts of bethlehem, about 700 mourners marched back to central manger square chanting: ``plo! israel, no!'' and ``allah akhbar'' (arabic for ``god is great'')
as army helicopters buzzed over the square, the site where tradition says jesus was born, an associated press reporter saw angry mourners smash the windows of the municipality building
el shaer, an electrician, was killed after israeli troops tried to keep a market from opening. groups of youths attacked the soldiers with rocks and the soldiers responded with bullets, witnesses said
the army spokesman said troops only fired when el shaer approached them with an object resembling a firebomb
on the 10-foot-wide street where el shaer was shot, the branch of an olive tree had been placed in a puddle of blood. it was accompanied by a sign which read: ``the heroic martyr, salim.''
the violence came on the eve of shultz's arrival on a middle east swing strongly opposed by palestinian underground leaders, who have accused the secretary of trying to crush their uprising
in the latest underground leaflet, released thursday, leaders called for a three-day general strike monday through wednesday to protest the shultz trip. they also ordered riots ``to block shultz's peace plan and stop him from killing the uprising.'' graf pvs ``for hundreds</note>
america's biotechnology industry, hailed saturday by president reagan for its ``promise to revolutionize medicine, agriculture and protection of the environment,'' is seriously hampered by government delays on patent applications, congressional and industry officials say
reagan, in a radio address from his california ranch, called for renewed u.s. determination to remain the world's scientific leader, noting that ``over the years, we've secured far more patents than any other country.'' he cited biotechnology as one of the most fertile fields for exploration
for hundreds of small biotech companies developing new drugs, plants and other products through molecular biology, the issuance of a patent can mean instant success. but the wait can take more than four years, leaving some firms to ponder the risk of marketing their products without patent protection
in some of the biotech examining units at the u.s. office of patents and trademarks, ``it takes an average of 27 months just to open an application file, and another 25 months to award or deny a patent,'' complained rep. ron wyden, d-ore, whose house small business subcommittee is looking into the problem
biotech products have begun to pour out of the laboratories of the 12-year-old industry, doubling the backlog of patent applications from 3,903 in 1985 to 7,821 by august of last year. by some estimates, 11,000 applications are now pending
according to industry forecasts, biotech sales in u.s. markets will total $650 million this year. barring further bureaucratic snags, the industry projects domestic sales of $3.4 billion by 1993 and $13.2 billion by 1998. international sales could triple the domestic figure, officials say
but ``the longer it takes of patents to be issued, the longer we work in a black hole,'' says hubert j.p. schoemaker, chairman of centocor, inc
that complaint is echoed by officials of genentech, which has begun marketing a much-acclaimed drug known as tpa _ a clot buster for heart attack victims. genentech's patent application is still pending, however, and several other companies are planning to market their own tpa drugs
turnover among biotech patent examiners, lured to private companies by higher pay, has been part of the problem. wyden said the turnover was 50 percent last year, though the patent office has created 10 new biotech positions for a total of 42, and recently consolidated all those positions within a special biotech unit
patent commissioner donald j. quigg said, meanwhile, that the office is seeking approval from the office of personnel management to create special pay rates for the examiners, who usually have a doctorate or master's degree in molecular biology or biochemistry
quigg said the goal of the patent office is to process all applications within 18 months, but that target likely won't be met until 1993 or 1994
to encourage inventions, the constitution gives inventors the right to a short-term exclusive monopoly on products that result from their new ideas. currently, the monopoly lasts 17 years
to make sure the invention is indeed new, and not an obvious twist to existing technology, the patent office examines applications in light of previous patents
lack of patents leads firms to hold their products off the market, or to risk theft of their invention if they sell without full protection. since the united states does not publish applications after 18 months, as all other major countries do, the backlog may lead several companies to undertake duplicate research they would not perform if they knew someone else was likely to win a patent
increasing backlogs in the processing of patent applications will have serious deleterious effects on continuing investment and the maintenance of the united states' leadership position,'' said george b. rathmann, president of amgen inc. of thousand oaks, calif., in testimony to wyden's subcommittee
linda i. miller, a vice president of painewebber inc., a wall street investment firm, found in a survey of four dozen prospectuses by biotechnology companies that nearly all mentioned uncertainty about patent protection as a potential risk for investors
she gave the subcommittee charts of price movements of several stocks, up when specific patents were awarded and down when patent disputes broke out between two companies
the applications backlog appears to be growing at 20 percent a year, she reported
with the lack of clarity of property rights in biotechnology in the united states, many companies are developing similar products _ expending valuable resources, both human and financial _ on me-too programs,'' she said
the man who allegedly stabbed two co-workers to death at an archaeological firm and severely wounded two others was a former prison inmate who was apparently hired out of sympathy, police and friends of the victims said
all four victims were ``stabbed with a knife or other sharp instrument,'' police capt. john sheehan said. he would not say if a weapon had been recovered
the philadelphia daily news reported saturday that the stabbings occurred after the attacker tried to rape one of the women who was killed, but lower merion township detectives refused to confirm that
friday's attack occurred in a house where the archaeological firm, sjs industries, examined artifacts. its excavation was federally mandated as part of a sewer line installation in this philadelphia suburb, said bill stanyard, 32, who has worked with sjs
lower merion township police lt. john maloney identified the dead women as clarice j. dorner, 30, of elk grove village, ill., and annaliese h. killoran, 22, of lynn, mass. they were graduate students in anthropology and archaeology
glenn w. sheehan, 39, of conshohocken, and his pregnant wife, anne m. jensen, 31, were taken to hospitals. they were working on their doctorates in anthropology at bryn mawr college in nearby bryn mawr, said college spokeswoman catherine lafarge
police flooded the wooded area, but failed to find the attacker. police also closed the schuylkill expressway, the state's most congested, for an hour, leading to an accident involving a truck on a side road
police were looking for arthur faulkner, a philadelphia man described as 40 to 45. wcau-tv, quoting police sources, reported that faulkner was released from prison last october after serving time for attempted rape
sheehan's friends said he often hired former convicts whom he felt needed a second chance
john jensen, anne jensen's brother, said he had worked with faulkner and others at the site. he described faulkner as a former inmate who seemed interested in his job as a digger
i just couldn't believe it,'' he said. ``i talked to him yesterday. he was a solid worker, he never complained.''
glenn (sheehan) is on the philadelphia prison board and he got him (faulkner) from there or the salvation army,'' jensen said. ``he had been assured that he had no violent past.''
sheehan is a member of the board of the philadelphia prison society, a prison advocacy group. telephone calls placed saturday to the society and the salvation army went unanswered
sheehan was taken to bryn mawr hospital with stab wounds of the legs, arms and abdomen. hospital spokeswoman elaine mcvay said he was in stable condition saturday
his wife was in serious but stable condition saturday at hahnemann hospital in philadelphia, spokeswoman phyllis fisher said. she suffered multiple stab wounds to the back and had internal injuries, but her fetus apparently suffered no trauma, a spokeswoman said
when he wrote a newspaper column about falling in love with the voice at the automatic teller machine, dick ferry never imagined he would meet the scottish woman who recorded the message
but a local newspaper found the woman and arranged for her to come to central illinois after editors decided ferry ``should get to meet his infatuation.''
sally masterson, a 29-year-old scot who hosts a radio talk show in london, is scheduled to arrive here wednesday
truthfully it is frightening ... that she will be so disappointed in me,'' said ferry, an education professor, columnist and happily-married 60-year-old man
i think i'm in love with a woman i've never seen,'' ferry wrote in his feb. 4 ``prairie talk'' column in the decatur herald &amp; review. ``my infatuation is with the talking teller at the money network station at first national bank downtown
i imagine i must have a lot of competition, too, from any other guy who is a pushover for her seductive, sophisticated high-english way of saying, `please wait while your transaction is processing.'''
the unmarried ms. masterson told the newspaper she was flattered by ferry's interest. ``i'd be delighted to give him his money personally,'' she said
her voice, recorded three years ago in dundee, scotland for ncr corp., was chosen because of its ``very soft-spoken scottish accent, nice and clear,'' said euan williamson, an ncr consultant engineer
the story has made a big splash in the british press, which is calling it a ``romantic rendezvous'' triggered by a scottish accent which is ``driving an american teacher wild,'' the decatur newspaper reported
the decatur paper published the woman's photograph and ferry, a professor at millikin university, said he wasn't disappointed
she's an absolutely beautiful girl. and i think i really should have my wife along when i meet her,'' he said
ferry's wife, carol, says she has been teased her about the competition
i didn't realize i was going to be face-to-face with her,'' mrs. ferry said. ``it's a little unreal. but how would anyone feel if a young sexy person wants to meet your husband. i don't know what to say.'' 4th pvs, `every few...'</note>
eight months after they landed to enforce a peace accord between rival ethnic groups, indian soldiers are chasing a faceless enemy
the tamil rebels, who have waged a four-year war of guerrilla fighting and terrorism against sri lanka's sinhalese majority, seem to be everywhere and nowhere at once
every young man is a potential foe, whether dressed in trousers or the plaid sarongs favored in the steamy heat of this tropical island 18 miles off india's southern coast
every few miles along potholed roads, indian soldiers man sandbagged checkpoints where they halt travelers who come on foot, on bicycles and jammed into minibuses
despite an indian force estimated at 50,000 by the indians and as high as 100,000 by sri lankan officials, a ragtag band of tamil tiger rebels continues to kill and maim indian soldiers, massacre sinhalese villagers and extort money from tamils, sinhalese and moslems alike
the indians say there are about 2,500 hard-core fighters in the liberation tigers of tamil eelam, the largest rebel group. the tigers claim there are only 175
more than 8,000 sri lankans, mostly sinhalese, have been killed since 1984. india has lost at least 400 soldiers since oct. 10, 1987, when it launched an offensive to disarm the tigers
the indians sent troops to control the rebels as part of a peace plan they sponsored in july 1987. the agreement granted some autonomy to tamils, but it was rejected by extremists on both sides of the conflict
india, sri lanka's northern neighbor, has a large tamil minority of its own
despite india's firepower, armor, lumbering troop trucks, darting jeep patrols and helicopters _ and allied government forces _ the tigers slip from village to village and even into big towns like batticaloa
in arapattai, 5 miles south of batticaloa on sri lanka's eastern coast, indian soldiers recently checked pedestrians' identity cards and munched snacks purchased in local shops
a five-minute walk away, a man sought by the indians for harboring tiger fighters said the rebels could not be vanquished. ``our fight is reasonable. we must win,'' he said, switching on an electric fan as an elderly relative tended his infant twins
the man asked not to be identified, although the indians know his name and where he lives. they also know that the minute they come after him, his neighbors will sound an alarm and he will slip away _ as he has done several times before _ through the fences of woven palm fronds that make arapattai look like an impenetrable maze
the tigers are fighting for an autonomous region in northern and eastern sri lanka. although tamils make up only 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people, they are a majority in northern and eastern provinces
in eastern province's batticaloa district, the population of about 365,000 is 72 percent tamil. sinhalese account for only 3 percent there, while moslems comprise 25 percent
the tamils say they have been discriminated against in education, jobs and by a 1956 law that made sinhalese the official language of sri lanka. tamils are mainly hindu, and the sinhalese are buddhists
batticaloa, population 46,000, is a town of poor fishermen, small shops and many churches, monuments to the missionary efforts of the dutch, portuguese and british colonial eras
the indian presence keeps armed tigers out of clear sight. but, according to residents who feared for their safety if their names were published, the tigers make themselves felt in other ways
they send notes asking for money. people who refuse are killed,'' a middle-aged tamil said. ``they have people in the banks, so they know how much money we have.''
but that tamil, like others who described the tigers' fund-raising tactics, defended the rebels' cause as a just fight for tamil rights
just because they're militant, they're not unreasonable,'' said one tamil bureaucrat
a occasional land mine or hand grenade explodes in batticaloa near a group of the indian soldiers or the predominantly sinhalese sri lankan police force
sometimes, the indian response is disciplined. other times, it verges on panic, batticaloa residents said
on march 26, a grenade was thrown at the sri lankan police headquarters. no one was hurt by the grenade, but it prompted three hours of gunfire that injured a half-dozen people, including two schoolchildren
sri lankan police officers declined to say whether their men fired, but batticaloa residents said the police apparently started the shooting and the indians followed with automatic rifle fire
the roads were packed with children,'' said the rev. harry miller, a jesuit from new orleans who has spent the past 40 years at st. michael's school. ``the schoolchildren just panicked. they dropped their books and bicycles and ran.''
an indian major, speaking on condition of anonymity, admitted that mistakes have been made. ``there is no doubt there is some confusion,'' he said
the disturbances in soviet armenia may have been instigated by a local leader who was a target of mikhail s. gorbachev's anti-corruption campaign, according to analysts
the local leader may have capitalized on unrest exacerbated by gorbachev's drive for economic reform, known as ``perestroika,'' and his allowance of greater public debate of some topics, known as ``glasnost,'' according to a government analyst
similar disturbances have been reported in each of the 15 republics in the soviet union. and in many instances, the demonstrations grew out of russian resentment of kremlin efforts to help non-russians by giving them jobs and raising their living standards, scholar paul goble of washington said in an article last year
many russians came to the conclusion that what had appeared to be reasonable affirmative action for the non-russians was in fact unreasonable reverse discrimination against themselves,'' goble wrote
that system worked under the late soviet leader leonid brezhnev, who tolerated corruption and widespread inefficiency in the economy. under his leadership, a russian and a non-russian were frequently allowed to hold redundant jobs
but gorbachev, in his effort to streamline the economy, has stepped on a lot of ethnic toes
it is not that he is coming down hard on any ethnic group. it is that he is trying to make the economy more efficient,'' said nancy lubin, a georgetown university professor
ostensibly, the demonstrations in armenia, a largely christian republic, stemmed from armenian desire to administer the largely armenian region of nagorno-karabakh, which is in neighboring azerbaijan, a predominately moslem republic
but the unrest began after party newspapers criticized the armenian party leader, karen demirchyan, said an administration source, who like other government analysts interviewed, spoke on condition of anonymity
demirchyan, 55, named to his post in 1974, was attacked last june by gorbachev, who said that reforms were ``stuck in a rut'' in armenia, and that demirchyan and his underlings showed ``totally unjustified complacency'' toward corruption
reformers in the armenia communist party attempted to oust demirchyan during a meeting of the party central committee last december, but were thwarted, according to elizabeth fuller, a soviet-watcher based in munich
the authoritative communist party daily pravda hinted strongly of a purge in armenia
the absolute majority of armenian working people are honest persons who conscientiously attend their duty, and it is not their fault that the process of democratization and renewal is meeting with fierce resistance of perestroika,'' pravda said in december. ``people yearn for genuine changes.''
the demonstrations in armenia began two months later ``with either the complicity or encouragement of demirchyan,'' said a government analyst. ``we believe he backed them, or encouraged them, to warn moscow that getting rid of him could cause trouble.''
demirchyan has survived the upheaval, although some party leaders in azerbaijan and nagorno-karabakh have been removed
gorbachev's efficiency drive has cost local jobs in kazakhstan, the scene of riots in december 1986. gorbachev abolished the kazakhstan ministry of non-ferrous metallurgy, transferring its functions to a parallel ministry in moscow, but ``throwing a lot of educated kazakhs out of work,'' said a government analyst
similarly, gorbachev's highly celebrated campaign against alcohol has cost jobs in the vineyards of armenia, creating tension there, said the analyst
the ethnic unrest has prompted gorbachev to announce that he will convene the policy-making communist party central committee to discuss the issue at an as yet unannounced date
gorbachev probably will continue to crack down, as he did in armenia and neighboring azerbaijan, ``to show people that they can't get what they want by going to the streets,'' an analyst said
a bus slammed into the back of a water tanker truck on a country road saturday, killing five french tourists and injuring 29, police said
the accident occurred at about 10:00 a.m. when the greek tour bus, carrying 47 french tourists to the ancient ruins and theater of epidauros, hit the back end of the truck, flipped over and crashed into an orange grove, police said
the bus was directly behind the truck. the truck took a left turn and the bus hit it from behind, flipped over two or three times and crashed into the orange trees,'' said a police official speaking on condition of anonymity
the official said two men, a woman and a young girl were killed instantly. a woman died after being taken to the athens kat hospital. seven of the seriously injured were also transported to the hospital, he said. the other 22 injured were being treated at corinth general hospital
the spokesman said the accident occurred near the seaside village of loutra oraias elenis, 27 miles south of corinth
he said the french tourists had left athens early saturday for the 114-mile trip to epidauros
the cause of the accident was not immediately known
officials identified the dead as claude patte, 44, michel patrick, 40, anne eugenie jouan, 9, and marie gabion, no age available. another woman killed in the collision was identified only by the surname dorre
police said all the tourists were from paris
an estonian nationalist, his family and the wife of another nationalist were kicked out of the soviet union on saturday, according to a spokesman for a stockholm-based estonian nationalist organization
mart kikerpuu, spokesman for hjalpcentralen, an organization which specializes in helping political refugees from the soviet republic, said one of the expelled, jaan nomm, held a nationalistic speech in tallinn last feb. 24, on the 70th anniversary of estonia's pre-soviet independence
the organization said this was why he was forced to leave
nomm was accompanied by his wife and two children, kikerpuu said
his oldest son, eke-part nomm, a buddhist activist, was expelled to sweden on feb. 13 along with another buddhist, vello vaartnou
the fifth estonian who arrived in sweden saturday was the wife of vaartnou, kikerpuu said
a diesel oil spill floated along about 50 miles of the ohio river on saturday, and the coast guard and state officials were searching for the source of the fuel
we want to make sure it's not still flowing into the river,'' said lt. eric mosher. ``we're looking for the source and have teams from louisville and cincinnati making bank searches.''
the oil extended from the area of madison in southeastern indiana to louisville
indiana conservation authorities also helped in the search, mosher added. barge fleets, towboats and holding tanks along the river were all being checked
mosher said the water was too choppy for an attempt to contain the oil slick
the spill apparently caused no serious problem for communities that use the river as a source of drinking water and mosher said none of them had closed water intake valves
we're treating (the river water) for some of the byproducts of oil, but the river is relatively warm and it doesn't look like it's emulsifying and it looks like it will float past,'' said jerry ford, manager of administrative services for the louisville water co
shutting down (intake valves) is always an alternative to treating, but when you have oil byproducts that will float on top of the water, normally you don't have that much effect,'' ford said. he noted that the intake valves are on the river bottom
indiana state police sgt. james hickerson said the slick was not thick and heavy all the way, but there were traces for the entire distance
patrolman tim armstrong, in madison, ind., said his department began getting reports of a strong diesel smell from the river about 7:30 p.m. friday, and the spill was discovered after sunup saturday morning
officials were unable to say what effect the spill might have on the environment
it depends on (the oil's) consistency as to whether or not it will threaten wildlife,'' ford said
we've had no fish kill and haven't observed loss of any marine life,'' said sgt. carroll henneke of the indiana department of natural resources. ``we don't anticipate any simply because this appears to be floating. if it doesn't settle in, we don't expect to lose any of our fishery.''
riot police fought hundreds of firebomb-throwing radical students saturday after the police used tear gas to keep the students from marching off a campus
riot police fired multiple tear gas launchers at about 500 students from a dozen seoul universities when they tried to march out of yonsei university after a pro-labor rally. students immediately streamed out of the campus and battled riot police for several hours
no serious injuries or arrests were reported
during the rally, student leaders denounced the government of president roh tae-woo as just another authoritarian regime. they had gathered to show support for workers who want higher wages and more independent unions
labor disputes have increased sharply since roh took office feb. 25, as have protests by anti-government students
since his election in december, roh has promised to better the lot of workers. but his government has also vowed to deal harshly with violent protests to ensure the country's stability and steady economic development
violent labor protests battered many south korean companies last summer following widespread protests that led former president chun doo-hwan to agree to democratic reforms
those reforms included the direct elections in which roh was chosen without having won a majority when two rival opposition candidates split the anti-government vote
members of a satanic cult have been frightened by the paranoia aroused by rumors that the cult was planning a human sacrifice, authorities say
they're keeping kind of low,'' magnolia police chief smithie buie said of the cult members friday
terrified parents kept hundreds of students out of schools in the nearby southern mississippi town of mccomb thursday as a precaution against a rumored list of potential student victims
but an unidentified source within the group informed police that ``they didn't want to hurt or frighten anyone,'' buie said
police in pike county reported a quiet evening thursday, the night, according to rumors, that satanists were to march down a mccomb street before sacrificing a young virgin
we didn't receive a single report thursday night,'' pike county sheriff robert lawson said friday
buie said the cult has existed since at least the 1960s and although its members occasionally sacrifice animals, including cats and dogs, they haven't been known to harm people
the midnight meetings are attended by between five and 20 couples, mostly between 17 and 23 years old, and are followed by group sex, buie said the source reported. new members traditionally are recruited by word of mouth and are required to sacrifice an animal, he said
i think they're mainly in it for the orgies,'' buie said
participants may be guilty of cruelty to animals and trespassing, buie said, but they change their ritual sites and police never know where they will meet
actually, as long as they are peaceful, we'd probably never know what was happening,'' the police chief said. ``also there's a question of a man having a right to his own worship.''
the animal liberation front claimed responsibility saturday for a raid on a large hatchery in what it called an ``easter liberation for life'' for at least 28 hens
members of the underground group broke into the davis poultry co. &amp; egg ranch in rural gilroy late friday, stole 28 hens and spraypainted the walls and grounds, said santa clara county deputy sheriff roland perez
the underground group said it raided the farm because of alleged ``atrocious conditions'' such as overcrowding and disease, according to margo tannenbaum, president of action for animals in san bernardino
tannenbaum said she was asked by the animal liberation front to speak for them. the group claimed it took more than 78 laying hens, but did not say what it did with them
the raid was the second by the group this easter season. it also took responsibility for a march 27 raid on a rabbit-breeding company in hayward, where 73 rabbits were taken in protest over the slaughter of rabbits for medical research, furs and meat
perez said a book on animal liberation was left behind and that the sheriff's department would increase patrols of the area. he said the three owners of the poultry farm were meeting with investigators
the owners could not immediately be reached for comment by telephone. a clerk at the farm said she knew nothing about the raid
in its statement, the animal liberation front said: ``a hatchery perpetuates the most abominable animal exploitation and abuse. we want everyone to think about how these hens live in order to furnish the eggs that are decorated in the celebration of `eternal life.'''
the group called its two raids an ``easter liberation for life.''
tannenbaum, who was also used as a media conduit after the rabbit-breeding company raid, told the associated press in a telephone interview that six members of the underground group participated in the hatchery raid
czechoslovak cardinal frantisek tomasek said in an interview published saturday that the czechoslovak government lost credibility when it broke up a peaceful demonstration for religious freedom last week
the roman catholic cardinal was quoted in the austrian daily kurier as saying that the demonstration in bratislava march 25 ``was a step towards more religious freedom and the government must take this into account.''
eyewitnesses estimated about 2,000 roman catholics took part in the protest on bratislava's downtown hviezdoslav square. officials said 125 people were arrested and later released. riot police and water cannons broke up the demonstration, which had been banned in advance
the czechoslovak government, through this measure, lost even more credibility,'' tomasek was quoted as saying in early sunday editions
tomasek, 88, said the roman catholic church is 99 percent laymen. ``it is the duty of the laymen to demonstrate for their rights,'' he was quoted as saying
the slovak communist party daily pravda charged saturday that the organizers of the demonstration were interested in the church and religious freedom ``only as long as they can misuse them politically against the socialist state.''
according to the czechoslovak state news agency ctk which carried parts of the editorial, pravda said religious activists intended to harm talks between the czechoslovak leadership and the vatican on filling 10 vacant bishoprics
tomasek complained in the kurier interview that the czechoslovak delegation which is to travel to the vatican for the next round of negotiations later this month was ``negotiating in rome about us, but without us.'' the paper said czechoslovak authorities had not allowed him to take part
austrian cardinal franz koenig, in a seperate interview with kurier, praised the strength of religious belief in the east bloc
what the believers in these countries want _ and the pope supports them in this _ is not an upset of the political relations, but the possibility as christians to live their beliefs in a state system which is officially based on atheism,'' koenig was quoted as saying
the former archbishop of vienna said he thought pope john paul ii's visit to austria in june would be a ``bridge between east and west in europe.''
what the pope says in austria will also be heard in yugoslavia, in czechoslovakia and beyond and will be followed with interest,'' koenig was quoted as saying in the kurier interview
