democratic presidential hopeful michael dukakis on saturday blamed arab leaders for the failure of middle east peace initiatives and said he disagreed strongly with jesse jackson on policies in the region
positioning himself for the crucial new york primary in two weeks, the massachusetts governor said that the question of a palestinian homeland should be resolved in the direct negotiations between israel and its neighbors
we will reach out to those on all sides, in all countries, who believe in a future of peace and security,'' dukakis said in a major foreign policy speech before about 600 people at the university of wisconsin at oshkosh. ``negotiations with the palestinian people are possible. negotiations with terrorists are not.''
dukakis has been reluctant to point out where he disagrees with rival jesse jackson on the issues, but he did so when asked about jackson's embrace of plo leader yasser arafat and whether the plo and israel are ``morally equivalent
i don't agree with him,'' dukakis said
that relatively mild statement contrasted sharply with sen. albert gore jr.'s denunciation of jackson's foreign policy ideas in the same area earlier this week
with the speech and a later news conference, dukakis was trying to make certain that rival presidential hopeful gore does not appear more committed to israel than he does _ a key issue with jewish voters who may make up a quarter of the new york electorate
aides denied the speech was designed to respond to gore but admitted it should blunt the controversy about gore's comments
on another matter, dukakis said the united states has the full right to defend the panama canal, and that he does not oppose president reagan's dispatch of more troops there in light of the unrest in panama
first on saturday, dukakis turned his attention to blue-collar voters in the wisconsin primary on tuesday. at a labor roundtable in kenosha, his approach was a combination of competence and earthiness
my friends, this is not a lot of talk. i know how to do things,'' the massachusetts governor told the crowd. ``after seven years of charisma, maybe it is time we had a little competence in the white house.''
twice in his speech, dukakis used an expletive, an unusual action for a politican with a repuation as a controlled technocrat
hell, i'm the only candidate in this race who has ever balanced a budget,'' he said at one point
then boasting about the benefits of full employment, dukakis added: ``hell, they are paying six bucks an hour in mcdonalds in my state, because they can't get people. it's a wonderful, wonderful thing. that's the kind of future i want to build for this country.''
in his foreign policy speech, dukakis touched on a range of issues, but the biggest chunk dealt with the middle east
dukakis called for a continuation of the camp david peace process, which he said was the ``unfulfilled'' vision of the late egyptian president anwar sadat and former israeli prime minister menachem begin
why? because few arab leaders have had the courage to see the middle east as sadat saw it. few arab leaders have had the wisdom to choose reconciliation over conflict, to choose hope instead of hate; to prepare for the future rather than relive the wars of the past,'' he said
dukakis made abundantly clear his commitment to israel
the first thing anyone must understand about the middle east is that we will never let israel down,'' he said . ``for decades, america leaders have know and the american people have understood, that israel's fate is our fate ... that our security interests are linked and that our historical and cultural bonds cannot and will not broken
israel _ like the united states _ is a special place.''
after support for israel, dukakis laid down three other tenets of his middle east policy
the second was the necessity for direct negotiations between israel and its neighbors
third was a continuation of the camp david understandings on the future of the west bank and the gaza strip
that framework recognizes the right of the people of the territories to shape their own destiny in a way that is consistent with israel's right to exist within safe and security and recognized borders,'' he said
and fourth, dukakis condemned the soviet union and china for continuing a major flow of arms into the middle east, particularly china's sale of medium-range missiles to saudi arabia
dukakis did not mention his dispute with gore over a letter 30 u.s. senators signed on march 3, encouraging secretary of state george shultz to pursue his peace plan and criticizing israeli leaders for not cooperating with the effort
on central america, dukakis praised the progress toward peace in the region, castigating the reagan administration for being unable to ``cope with the threat of peace'' there
dukakis also brought up u.s. policy toward south africa where he declared the president must ``say `no' to apartheid; `no' to racism; ``no to doing business with south africa.''
china's liberal economic reforms have caused a major increase in economic crimes, debt cases and divorce, the president of the supreme people's court said saturday
zheng tianxiang told the national people's congress, china's legislature, that since a crackdown on white-collar crime began in 1983 about 760,000 people have been sentenced to punishments ranging from a jail term of five years to execution
he also said there were 547,000 divorce cases last year, almost half the 1.2 million civil cases heard
china's reforms, started in 1976 after the fall of the ultra-leftist gang of four, have loosened state controls over business and opened the nation to foreign influences
but they also have prompted the ``corrupt and ugly'' phenomenon of nouveau riche ``upstarts who use money to seduce or philander with women, and even take concubines,'' zheng said
in addition, bribery, embezzlement and speculation have become commonplace, he said
from august 1983 to the end of 1987, the nation's courts passed judgment on 2 million people for white-collar crime. about 38 percent, or 760,000, received sentences of at least five years in jail, he said
last year the number of criminals given sentences of 10 years or more for such crimes more than doubled, zheng said, although he did not provide figures
zheng said that of the offenders since 1983, government employees made up 15 percent while 28 percent were factory workers
zheng did not say how many people were sentenced to die
foreign analysts have estimated that more than 10,000 people have been executed since 1983, but china has never released figures on capital punishment. it is unclear how many people were executed for white-collar crime
zheng said the growth of nongovernmental loans, many without written contracts and with high interest rates, has led to a sharp jump in debt cases. last year, there were 256,000 cases, eight times the 1983 figure
divorce cases are also up, he said, partly because women have become more economically independent under the government's reform policies
some women with greater economic means ``cannot bear the bond of arranged marriage or maltreatment by their husband, thus demanding divorces. their demand is progressive and the people's courts give them full support according to law,'' he said
in a separate speech, yang yichen, head of the supreme people's procuratorate, or prosecutor's office, said 1,500 leading officials had been prosecuted over the past five years for such crimes as tax evasion, trademark counterfeits and manufacturing fake and faulty commodities
zheng said the courts continued to deal with cases of people wronged during the leftist anarchy of the 1966-76 cultural revolution. he said courts had taken up 789,000 related criminal cases, and new verdicts were given in 286,000 cases
an organization of libyan exiles opposed to libyan leader col. moammar gadhafi said saturday an army officer had defected and denounced ``gadhafi's bloody rule.''
the statement was distributed by the cairo-based national front for the salvation of libya _ nfsl
it said libyan lt. col. abdallah ahmed khaled al-sheikhy had joined the nfsl because it is ``the honorable force struggling to overthrow gahafi's bloody rule.''
the statement was not signed by the officer and there was no way to independently verity the claim
the nfsl has reported two other defections of libyan colonels in the past nine days, but did not say where the officers were
a salvation of libya statement on march 30 was signed by col. saleh mohammed and said he had joined the nfsl
five days earlier, a statement said the chief of libya's forces in chad, col. khalifah abu el-kassem haftar, had defected to the nfsl. the statement gave no details but an nfsl spokesman said haftar had been a prisoner of war in chad
libya claims a large zone of northern chad and the dispute has provoked frequent battles between the north african neighbors. gadhafi also backs chadian rebel forces
the 500-foot highway of steel over the little missouri river is more than just a bridge to this small village on the fort berthold indian reservation
this one possesses personality, they say, so much so they refer to it by name _ lost bridge
the 20-foot-wide, three-span truss bridge was erected in 1929 when it only connected two dusty cattle trails, said bill jennings, assistant bridge engineer for the state highway department
they built a bridge that had no access to it,'' said lisa redford, a spokesman for mandaree inc
now that state highway 22 crosses the bridge, the state wants to build a replacement, and mandaree inc. hopes to preserve the old span as a focus for development
people old enough to remember its origin are still baffled. ``i don't even know why they built it,'' fred lone fight said
nobody used lost bridge before garrison dam was built downstream in the 1950s and lake sakakawea blocked many roads, pamela black hawk recalled
eventually, highway 22 became a paved ribbon of asphalt and the bridge, part of the shortest western route around the lake, got far more use. the state wants to replace it with a modern bridge that's 16 feet wider and can carry heavier loads, jennings said
so the state is searching for a buyer for the steel structure and is offering $50,000 to aid in moving it. if no one takes the bridge, it will be torn down
mandaree inc. is exploring the possibility of essentially adopting the bridge. the group envisions using it for a fishing site, the focal point of a place for prairie-weary travelers to stop for rest or a picnic, said redford
that would preserve lost bridge for its historic and sentimental importance, she said
the bridge sits 10 miles south of mandaree in a picturesque valley of rolling river bluffs that are void of any man-made structures except for the highway itself and an occasional highway sign
driving into the valley, the sun-drenched metal bridge glistens as it stands against a backdrop of prairie grass
any group that agrees to preserve the bridge gets at least $50,000 _ the estimated expense for tearing it down _ from the state, jennings said
the deadline for assuming ownership of bridge is november, he said. mandaree inc. hopes to make a decision within the next few weeks, redford said
we are looking right now into the liabilities and what the federal guidelines call for in maintaining a (historic) bridge,'' said redford
the history is what makes it unique,'' jennings said. ``the fact they call it a lost bridge.''
a new bridge just west of lost bridge will cost an estimated $1 million, he said. the state hopes to begin construction in 1990
in the early 1970s, the state tried to give away a rainbow-arch bridge over the cannonball river but found no takers, jennings recalled
they took a lot of pictures, wrote up quite a documentary on it, and destroyed the bridge,'' he said. than seats</head>
china's legislature blew a small breath of democracy into the government on saturday by approving a bill that for the first time allows candidates to compete for seats on its standing committee
from now on, the 2,794 delegates to the national people's congress will elect its 155-member standing committee
as before, 20 candidates, including the chairman and vice chairmen, will be chosen by the congress' ruling presidium and elected without opposition, but now 144 candidates will compete for the other 135 seats
deputies can vote against a candidate or abstain, but the 20 without opposition can be defeated only if they get fewer than half of votes cast
only two delegates opposed and one abstained in the vote to approve the procedure
the congress ruled out more than one candidate for such posts as president and vice president, congress chairman, chairman of the central military commission and president of the supreme people's court
it said the presidium will fill those key posts ``in line with the opinions of the majority of deputies.''
the presidium will also elect the premier, vice premiers, ministers, state councilors and other government officers, with a single candidate for each post submitted by the president
acting premier li peng is certain to be formally named head of government
china says the current session of the congress has been the most open and democratic ever. official newspapers and national television have spotlighted debate among the delegates and speeches voicing opposition to various policies
still, the communist party and its governing politburo remain in firm control over decisions of policy and personnel. the congress' main function is still to rubber-stamp moves by the party. insert two grafs after 5th graf pvs: a tenuous .... pick up 6th graf pvs: kuwait's ruler...</note>
iraq said saturday its forces killed thousands of iranian troops and overran bases of iranian-backed kurdish rebels in mountainous northeastern iraq
iranian warplanes bombed an iraqi garrison in the region, tehran radio reported, but iran's news media had no immediate comment on the iraqi victory claim
iran's islamic republic news agency reported that iraqi forces were leveling the kurdish town of seyyed sadiq in sulaymaniyah province and its inhabitants were seeking refuge in nearby towns
kurdish separatist leader jalal talabani confirmed there was heavy fighting and said iraq was ``waging a genocide campaign against our people through the daily use of poison gas.''
a tenuous halt in the ``war of the cities'' held as iraq continued to silence its long-range missile launchers for the duration of a trip to baghdad by turkish prime minister turgut ozal. iran did not report any attacks on civilian targets either
iraqi foreign minister tariq aziz reaffirmed his nation's readiness to continue the halt even after ozal returns to turkey, probably sunday evening, the iraqi news agency reported
but it quoted him as saying the truce would continue only if iran accepted several iraqi demands, including an iranian withdrawal from iraqi territory, that iran has repeatedly scoffed at
kuwait's ruler issued a new appeal to iran to end the war with iraq through negotiations
baghdad radio quoted a high command communique as saying iraqi troops ``completely purged'' the area around qara dagh in the sulaymaniyah region of iraq in the last two weeks
qala dagh is only 20 miles west of lake darbandikhan, where iranian revolutionary guards have thrust into iraq in a 16-day-old offensive
the iraqi news agency quoted its correspondent as saying thousands of iranians were killed. he did not give figures for casualties among the kurdish guerrillas
the correspondent also specifically denied a report, carried friday by the associated press, that kurdish rebels were within five miles of a major highway linking sulaymaniyah with other iraqi cities
the communique quoted by baghdad radio said ``all traitors have finally been destroyed,'' in a reference to the iranian-backed kurdish rebels who have been fighting baghdad for an independent homeland for years
it said an iraqi force, including kurdish fighters loyal to baghdad, had overrun 21 kurdish bases and villages used by the guerrillas in the last few days
tehran radio said iranian warplanes bombed an iraqi garrison at shanandari, in the heart of the area of hostilities, ``inflicting heavy losses and damage.''
talabani, leader of one of the two main kurdish rebel groups, the patriotic union of kurdistan, said an iraqi chemical attack on the village of seo-o-saru earlier last week killed 60 kurdish villagers and wounded 211
they are now resorting to a scorched-earth policy, killing defenseless women and children indiscriminately and destroying whole villages,'' he said in london on friday
irna reported that iranian troops who were nearby heard ``several huge explosions'' coming from seyyed sadiq on saturday and ``many buildings in the iraqi town have been demolished.''
it said groups of inhabitants were escaping from the town to nearby towns and villages
massud barzani, leader of the other big rebel group, the kurdish democratic party, had said several days ago that the iraqi army launched a major offensive against the guerrillas march 23
he said two divisions of troops, backed by tanks, artillery and air strikes, were seeking to dislodge rebel fighters and their allies, the patriotic union of kurdistan, from the qara dagh mountains between kirkuk and the provincial capital of sulaymaniyah
an iraqi division usually numbers about 12,000 men
the villages are north of the iranian bridgehead around lake darbandikhan, where iran claims iraqi chemical bombing attacks march 16-17 on ``liberated'' kurdish towns killed 5,000 civilians and injured 5,000 more
kuwait's ruler, sheik jaber al-ahmed al-sabah, said in an address at the inauguration of the sixth conference of arab justice ministers, ``judging by islamic and arab history, we find that inter-islamic wars did not provide any radical solution to problems.''
he called on iran ``to abide by the islamic teachings, stick to good neighborliness and accept reconciliation and dialogue instead of aggression and the continuation of war and destruction.''
sheik jaber's peace appeal came only three days after three iranian gunboats opened fire on a military post on kuwait's bubiyan island, wounding two kuwaiti soldiers
the daring prison escape of the leader of the august coup attempt raised new doubts about military leadership under president corazon aquino's government
the flight saturday of former lt. col. gregorio ``gringo'' honasan, with 14 prison guards from an elite navy unit, came four days after the military boasted of the arrest of seven top communist rebels
how was it possible, because he was on a ship and under guard?'' sen. juan ponce enrile said of the escape. ``how could it happen?''
honasan, 39, served as security chief when enrile, now an opposition leader, was minister of defense
before dawn saturday, honasan fled the prison ship where he had been held since his capture in december. the 14 officers from the navy's special warfare unit were supposed to be guarding him, but they fled with him
honasan and the guards escaped under gunfire from other guards and reached shore in two rubber dinghies a few hundred yards from navy headquarters
in what may be worse for the military's image, spokesman col. oscar florendo acknowledged the armed forces learned last week of a possible escape attempt and had doubled the guard force on the ship. the dinghies had come with the increased security
mrs. aquino announced saturday that the vessel's commander, lt. cmdr. fred tuvilla, had been arrested and may face court-martial for negligence
she also threatened to punish any soldiers who help honasan. he and other military dissidents were responsible for six major coup plots against her government
florendo said honasan was apt to try to organize new plots against the government and to divide the 160,000-member military. the charismatic former colonel remains widely admired in the military even though he was dismissed after his aug. 28 coup attempt left at least 53 people dead
his escape was widely reported saturday in the filipino media, which normally curtail operations on easter weekend. scores of callers to manila radio stations questioned how honasan could have escaped without the help of the guards
military chief of staff gen. renato de villa told reporters saturday he accepted responsibility for the escape but would let mrs. aquino decide whether he should be relieved
somehow, in one way or another, i bear responsibility for ensuring that our detainees are secured and procedures are followed,'' he said
last month, the congressional commission on appointments approved de villa's nomination as chief of staff
the move came despite opposition from some congressmen who felt the former constabulary commander should have retired instead. critics said extending his tour of duty limited promotion of younger officers and smacked of practices under ousted president ferdinand marcos
the escape also raised doubts whether the congressional commission would approve the recent nomination of adm. carlito cunanan, former chief of the coast guard, as navy commander
congressional sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said they already had misgivings about cunanan because of the coast guard's inept handling of rescue efforts in a december collision of a filipino passenger ship and oil tanker that killed 3,000 people
the escape took place as the military was enjoying new prestige for tuesday's arrest of seven leading communists, including romulo kintanar, commander of the rebel new people's army
defense secretary fidel ramos had said the arrests showed that the military had overcome past divisions and could now act effectively
but on saturday, he called the escape ``disturbing news.''
de villa said the search for honasan, moreover, would divert military resources from the fight against the rebels
one filipino politician also worried about the international impact of honasan's escape. sen. john osmena said it was bound to tarnish the government's image abroad and raise more doubts about the stability of the aquino administration
