massachusetts gov. michael dukakis held a narrow lead over the rev. jesse jackson in the week leading up to tuesday's wisconsin presidential primary, according to a newspaper poll published sunday
dukakis held a 43 percent to 35 percent lead over jackson among voters who said they would vote for, or leaned toward, a democratic candidate if the primary had been held at the time of the poll, the milwaukee journal reported in its sunday editions
in a poll two weeks earlier, dukakis led jackson by 38 percent to 30 percent, the newspaper reported
sen. albert gore jr., of tennessee, made the largest gain in the two-week period between polls, increasing his support from 10 percent to 15 percent, the newspaper said
despite campaigning heavily in wisconsin, sen. paul simon of illinois slipped from 11 percent support to 5 percent in the two weeks, the newspaper said
simon has pinned his fading presidential prospects on wisconsin, hoping that a victory in the primary would give him a boost going into next week's primary in new york
on the republican side, the poll showed vice president george bush would easily defeat his remaining primary challenger, former television evangelist pat robertson but might have a difficult time winning wisconsin in the general election if dukakis were the democratic nominee
bush held an 80 percent to 7 percent lead over robertson, the poll showed
however, bush and dukakis ended in a virtual tie among voters who were asked which of the two they would likely vote for in the general election in november
in similar matchups, bush held a 5 point lead over gore and a 14 point lead over jackson, the newspaper said
the poll was conducted wednesday and thursday and was based on interviews with 845 randomly-selected wisconsin adults who said they were absolutely or fairly certain to vote in the primary, the newspaper said. the margin of error was plus or minus 5 percentage points
the wisconsin primary is expected to draw a large voter turnout with as many as 1.6 million voters or 45 percent of the eligible voters participating, state elections board officials said
this week's expected verdict in gov. evan mecham's impeachment trial won't necessarily end the legal morass that surrounds the arizona governorship
the senate plans to vote monday or tuesday on whether mecham, a first-term republican, should be the first arizona governor removed from office
senators heard five weeks of testimony on allegations that mecham misused $80,000 in state money by loaning it to his auto dealership, and that he tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official
with 20 of the 30 senate votes required for conviction, nobody is predicting what will happen
if he is acquitted, mecham will automatically regain the gubernatorial powers he gave up to acting gov. rose mofford, the democratic secretary of state, when he was impeached by the house feb. 5
if the senate convicts him on either count, mecham will be removed from office immediately
in either event, the matter won't necessarily end there
if acquitted, mecham faces two more battles to keep the governorship
a criminal trial is due to start april 21 on a charge similar to one impeachment charge the senate dropped: failure to report a $350,000 campaign loan. the governor faces six felony counts of fraud, perjury and filing false documents, and his brother and 1986 campaign treasurer, willard mecham, faces three similar counts
senators who voted to drop the impeachment count said they feared that if they heard evidence on the charge it would jeopardize mecham's right to a fair trial
if convicted in the criminal trial, mecham would be removed from office automatically and could face up to 22 years in prison
mecham also is running against six candidates in a recall election may 17. polls vary widely, with some showing him far behind but one putting mecham and mrs. mofford in a dead heat for first place
if the senate votes to oust him, the governor and his defense attorney, jerris leonard, say they could appeal to the u.s. supreme court on grounds that mecham's constitutional rights were violated
it's also unclear whether the may 17 recall must be held if the state senate convicts mecham on the impeachment charges
attorney general bob corbin, a republican, said friday he believes the recall still must be held because the arizona constitution says a recall is aimed at the office, not the officeholder
however, corbin said he philosophically opposes holding the recall if mecham has already been removed
i don't think our founding fathers who drafted the constitution ever dreamed we would be in this position,'' he said
this and other remaining legal questions should be settled in court, corbin said
if the recall were to go ahead following a senate conviction, officials say it's also unclear whether mecham would be allowed to run
he has an automatic spot on the ballot, but paul bender, dean of the arizona state university law school, argues that a senate vote to remove him would apply to the entire four-year term and he could not remain in office even if he won the recall vote
legal questions surround mrs. mofford's gubernatorial candidacy too. a campaign was formed to draft her because arizona's ``resign to run'' law apparently would require her to quit as acting governor and secretary of state if she declared her candidacy
a court challenge has been mounted to see if the mofford draft campaign was handled properly, without any involvement by the intended candidate
corbin said his office warned years ago that the laws were unclear and should be straightened out, ``and nobody has, so here we are.'' picks up 5th graf pvs, bgng: some 18,000...</note>
jesse jackson overwhelmed michael dukakis in democratic party caucuses saturday to win three of the virgin islands' delegate votes at the national convention
party vice chairman st. claire williams said jackson got 634 votes while dukakis trailed with only 37 votes. they were the only two candidates on the caucus ballot
six people, each casting one-half vote at the convention, were chosen in the caucuses held on the islands of st. thomas and st. croix
some 18,000 registered democrats live in this u.s. territory, whose three major islands are st. thomas, st. croix and st. john
st. john democrats traveled to st. thomas to attend the caucus
saturday's caucuses were the only step in the democrats' process to pick national convention delegates from the virgin islands. party members register their support by showing up at a caucus site and filling out a sign-in sheet, which is similar to casting a ballot in a primary
in addition to the six people being selected saturday, four members of the democratic national committee from the virgin islands, including gov. alexander farrelly, automatically will be delegates to the democratic national convention in atlanta july 18-21. those four dnc members each cast one-quarter vote at the convention
in all, the virgin islands' delegation will cast four votes at the national convention
republicans in the u.s. virgin islands pick their four national convention delegates at a territorial convention on may 21
while suds, sun and sin may prevail among much of the spring break throngs on the wide beaches of daytona this easter weekend, morning devotions replace hangovers in at least three beach hotels
daytona beach has become a mecca for spring break in recent years, and an estimated 500,000 students descend on the area to forget classwork and laze in the sun. but it's not all rowdy parties and promiscuity
at the beachfront el caribe hotel, students carry bibles through the lobby. the hotel caters to members of the campus crusade for christ, a national interdenominational group
you can only get so drunk and sunburned and bored,'' said cliff mills, director of operation sonshine of the campus crusade. ``a lot of them want to know more about christ.''
mills, whose organization has conducted conferences for some 3,000 students during spring break, said campus crusade members take their gospel message to the beach in the afternoons and that sun worshipers are often receptive
el caribe does not allow unchaperoned non-member students under 21 to rent rooms during spring break
the difference is day and night,'' said el caribe owner mary ann richardson, explaining how students in her hotel act compared with students staying at the dozens of other beach hotels
ms. richardson said the biggest problem in her hotel is minor noise making, and that the students are generally well-behaved and polite
the situation was much the same at the desert inn and the high seas motel, also spring break gathering places for campus crusade members
there was no muss, no fuss and no beer-bottle throwing,'' said anne madorsky, a part-owner of the desert inn, the voyager and americana hotels
many of the crowds at daytona used to go to fort lauderdale before that community began to try to change its image with stricter law enforcement
officials in fort lauderdale have estimated their crowds will range between 100,000 and 200,000 this year, compared with 350,000 in 1985
daytona officials say this spring break, students generally have behaved better than in the past, when hotel guests tossed such objects as unopened beer cans, room chairs and even rollaway beds from balconies
so far this year, there have been two spring break fatalities in daytona, one a 24-year-old man, not a student, who fell from a balcony, the other a 21-year-old student who was hit by a car
there were five other balcony falls this year in daytona, but only two of the six involved students and most resulted in only minor injuries. in the past three years, six deaths have resulted from balcony accidents
in the florida panhandle, two spring break visitors were hospitalized after balcony falls friday in destin, a gulf coast resort town
david jeffers, 26, of atlanta, fell while doing pullups from a fifth-floor balcony railing, authorities said. he was listed in guarded condition at humana hospital in fort walton beach
david mcgee, 18, of baton rouge, who fell three floors, was in stable condition at the same hospital
evelyn fine, executive director of the mid-florida research and business center of daytona beach community college, said some 500,000 students have come to daytona for spring break this year and 330,000 will have lodged in a hotel for an average stay of about five days
she predicted that each student spends an average of $375, not including transportation, for a direct-dollar impact of $123.7 million on the daytona beach economy
the incense vendor accepted a poor woman's coins and spooned tiny measures of powdered red sandalwood, honey-crystal myrrh and dried rosemary into scraps of paper
thirty cents,'' lamented miguel valencia, appraising the three dimes paid for the incense. ``this is the worst year ever.''
the tall, ebony-skinned man, who peddles crosses and other piety objects, said he has sold only a $1 portrait of jesus christ since midweek
holy week is usually the best time of year for valencia and the small business he runs from a rickety stand in front of the metropolitan cathedral. indeed, the easter holiday usually brings joy throughout this country where about 95 percent of 2.2 million people are roman catholic
but an economic and social crisis over the rule of military chief gen. manuel antonio noriega has cast a pall over this year's celebration
gen. noriega, under drug-trafficking charges in the united states, has moved to consolidate control despite increasing u.s. pressure on him to step down and leave the country
he closed banks a month ago to prevent a cash panic after washington froze panamanian assets in the united states. the government has failed to pay most of its 130,000 workers, and private employees have nowhere to cash their checks. the money crisis worsened nationwide hunger and unemployment
meanwhile, the u.s. government has been stepping up its military presence in panama, though administration officials say they don't intend to use force to oust the strongman they once backed. another 1,300 military personnel will arrive tuesday, bringing to nearly 12,000 the number of u.s. troops there
the administration says the troops are intended to protect u.s. bases and 45,000 americans living in panama
never have we panamanians lived a lent with such tension, division and increasing want in great sectors of the country,'' said a catholic church statement. ``the people suffer and await the feast of the resurrection, that it may signal some light of hope.''
few panamanians saw cause for optimism. the church said saturday that opposition leaders had accepted a church role as mediator in the country's travail. but the opposition continued to demand that noriega leave the country, something he has doggedly refused to do
many people in the streets expressed despair over unremitting price increases and hunger. fresh fish, a typical easter meal in years past, has risen beyond modest means in this isthmus between the atlantic and pacific oceans
many hunkered down in the capital of panama city, forgoing customary visits with family in the provinces to protect diminishing savings. department of transportation agent roger chacon said outbound traffic through la chorrera, the main gate to the countryside, was extremely light all week
external calm replaced weeks of political activity and demonstrations in panama city. police replaced the heavily armed defense forces soldiers on the street friday for the first time since an unsuccessful march 16 coup attempt against noriega
five men conversed on 17th street downtown. two sat on a workshop bench carried out to the sidewalk and three others stood while all sipped a mixture of rum, milk and ice from paper cups
none of us would be here now if it weren't for the crisis,'' said a man in a sleeveless t-shirt and shorts. ``we'd be in chiriqui where it's cool.''
the mountainous western province is a favorite tourist spot in better times
so our recreation is conversation and a couple drinks,'' said another in a blue ``guayabera,'' the loose-fitting tropical shirt
inevitably, talk turned to the crisis. all five said they opposed noriega. one suggested that ``out of the 2 million panamanians, 200 support him.''
because of fear of reprisals, none wanted his name published
some of the men also talked bitterly of how u.s. sanctions were making their holiday and their lives difficult
panama has been a good friend to the united states for more than 80 years,'' said one. ``and it hurts more to be wounded by a friend.''
and all doubted that the population, stymied by government repression, could do much to change things after the holiday
the families of six california scuba divers arrested in indonesia nearly two weeks ago say they are still anxiously awaiting word on whether the men will be charged with crimes for allegedly entering restricted waters
indonesian authorities suspect the six were seeking valuables from a dutch ship that sank more than 200 years ago, according to ruth van heuven, a spokeswoman for the u.s. bureau of consular affairs in washington, d.c
our lives are at a standstill. we all live hooked to our phones,'' said jennifer craft, wife of one of the men taken into custody march 22 when indonesian authorities boarded the boat they chartered in singapore
in addition to the six californians, three australians, a briton and an iranian were also aboard the budi indah, according to julie meldrum, an australian embassy spokeswoman
the divers are being held until the investigation is completed
sophisticated sonar equipment found on the boat added to authorities' suspicion about the group, ms. van heuven said
joseph yun, an american vice-consul in the north sumatra capital of medan, said the detained americans contended they were in international waters
as of yet there have been no formal charges filed against the divers,'' ms. van heuven said in an interview last week
they are in good condition and have no complaints about maltreatment,'' said james alleckson brown, a u.s. embassy spokesman in jakarta
mrs. craft said indonesian officials have told her the country does not hold a person for more than 20 days without bringing formal charges
u.s. and australian embassy officials said last week they were still trying to establish the facts surrounding the incident. indonesian officials in the department of communications, the foreign office and the navy would not make any comment
one of the six, cliff craft, 43, a building inspector from whittier, faces misdemeanor charges in california in the pillaging of an underwater wreck off channel islands national park, said allan gordon, a ventura county deputy district attorney
debi commerford of orange, the wife of another diver, said none of the six in indonesia was looking for treasure. she said her husband, danny, and craft were there to start a building inspection business in singapore and to dive with the others for recreation
the others from california have been identified as patrick gibson, 47, a systems analyst from van nuys; jim vorus of santa monica, and bob and bruce lanhan of pleasant hill. owners'</head>
the national rifle association is trying to get this city's interim police chief ousted, saying he unfairly charged a service station owner with illegal possession of a handgun after a robbery
in a letter mailed to nra members here friday, one of the organization's national directors asks for help in keeping keith bergstrom ``from bringing his campaign against law-abiding gun owners to tarpon springs.''
the letter told members they should to voice their opposition tuesday when city commissioners meet to consider permanently appointing bergstrom as chief
in question is bergstrom's enforcement of an anti-gun ordinance while he was police chief in oak park, ill. an april 1984 measure banned possession of a handgun within the city limits
i find it very ironic that the nra in effect is criticizing me for obeying the law and being accountable to the people who make the law,'' bergstrom said friday
oak park police charged service station owner don bennett with violating the ordinance when, following a robbery at his station in 1986, he chased the suspects and fired at them with a .45-caliber pistol, bergstrom said
bennett ultimately was acquitted
the police department and their attorneys spent all of their efforts in prosecuting don bennett and there was never an attempt to find the robbers,'' said theodore a. lattanzio, the washington-based nra official who wrote the letter. ``they were trying to prosecute a man who tried to use a weapon in self-defense.''
bergstrom, who came to tarpon springs in october 1987, denied the nra accusations
bennett has filed a federal lawsuit naming bergstrom, two oak park police officers and another city official and seeking more than $2 million in compensatory damages and $1 million in punitive damages from each defendant
the lawsuit alleges the defendants were part of a conspiracy to prevent him from doing business, bennett said friday
a 60-year-old easter tradition _ a sidewalk display of live easter bunnies _ may bow to protests and be gone next year, the florist who sets it up said saturday
it will be determined by the public. if they want us to have the rabbits next year, we suggest that they write in to us,'' said arthur scheinuk, owner of scheinuk the florist
he said he wanted tangible support for the display, not just comments from people who walk into the store
just to come here and say, `i was here as a young kid and now i'm bringing my grandchildren,' without bringing some moral support _ you ... get a little disgusted.''
the fenced-in display, in which dozens of adult and baby rabbits hop around a lawn or snuggle in wooden boxes cut to resemble buildings along st. charles ave., opens 10 days before easter and lasts until easter sunday
scheinuk said thousands of adults and children come to look at the rabbits every year. some buy them for $10.90 each _ a price at which scheinuk said he makes no profit
for the past several years, the display also has attracted pickets, people who say selling live rabbits for easter gifts amounts to animal cruelty because the bunnies all too often wind up at animal shelters
we suggested to them they would do beter telling unwed mothers how to take care of their children,'' scheinuk said
to add injury to insult, 15 rabbits were stolen late thursday or early friday by someone who cut an 8-inch-square hole in the chain-link cage
in this weather that we've had, these flooded conditions, police have too much to do than to fool with rabbit stealers,'' he said
defendants in white robes waited in cages in a makeshift courtroom as the trial began saturday for the 33 moslem fundamentalists accused of using terror to disrupt the government
prosecutors are seeking the death penalty for 15 defendants, two of whom remain at large, for allegedly trying to kill two former government ministers and a magazine editor
they are seeking penalties for the others of up to life in prison
the defendants pleaded innocent and said they were tortured and abused by state security policemen and prosecutors during questioning. the prosecution denied the allegations
the 15 facing possible death sentences are charged with forming an illegal organization called ``salvation from hell'' with the intent of destabilizing the government through assassinations and other attacks
they are charged with the attempted murders last year of former interior ministers hassan abu basha on may 6 and el-nabawi ismail on aug. 13, and magazine editor makram mohammed ahmed on june 4
abu basha was wounded seriously, ahmed sustained a minor hand wound and ismail was not injured
all of the defendants are accused of illegally possessing firearms, explosives and pamphlets that contained information designed to incite anti-government violence
security was strong outside the courtroom, with at least four armored personnel carriers and scores of armed soldiers present. the 4{-hour session before chief judge omar el-oteify of the supreme state security court and two fellow judges dealt mainly with procedural matters
the 31 defendants in custody sat or stood in three cages in the courtroom, a renovated exhibition hall
white banners hanging on the cages' iron bars proclaimed ``the moslems are coming'' and ``prison and execution won't move us away from islam.'' the defendants chanted similar slogans
attorney abdel-halim mandour, speaking for the group of 47 defense lawyers, told the court that police fabricated evidence against the defendants
there is no illegal organization. this is a fabrication from the state security,'' mandour said. ``it is an attempt by these people to strike against islam and religious men.''
a developer who is buying a marine laboratory in the florida keys from harcourt brace jovanovich inc. says he plans to build a resort but also hopes to preserve the research facility
henk mastenbroek, who has developed several time-share vacation properties in the keys, agreed to pay $700,000 for the 7{-acre sea world marine science and conservation center, the only operating facility of its kind in the country. an official at the florida institute of oceanography said the marine laboratory was unique because of its access to tropical waters
the lab is being sold by the book publishing company harcourt brace jovanovich inc., which has been under pressure to sell real estate and other assets to repay creditors after fending off a hostile takeover bid last year. the marine lab was used to collect sharks and tropical fish for hbj's sea world theme parks
the company had agreed to sell the laboratory to the florida institute of oceanography, an arm of the state university system, but the deal fell through when the hbj realized there was no guarantee that the legislature would allocate money for the purchase, said jim harris, senior vice president of hbj land co
mastenbroek agreed to pay the same price the state would have paid. he said although he planned to build a resort on the site, he hoped he could maintain the lab, built in 1978, the orlando sentinel reported in saturday's editions
an administrator at the institute of oceanography said she doubted that the marine laboratory would remain intact
our problem is they (the developers) keep saying they have to make money out of it, which isn't too likely,'' sandra vargo, a project coordinator at the institute. ``i've seen too many research facilities and they're not money makers.''
three years ago, the institute contracted with hbj to use the marine center for its own research. about 400 community college and university students visit the center every year for a week-long course on marine biology
currently, the department of natural resources is growing 10,000 conchs there to determine whether they can be grown to reseed depleted conch beds. state and university researchers also are studying the lobster population to determine whether the creature has been overfished and needs protection
