democratic presidential hopefuls michael dukakis and jesse jackson campaigned saturday for momentum and paul simon fought for survival in this week's wisconsin primary, as the state reclaimed its historic role as a decisive crossroad on the long nomination trail
dukakis and jackson are locked in a close wisconsin contest whose outcome could label one the front-runner in the 1988 race
both men were in wisconsin and colorado on saturday, preparing for colorado's precinct caucuses monday that will set the stage for the wisconsin balloting tuesday
dukakis, delivering a major foreign policy speech saturday at the university of wisconsin at oshkosh, offered strong support for israel while blaming arab leaders for the failure to achieve peace in the middle east
at a news conference later, dukakis said he disagreed with jackson's embrace of plo leader yasser arafat and his position that israel and the palestinians are moral equivalents
jackson, who was campaigning near greeley, colo., kept his attack on the reagan administration, which he said has ``the most indictments, the most corruption, the highest sleaze factor in the history of american government. we deserve better government _ we deserve honorable leaders.''
in wisconsin, both candidates have laid down a clear appeal to the blue-collar workers who are critical to democratic success in the state
i have argued your case. i've stood with you and with the working people of america,'' jackson told a crowd at st. norbert college near green bay late friday. ``and now i want you to stand with me.''
dukakis turned his fire on the coporations
if we're serious about winning the battle for our economic future, we've got to get control of the merger and acquisition binge that's ... leaving the average working men and women of america holding the bag,'' he said in racine
the two other democrats _ sens. simon of illinois and albert gore jr. of tennessee _ ignored colorado in favor of wisconsin
the latest poll, published sunday in the milwaukee journal, showed dukakis with a 43 percent to 35 percent lead over jackson among voters who said they would vote for, or leaned toward, a democratic candidate. gore received 15 percent and simon was fourth with 5 percent. the poll, conducted last wednesday and thursday among 845 likely voters, has a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage points
this is the most important primary vote we have had since 1960 because of the closeness of the race.'' said suellen albrecht, chairwoman of the wisconsin democrats. ``this is our moment in the sun.''
simon put the rest of his chips on wisconsin, playing for an upset that would keep his hopes alive. the polls suggested his effort could end next week
not since 1960 has wisconsin had a chance to say in such concrete terms: we want a basic change,'' simon told a crowd in madison last week
in 1960, then-sen. john kennedy upset sen. hubert humphrey in the wisconsin primary and took a big step toward the white house
gore is making a major effort in the state with hard campaigning and a big investment in television ads. a surpising showing in wisconsin could be a big boost for what gore has set as his pivotal contest two weeks hence, in the new york primary
the republican primary in wisconsin is drawing little attention since sen. bob dole dropped his bid last week, leaving the nomination wrapped up for vice president george bush. there are 47 gop delegates at stake
the lack of a republican race adds uncertainty for the democrats, since the wisconsin open primary law allows gop faithful to vote in the still-disputed democratic race
i'd welcome any republican into the democratic party who wants to vote for any candidate we have, if the vote is given sincerely,'' ms. albrecht said. ``this is the very nightmare that we had with the national party four years ago,''
while academic experts say crossover voters have never made the difference between winning and losing, democrats were upset when republican gov. tommy thompson said last week he would vote for jackson if he were a democrat. thompson later said he was not trying to encourage crossover voting
in the delegate race, dukakis held a narrow margin _ 653.55 to 646.55 for jackson. gore held 381.8 votes and simon 169.5. a total of 468.6 votes are uncommitted. at the july convention, 2,082 votes are needed to win the nomination
jackson got a three-delegate boost saturday wehn he swept the party caucuses in the u.s. virgin islands. party vice chairman st. claire williams said jackson got 634 votes while dukakis trailed with only 37 votes. they were the only two candidates on the caucus ballot
six people, who each will cast one-half vote as delegates to the democratic national convention, were chosen in saturday's caucuses in the u.s. territory
the wisconsin primary offers 88 democratic delegates, but that is not the big prize. the winner in wisconsin has the chance to start momentum for a five-week stretch of big-state primaries that could decide the nomination
dukakis is looking for a big-state win to get his campaign back on track after jackson derailed it with a win on march 26 in the michigan precinct caucuses
the massachusetts governor has started to retool his campaign style, unveiling a new speech in milwaukee thursday night. dukakis, sometimes called a cold technocrat, admitted that he will never be the ``great communicator'' in the mold of ronald reagan, but what he called a ``great builder.''
jackson is looking to keep on winning, particularly in a state where his base _ black democrats _ is so small. less than 4 percent of the state's population is black
but jackson has made a major effort to reach out to blue-collar workers and farmers _ and has drawn dramatically large and enthusiastic crowds in that effort
he's one of us, not a washington big-wig,'' said dave dittman from st. croix county as he attended a big farm rally for jackson in the northern dairy country
a poll published in this week's editions of u.s. news &amp; world report said that if jackson became dukakis' vice presidential running mate, the democrats could defeat the gop ticket, regardless of who became bush's running mate. a dukakis-jackson ticket was supported by 47 percent of the 1,004 people contacted last week by telephone for the poll, while a hypothetical gop ticket of bush and illinois gov. jim thompson would win 42 percent
the poll, conducted by the roper organization, has a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points. ams</note>
flickering lights from thousands of candles illuminated st. peter's basilica late saturday as pope john paul ii followed a procession of cardinals and bishops in ceremonies to usher in easter
a two-hour vigil on the eve of christianity's holiest day of the year culminated with a midnight mass celebrating the resurrection of jesus christ
thousands of people packed into the pews and aisles lit small candles as the silent procession moved through the cavernous church
the pope carried a long white candle as he walked to the main altar under the ``baldacchino,'' the baroque canopy designed by the 17th century sculptor and architect gian lorenzo bernini. the pontiff's candle was lit from a large easter candle in an act that symbolizes the light of christ
the ``lumen christi,'' or light of christ, was chanted three times as the pope reached the main altar. after the third time, the lights of the basilica suddenly came on
during this night of vigil we are baptized in the death of christ. we are buried together with him in death, so that we may walk in a new life, like christ,'' john paul said in his homily delivered in italian
after the homily, john paul baptized and confirmed 27 people from 11 countries. they youngest was a 7-year-old boy from india, asmathy cristofanilli, and the oldest was joana maria evora, 49, from cape verde
the only american in the group was sean lamb, 19, a baskeball player at the university of california at los angeles
via you i send my greeting to your respective countries: korea, germany, japan, india, indonesia, cape verde, italy, peru, the united states of america, hungary and vietnam,'' the pope told them
coming from different parts of the world you symbolize the universality of the church, the universality of redemption.''
in his homily, the pontiff said ``this night of vigil invites us to the greatest joy, the joy of the easter of christ.''
on sunday, during an open-air mass, the pope will give the traditional ``urbi and orbi'' greetings to the pilgrims in st. peter's square and television viewers around the world
that mass caps a week of easter activities. on friday evening, the pope carried a simple black wooden cross in a torchlit procession at the colosseum. tens of thousands watched the ``via crucis'' or way-of-the-cross, as the pope stopped at the 14 stations that symbolize christ's agonizing walk to his crucifixion
on thursday at the basilica of st. john the lateran, the pontiff washed the feet of 12 priests in a service recalling christ's last supper with the apostles
earlier saturday, workers prepared for the outdoor mass by adorning the stairs to st. peter's with thousands of flowers of a multitude of colors. they hung ruby-colored draperies from the columns around the entry to the basilica and from the papal balcony
hundreds of chairs were placed near the stairs and workers installed loudspeakers so the huge crowd expected sunday can hear the pope
a stress test showed the space shuttle's redesigned solid rocket boosters apparently can withstand the weight of the orbiter, launch pressures and then some, a nasa spokesman said saturday
the structural load test was another step in certifying the space shuttle for flight, said ed medal, a spokesman for the national aeronautics and space administration at its marshall space flight center
hydraulic systems were used to apply pressures to a shortened solid rocket booster. the test section was subjected to forces equaling 150 percent of those normally experienced during launch, he said
the booster rocket was not fired
detailed analysis of the load condition will be conducted ... over the next several weeks, but it appears the test was successsful in demonstrating the capability required with reserve for returning the shuttle to flight status,'' said medal
he said the test booster, with included a flared aft skirt like the two that support the shuttle's weight on the launch pad, failed at the predicted weld when subjected to excessive pressures during the friday night procedure
this test demonstrated a capability greater than that tested prior to the first shuttle launch,'' said medal
the shuttle fleet has been grounded since the jan. 28, 1986, explosion of challenger in which seven people died. investigators blamed the disaster on a failed solid rocket booster joint that allowed flames to burn into the vehicle's huge external fuel tank
nasa hopes to resume shuttle flights this summer
the mormon church on saturday reported a record increase in converts during 1987, and leaders warned members against ostracizing non-mormons in the church's utah stronghold
leaders also announced the appointment of two new members of the leadership hierarchy and named a new president to the church's organization for children
mormon missionaries baptized 227,284 new members last year, compared to 216,210 in 1986, according to the annual statistical report of the 6.5-million-member church
the membership report was delivered on the opening day of the 158th annual general conference of the church of jesus christ of latter-day saints
the two-day conference has drawn thousands of mormons from around the world to hear sermons from the church's hierarchy, including president ezra taft benson, 88, who is considered a prophet
robert e. sackley, 65, bow island, canada, and l. lionel kendrick, 56, greenville, n.c., were named new members of the seventy, full-time clergy who assist the governing first presidency in directing the church. sackley is currently president of the church's mission in nigeria, while kendrick is directing missionary efforts in the tampa, fla., area
michaelene packer grassli was named president of the children's program primary. she succeeds dwan j. young, who is leaving the position to accompany her husband, who has been appinted president of the calgary, canada, mission
the church's success in proselytizing has been accompanied by a sharp increase in its missionary force, which has grown to 34,750 men and women, compared to 31,803 during 1986
outside the church, many watch in amazement at this consistent expansion, in spite of popular secularism,'' said david b. haight of the council of the twelve apostles. the twelve are full-time clergy who assist the three-member first presidency in directing the church. the seventy follow the twelve in the hierarchy
but while leaders celebrated the growth, they warned members to avoid religious arrogance, particularly in utah, where non-members often complain that they are excluded from politics and social life
about two-thirds of utah's 1.6 million people are mormon, and church members hold nearly all major political offices. the governor and the congressional delegation are members. more than 80 percent of the legislature is mormon, including the senate president, house speaker, and the majority leaders in both chambers
numerical superiority does not justify disdain for those who are not mormon, said dallin h. oaks, a member of the twelve and former utah supreme court justice
he said he recently received a letter in which the writer complained that newcomers who are not mormon arrive in utah to find themselves ``excluded at best and ostracized at worst.''
that sentiment was demonstrated last week when sacramento, calif., developer john roberts turned down a job as chief of the privately run utah economic development corp., saying the state has an image of being inhospitable to non-mormons. ``i was asked what my religion was more in one afternoon in salt lake city than i have in my entire life,'' roberts said
j.d. ``dull'' stewart, self-proclaimed leader of international dull folks unlimited, crashed the seventh annual national humor conference saturday to panhandle for his mythical presidential candidacy
stewart, a statistical analyst from rochester, n.y., became the champion of dullards everywhere with the creation of densa, an organization whose name stands for nothing except as a send-up of the high-iq society, mensa
talking to a roomful of professors gathered at purdue university for a serious study of humor in american society, stewart made his money pitch: ``i said i'm in room 228 in the union club. you can just leave your $250 checks ouside the door. i haven't seen any yet.''
stewart is actually a registered participant and welcome, said don nilsen, an arizona state university professor
stewart's kind of self-deprecating humor won a nod of appreciation from the professors. ``it's funny because it's a reversal,'' said nilsen. ``it's an opposite of expectations. whatever our frustrations are, we have ways of dealing with those frustrations by using this kind of humor.''
it's more sophisticated than one-liner humor that commonly targets ethnic groups, politicians or sex, he said
it's a coping device,'' he said. ``you have to develop coping devices for the real problems of the world.''
another researcher, rhoda lee fisher of the state university of new york, said stewart's style has lot in common with many successful professional comedians. despite success and the admiration of the audience, genuine self-doubt remains, she explained
in fact, most comedians come across as being down and up at the same time,'' she said. ``they tell us they're silly, but we secretly know they are special and brave and doing something most of us would not have the fortitude to attempt.''
the four-day humor conference, attended by about 70 professors from a variety of disciplines, runs through monday. studies will be presented on humor and business management, the humor of intentional mispronunciation, and a paper titled, ``the continuing saga of arizona's governor: a humorous sequel.''
a 9-year-old california boy landed his father's twin-engine plane in this boston suburb saturday, becoming the youngest pilot to complete a transcontinental journey
tony aliengena of san juan capistrano touched down at 5:45 p.m. at hanscom air field to break the record set last august by 10-year-old christopher lee marshall of oceano, calif., officials said
i like to fly so i wanted to break it,'' the 4-foot-8 pilot said after he was greeted by his parents and friends, who gave him a trophy, an aviator's scarf and a glass of champagne
national aeronautics association observer don taylor, who accompanied tony, verified that the boy was at the controls throughout the transcontinental flight
i'm going to call washington on monday and tell them it's a go,'' taylor said
christopher flew a plane from san luis obispo county, calif., to fort lauderdale, fla., to burbank, calif., the longest trip by the youngest pilot. if tony succeeds in his plan to fly back to calfornia this week taking the long way home he says he will beat the distance record, too
tony, who is known as ``buzz,'' completed the longest leg of his four-day trip saturday after taking off from memphis. he had to land twice _ in bristol, tenn., and cambdridge, md. _ because of a stomach ache and was two and a half hours late in arriving. he spent five hours in the air saturday
when his father, gary, asked why he didn't stay on the ground if he felt sick, tony replied: ``i wanted to make it here.''
i'm very proud of him,'' said his father, who is from palmer
the trip began wednesday when tony took off in his father's twin-engine cessna from john wayne airport in costa mesa, calif. he plans to return to california next saturday, spending four to seven hours aloft each day except easter sunday, when he visits relatives in palmer
with him in the cockpit were taylor and his flight instructor, ed fernett
tony, who uses a booster seat to see over the control panel, is to fly to washington on monday to receive an award from the national aeronautics association for being the world's youngest pilot
the sunday times of london said there is a secret israeli operation under way to sell advanced missile technology to china
it said israel sent a five-man team of military specialists to china in november and a deal was made to supply the chinese armed forces with missile warheads and armor-piercing devices developed by israel
the newspaper identified one of the men it said traveled to china but did not give further attribution
it said there are indications israel has been helping china develop its own multipurpose combat fighter plane using technology derived from the canceled israeli lavi fighter. the united states had helped finance development of the lavi, and the program was dropped after washington complained about delays and rising costs
western intelligence agencies have suspected for some time that there is a link between israeli expertise and the speed china has shown in developing advanced weaponry,'' the sunday times said
according to the newspaper, the arms deal was supervised by reuven merhav, who it said is israel's consul general in hong kong and formerly worked for mossad, israel's secret service
israel and china do not have diplomatic relations
the sunday times said five men flew to the chinese capital of beijing using passports from the philippines. it identified one of the men as israel radomsky and said he was program manager of the state-owned israel military industries _ imi. radomsky ``reluctantly admitted that he and his team traveled to china,'' the report said, adding:
he also said that, far from being a rogue operation, the covert mission to china had been cleared at the highest levels of the israel government.''
the newspaper said the other four members of the delegation were all experts in imi's missile division
lawmaker anthony beaumont-dark of the governing conservative party said saturday night that britain should freeze all technology and information exchanges with israel until it explains the deal with china
he said foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe should tell israel the arrangement is ``totally unacceptable.''
we cannot go on sharing things with people who want to sell it to a potential adversary for mercenary reasons, or with people we cannot trust,'' beaumont-dark said
the sunday times said israel officially denies arms ties with china, but ``jane's defense weekly, the authoritative military affairs magazine, estimates the trade is already worth as much as three billion dollars.''
it claimed china wanted to keep its military links with israel secret ``for fear of harming its position in the middle east.''
israel sought secrecy because a missile deal with china would antagonize the united states, which has expressed concern about china's sale of silkworm missiles to iran, according to the sunday times. 5 grafs to update with campaign appearances in pueblo, aspen, spokeswoman comments on boom in contributions</note>
democrat jesse jackson condemned the reagan administration saturday for corruption and economic suffering, telling striking meat workers, ``reagan is on the way out and we're on the way in.''
jackson began two days of campaigning among colorado democrats who hold caucuses monday night to apportion 45 delegates. wisconsin's important primary follows on tuesday
jackson didn't refer to his democratic rivals, except for ex-candidate gary hart, the former colorado senator. ``since my friend gary is out, i am colorado's favorite son,'' he said
jackson spoke to about 1,000 workers outside the monfort portion foods meatpacking plant, where workers have been on strike for higher wages since nov. 16
jackson said there have been ``seven years of midnight'' under president reagan and vice president george bush. he referred to the easter season in encouraging strikers to continue to have hope
innocent people do suffer _ that's one of the lessons of easter,'' the black preacher and civil rights activist told the mostly white audience
but just because you're suffering, don't surrender,'' he said. ``in the end, faith will not disappoint. ..
they could not stop the government from killing jesus, but the government could not stop new hope, could not stop resurrection, could not stop renewal,'' he said. ``we cannot stop reaganomics, but reaganomics cannot stop us. ... reagan is on the way out and we're on the way in _ we, the people, are on the way in.''
jackson, who with his democratic rivals has called for the resignation of attorney general edwin meese iii, blasted the reagan administration for what he said was corruption and contempt
the iran-contra scam expresses contempt for the law. we must have a president who knows and respects the law, a president who sets the moral tone for our nation,'' he said. ``we have in this administration the most indictments, the most corruption, the highest sleaze factor in the history of american government. we deserve better government. we deserve honorable leaders.''
jackson received an enthusiastic response from about 2,000 people _ mainly white and hispanic _ who gathered later at an outdoor rally in pueblo. he then headed to the mountain resort of aspen _ which had 1{ feet of snow last week _ where he was attending a fund-raising event and speaking to a group of local residents and skiers
jackson's campaign said it had had its best success ever in raising money during the past month
campaign spokeswoman denise lee said the campaign raised $2.1 million during march, including $500,000 in the week since jackson's stunning victory in michigan's caucuses. she said that since super tuesday, the amount of money received by the campaign by mail has increased from about $20,000 a day to $60,000 a day
jackson planned to attend easter services in denver on sunday morning
in greeley, jackson repeated his common themes of attacking corporations for exporting jobs and exploiting cheaper foreign labor. he led the crowd in chanting that they would vote for jackson at caucuses around the state monday night _ meetings called ``get togethers'' rather than by their formal name, which he said was intimidating to average voters
he noted that they fall on april 4, the 20th anniversary of the assassination of martin luther king jr. in memphis, tenn., where jackson was present as a young aide to the civil rights leader
answering questions after his speech, jackson called efforts to require only english to be taught as the main language in schools a ``mean-spirited mistake.''
president alan garcia on saturday extended a state of emergency in an important mining region where leftist guerrillas have repeatedly attacked mines and railroads
a decree in the official gazette, el peruano, said the emergency measures would be extended for another two months across the mountainous eastern half of pasco state. cerro de pasco, the state capital, is 120 miles northeast of lima
pasco is the center of peru's vital mining industry that provides more than 50 percent of the nation's foreign exchange. maoist shining path guerrillas have made hundreds of attacks in the zone in an effort to cripple peru's economy
the government began decreeing states of emergency in november 1980 because of the insurgency. parts of seven states, including lima, currently are under states of emergency
a state of emergency suspends citizens' rights to travel and assemble freely and permits government forces to conduct searches without warrants and hold suspects for lengthy periods without filing charges
