a 9-year-old girl whose lower legs were amputated after she was found abandoned and freezing has a new foster family and should be leaving the hospital before long, officials say
darlwin carlisle, of gary, ind., has been learning to walk on artificial legs at la rabida children's hospital
the foster parents ``are known to darlwin and will begin discharge training next week,'' said hospital spokeswoman kris bangert
the girl has been at la rabida since the end of january after her frostbitten legs were amputated below the knee. she had been abandoned in an empty, unheated house in gary, and was found jan. 17. gangrene brought on the need for the amputations, doctors say
her mother, darlwin britt, 24, was charged with felony child neglect
the girl's foster parents were appointed by the child and protective services of indiana. their identities were not released
the ``hospital has been her family since the end of january,'' said ms. bangert
but it's still a hospital, not a real home,'' she said
darlwin has made steady progress in her recovery, the spokeswoman said
she walks everywhere with no assistance,'' said ms. bangert. ``and she looks great when she walks, too _ not wobbly or halting.''
the party of former opposition leader joshua nkomo voted saturday to merge with the ruling party of prime minister robert mugabe in a step to unite the nation's most powerful political movements
nkomo, president of the zimbabwe african people's union, opened the party's one-day congress with a plea to more than 5,000 delegates to endorse a unity accord he signed with mugabe on dec. 23
nkomo said, ``this accord opens up broad vistas for the economy of the country through the participation of all the people in development.''
nkomo, 70, needed a simple majority vote to endorse the merger but the congress passed two resolutions by unanimous vote. the resolutions approved the merger and asked nkomo and mugabe to proceed with uniting their parties' structures under one banner, effectively dismantling nkomo's party
this country will owe a lot to your decisions,'' nkomo said after the vote. ``we have a collective vision. we must stand together. we must not deceive each other.''
mugabe's zimbabwe african national union is to vote on the unity accord on april 9
mugabe and nkomo originally were allies in the campaign to bring majority black rule to the country that was the white-ruled british colony of rhodesia
in 1963, mugabe and some other officials left nkomo's party to form their own leftist movement
both parties were outlawed by then-prime minister ian smith's white-dominated government in 1964. nkomo and mugabe, along with hundreds of other black nationalists, were detained for more than a decade
mugabe and nkomo then became leaders in a seven-year guerrilla war that ended when the country became independent on april 18, 1980. the alliance mugabe and nkomo had formed during the war came apart after mugabe's party won zimbabwe's first election after independence
nkomo and mugabe remained political foes until dec. 23, when they signed the unity accord that signaled an end to frequent fighting between their supporters. in january nkomo was appointed one of three senior cabinet ministers in a government shuffle
if both parties approve the merger, mugabe, 64, will have the support of all but one legislator in the 100-seat national assembly and the 40-member senate. he needs the vote of all 140 lawmakers to change the constitution and establish a one-party socialist state that he advocates
the dissident lawmaker is businessman goodson sithole, but political observers say he could join mugabe's party before a vote is taken in parliament later this year
in another development, a gang of men stabbed to death a white zimbabwean farmer at his home and beat his wife unconscious, police reported saturday
they said the body of johannes du toit, 55, was found by the family cook friday in the farmhouse near the town of karoi, 112 miles northwest of harare
police said they had not determined the motive, but neighbors who spoke on condition of anonymity said du toit recently had argued with some of his black employees
